<FIRST>r a AM-ColdFusion     12-12 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cold Fusion,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Some Evidence Backing Cold Fusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Evidence showing ``cold fusion'' may be a
real way to produce energy was presented Tuesday by Tennessee
scientists, prompting a senator to urge the government to
reconsider a recommendation against special funding for such
research.
   But a member of a U.S. Department of Energy advisory board that
recommended against such funding said the panel remains unconvinced
by the new findings.
   Gordon Michaels of Oak Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee
presented the new results here Tuesday to a meeting of the American
Society of Mechanical Engineers.
   Chuck Scott, a chemist and senior research fellow who leads the
lab's research team, said the experiments repeatedly found
unexplained excesses of energy released in the form of heat, and
also found inconsistent signs of neutrons and the chemical tritium,
which are products of fusion reactions.
   ``We feel very strongly we have observed excess energy,'' he
said. ``We feel confident in being able to measure the heat. It was
sufficiently above experimental noise that we know it's really
there.''
   Nuclear fusion is the process that powers the sun and hydrogen
bombs. Attempts to harness it as an unlimited source of energy
previously concentrated on simulating the extremely high
temperatures and pressures found in the sun.
   Chemist B. Stanley Pons of the University of Utah and a
colleague, Martin Fleischmann of England, announced in March they
had created a nuclear fusion reaction in a bottle of heavy water
using a palladium electrode wrapped in platinum wire. They ran
electricity through the two metals and reported that the device put
out more energy than they put into it.
   The potential to create vast amounts of power in a jar of water,
which could be cheap, easy and have relatively benign by-products,
sparked a furious series of attempts by scientists around the world
to reproduce the Pons-Fleischmann results.
   But many scientists soon became convinced that Pons and
Fleischmann were mistaken and that their research was sloppy.
   The new findings prompted U.S. Sen. Jake Garn, R-Utah, to urge
the Energy Department _ which oversees Oak Ridge National
Laboratory _ to reverse a recommendation against special funding
for cold fusion research. The recommendation was made by the
department's Energy Research Advisory Board.
   Advisory board co-chairman John R. Huizenga, a chemistry and
physics professor at the University of Rochester, N.Y., said the
panel remains unconvinced by the Oak Ridge experiments.
   He said the panel considered the findings in writing its report
and recommendations to Secretary of Energy James D. Watkins. The
panel, which issued the final report Friday, was sympathetic toward
restricted study within present funding limits.
   The Oak Ridge group has been doing tests since April. Scott said
excess energy was measured for several hours at a stretch, usually
on the order of 5 percent to 8 percent above what would be
considered normal. On one occasion excess heat of up to 50 percent
was measured for a period of 12 hours, he said.
   The Oak Ridge researchers also found what seemed to be excess
levels of neutrons and tritium, but not consistently. Asked what
the results mean, Scott replied: ``I don't know.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
