<FIRST>r a BC-Opera     12-12 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Opera,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Flying Dutchman Sails into Met after Long Absence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs separate planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE SILVERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legend has it that the Flying Dutchman was
condemned to roam the seas eternally, coming ashore just once every
seven years in search of redemption.
   His ordeal was nothing compared to that of Metropolitan Opera
audiences, who have had to wait more than a decade between
performances of Wagner's youthful masterpiece about the ghostly
sailor.
   The Met's reluctance was understandable. Its last attempt at
``The Flying Dutchman,'' by the late Jean-Pierre Ponnelle, was
nearly hooted off the stage at its 1979 premiere. That production,
which turned the action into the dream of a minor character, is now
frequently cited as a textbook case of how a composer's intention
can be distorted for the sake of operatic novelty.
   For its new staging, which premiered Monday night, the company
wisely called on a traditionalist, August Everding, the head of the
Bavarian State Opera who has successfully produced several other
operas here, including Wagner's ``Lohengrin.''
   Everding's ``Dutchman,'' with sets by Hans Schavernoch, costumes
by Lore Haas and lighting by Gil Wechsler, is impressive to look
at, from the forbidding rocks that line the Norwegian coast to the
ominous appearance of the Dutchman's ship and its sepulchral crew.
The Dutchman arrives on a mechanized gangplank that may be
anachronistic for the 18th century but is eerily effective. Less
apparent is why a Norwegian house of the period would have electric
lights, or why the spinning wheels Wagner calls for have been
replaced by sewing machines.
   No production of the opera will get very far unless the title
role is strongly cast, and here the Met was fortunate to have bass
James Morris. He began tentatively, failing to make the most of his
brooding opening soliloquy, but his resonant tones became
impressive in the Act Two love duet and thrilling in the closing
moments of the opera.
   As Senta, the maiden who is willing to die to bring the Dutchman
salvation, soprano Mechtild Gessendorf filled the house with
bright, silvery tones and threw herself into the role
enthusiastically. Vocally, she fell short only in her upper
register, which on occasion turned screechy.
   In supporting roles, bass Paul Plishka was a stalwart Daland,
Senta's pragmatic father, and tenor Gary Lakes was suitably
distraught as Erik, her jilted fiance. Tenor Robert Gambill, making
his debut as the Steersman, displayed a small but beautiful voice.
   Music director James Levine conducted the Met orchestra, which,
as usual these days, sounded superb.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
