<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--GatorAid     12-12 0157</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Gator Aid,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baby Alligator Rescued From Frozen Reservoir</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-foot-long alligator, freed from ice at a
reservoir, is resting comfortably in a box at an Indianapolis
couple's home.
   Dale Bertelson, an environmental consultant, and his wife,
Marilyn, aren't that comfortable about the arrangement.
   ``Hamsters and fish are one thing, but this is something else,''
said Bertelson.
   The alligator was found Saturday near Eagle Creek Reservoir dam
by children who saw its snout. It was revived the next day after
the Bertelsons broke the ice and pulled it free.
   ``As soon as we got it out of the hole the thing started moving
its feet around. We carried it back in a box. And there we are,''
Bertelson said.
   The Bertelsons hope to find animal experts to take the alligator.
   ``I don't want to become a foster parent here. It's probably not
in my lease I can have one of these,'' Bertelson said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
