<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0231EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DefenseProbe     12-12 0662</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Probe,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Pentagon Contracting Official Testifies in Bribery Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Marine Corps contracting
official says he solicited more than $80,000 in bribes to steer
business to a defense firm and stashed some of the proceeds at home
in his freezer.
   ``I put it in the freezer, in aluminum foil,'' Jack A. Sherman
testified Monday at the trial of two men accused of paying him
bribes.
   Sherman, a former civilian Marine Corps contracting official,
testified that he hid the cash in the freezer so his wife wouldn't
find it.
   ``I put it under the ice cubes ... It wasn't a large stack,''
Sherman told jurors.
   Sherman, who is serving 18 months following his guilty plea to
bribery charges, said the rest of the money was placed in a credit
union account.
   The former Pentagon official described how he negotiated with
Lee Telecommunications to receive the bribes. In return, Sherman
said he approved the contract and later increased its value to give
Lee more work at a time when it was struggling financially.
   His testimony came at the federal court trial of former Lee vice
president Leonard L. Ingram and Thomas Muldoon. The two are accused
of participating in a six-year bribery scheme that prosecutors said
funneled more than $80,000 to Sherman.
   Ingram's attorney, Marcus Topel, told jurors in his opening
statement that his client protested the bribe arrangements to
company vice president Scott Lamberth and was told ``to mind his
own business.''
   ``He is an innocent man who was in the wrong place at the wrong
time,'' Topel said.
   Two former Lee executives, including Lamberth, have pleaded
guilty to participating in the scheme along with a subsidiary of
the Whittaker Corp., which absorbed Lee in 1986.
   ``Was the money paid in cash or checks?'' asked prosecutor Jack
Hanley.
   ``It was always in cash,'' Sherman replied. ``In most cases I
was paid in the car, riding around the block.''
   He said he first began taking illegal gratuities in 1974 and
received his first bribe _ $800 _ in the late 1970s.
   Sherman said he discussed with Lamberth the possibility of
helping Lee get a contract in 1981.
   ``Mr. Lamberth said if the contract could be expedited, he would
be able to pay me $75,000. The money would be paid to a consultant
I knew, Tom Muldoon,'' Sherman said.
   Lamberth also promised a $10,000 bonus if the contract was
signed by a certain date, Sherman testified.
   Sherman said he and Muldoon originally agreed to evenly split
the money from Lee. But later, Muldoon complained that he needed a
larger share to pay taxes, so Sherman said he took only one-third.
   Sherman could not recall all the payments he received but
testified that he was paid about $25,000 from Muldoon. He also
arranged to be paid $800 a month by Lee through John Marlowe,
another defense consultant, from fall 1985 to mid-1987.
   Sherman said he couldn't recall doing anything specific for the
money. Those payments were made ``to keep me interested in looking
out for the best interests of the company,'' he said.
   Sherman said he later arranged to split 5 percent of the value
of a $1 million contract he steered to Lee with defense consultant
Donald Illeman, who also has pleaded guilty.
   While he usually dealt with Lamberth, who once paid him $4,800,
Sherman said he once discussed bribes with Ingram.
   Sherman said he called Ingram after Lee's estimate of the
contract's cost abruptly went from $1 million to $1.6 million.
   Sherman admitted to defense attorney Albert Ahern that even
after talking to the FBI when the investigation became public in
June 1988, he attempted to collect bribe money from Illeman.
   Sherman said Illeman still owed him $4,000.
   ``You were so greedy you wanted to get that money?'' Ahern said.
   ``Yes,'' Sherman said.
   ``You weren't full of contrition then?'' Ahern said.
   ``I was, but I made the call,'' Sherman said.
</TEXT>
