<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     12-12 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In Tokyo, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar moved slightly lower against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo Tuesday, while stock prices rose moderately.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues gained 50.86 points, or 0.13 percent, ending
trading at 37,803.53. The index had gained 28.61 points on Monday.
   The dollar closed at 144.47 yen, down 0.18 yen from Monday's
close of 144.65 yen. The U.S. currency opened at 144.41 yen and
ranged between 144.40 and 144.58 yen.
   After opening lower in Tokyo, the dollar moved narrowly as
market players were wary of central bank intervention, said a Bank
of Tokyo trader.
   The Bank of Japan sold dollars around 144.50 yen shortly after
Tokyo dealings opened, but the sale had no major impact on exchange
rate movements or the tone of trading, the trader said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
   Central bank intervention was not observed after the early move,
which made market players reluctant to buy more dollars, the trader
said.
   In the United States overnight, the Federal Reserve Board sold
dollars to stem the currency's rise against the yen.
   On the stock exchange, trading was active as market players
bought issues related to natural resources, including petroleum,
said Kazuyuki Suzuki, a Daiwa Securities dealer.
   ``Market players were getting reassured as the yen was at least
a bit stronger than it was yesterday,'' he said.
</TEXT>
