<HEAD>State Department: Continued Nicaraguan Violence Will Negate Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elections next February in Nicaragua will be
dismissed as illegitimate if violence against the country's
political opposition continues, according to a State Department
spokesman.
   Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government ``is at a
crossroads,'' spokesman Richard Boucher said Monday.
   His comments were triggered by a Sunday rally by the opposition
coalition UNO at Masatepe, 30 miles south of Managua, which turned
into a machete-slashing riot that left one dead and more than 20
injured. Foreign observers blamed Sandinista sympathizers for the
violence.
   The opposition, a coalition of more than a dozen parties, is
promoting publisher Violeta Chamorro as its candidate to replace
Sandinista leader Daniel Ortega as president in elections set for
Feb. 25.
   At the State Department, Boucher called it ``the latest in a
string of Sandinista-sponsored attacks on Nicaragua's internal
opposition'' since a cease-fire with the Contra rebels was lifted
Nov. 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Skinner: New Restrictions on Alcohol Advertising May Be Considered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transportation Secretary Samuel Skinner says
new restrictions on alcohol advertising may be necessary for the
ongoing effort to keep intoxicated drivers off the road.
   At a White House briefing Monday for 150 anti-drunken driving
activists, President Bush called drunken driving ``one of the most
deadly scourges'' of our times and signed legislation declaring
this National Drunk and Drugged Driving Awareness Week.
   Before Bush spoke, Skinner was asked why the government does not
raise excise taxes on alcohol to discourage drinking and does not
restrict brewers' and liquor manufacturers' ads.
   ``I'm not so sure it isn't time to revisit those issues'' of
regulating advertising, Skinner said. People are ``not going to
stop drinking,'' he said, but they must be stopped ``from getting
behind the steering wheel.''
   Health Secretary Louis Sullivan was more direct, telling the
briefing that the nation should ``consider some form of
restrictions on the advertising of alcoholic beverages.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Arts Institutions Receive $14 Million in Grants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Endowment for the Arts has
awarded $14 million in grants to institutions across the country in
an effort to generate more than $50 million in additional matching
funds.
   Four $1 million ``challenge grants'' were awarded Monday to
benefit Arena Stage in Washington, D.C., the San Francisco
Symphony, the Lyric Opera of Chicago and the Charlotte, N.C. Arts
and Science Council.
   Those four grants, which require $3 in private funds for every
federal dollar given, were the biggest of 37 endowment awards to
arts institutions across the country totaling $14,125,000.
   The federal grants are intended to generate more than $50
million in additional matching funds over the next three years to
support ``long-range projects of special artistic merit,'' the
endowment said.
