<FIRST>r a PM-ArceGomez Bjt   12-12 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arce Gomez, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Bolivian Ex-Minister Awaits Hearing in Miami</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto covering</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Bolivian interior minister who allegedly
hired Nazi war criminal Klaus Barbie to teach torture techniques to
death squads arrived here to face drug charges after being spirited
out of his country.
   Luis Arce Gomez, known as the ``minister of cocaine'' in Bolivia
after he allegedly created an elite paramilitary squad to
confiscate cocaine from drug dealers who refused to pay him bribes,
landed in Miami on Monday night on a U.S. Drug Enforcement plane,
said Justice Department spokesman Dan Eramian.
   Federal officials late Monday refused to comment about the
timing of his arraignment or any other details of his extradition.
The case was surrounded by tight security ordered from Washington,
said sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``The arrest of Arce Gomez sends a message that the president
will work with other governments to pursue vigorously individuals
who traffic in drugs,'' the White House said in a statement.
   Bolivian President Jaime Paz Zamora said Arce Gomez was expelled
even though the two countries have no formal extradition treaty
because the United States was the first country to bring charges
against him.
   Arce Gomez's whereabouts were unknown until his capture Sunday
at a ranch near Santa Cruz, 350 miles east of the capital La Paz.
Clad in soccer shorts, he offered no resistance when hundreds of
police officers converged on the ranch, where he was attending a
family party.
   ``We congratulate the government of Bolivia for the capture,''
said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, one of five U.S. senators in La Paz
on a one-day visit when Arce Gomez was put on the plane.
   He was to be held at the federal Metropolitan Correctional
Center south of Miami pending arraignment on a 1983
drug-trafficking indictment here, officials said.
   Arce Gomez, who had a reputation for personally torturing
political prisoners, became his nation's powerful minister of the
interior when he and Gen. Luis Garcia Mesa overthrew a civilian
government in 1980. The right-wing government allegedly was
financed by cocaine traffickers.
   Human rights groups say Arce Gomez directed Bolivian death
squads and hired Barbie to advise the country's paramilitary forces
how to torture. The forces murdered hundreds of journalists,
political and labor leaders and church officials, according to
human rights organziations.
   Barbie was later expelled to France, where he is serving a life
sentence for a conviction on crimes against humanity stemming from
his days as Gestapo chief in Lyon.
   Arce Gomez was removed as interior minister in 1981 under
pressure from the U.S. government. When Bolivia stripped him of his
citizenship in 1982, he fled to Argentina and was arrested under
the Miami indictment, but he was freed in December 1983 in the
final days of Argentina's military regime.
   The indictment accuses Arce Gomez, along with 18 other people
including his former top aide Rene Benitez, of running a drug
protection racket while he was interior minister. He is
specifically charged with two counts of conspiracy to import and
distribute cocaine to Florida. He faces a maximum of 30 years in
prison if convicted.
   DEA officials have said that Arce Gomez directed a multi-million
dollar cocaine trafficking empire, charging Bolivia's top five drug
traffickers $75,000 every two weeks in exchange for freedom to
export cocaine.
   Two of his lieutenants charged in the indictment once received
$1.5 million for cocaine that was confiscated by Bolivian
authorities and stored in bank vaults, according to the indictment.
   The indictment said Arce Gomez personally ordered it released.
   Also named in the indictment is Ana Rodriguez de Tamayo, 50, who
faces up to 30 years in prison and $50,000 in fines if convicted of
conspiracy to import, possess and distribute cocaine. She was
extradited from Colombia following Colombian President Virgilio
Barco's August crackdown against the cocaine cartels and remains
held without bond in Miami.
</TEXT>
