<FIRST>r a PM-US-Slovaks     12-12 0546</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Slovaks,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Immigrants' Descendents Plan High-Tech Aid to Homeland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Czechoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH KIRKPATRICK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIDDLETOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joseph J. Krajsa knows what's needed once
a non-communist government is installed in Czechoslovakia:
electronic equipment.
   ``Their biggest problem is communications. They need to
communicate with the rest of the world,'' said Krajsa, who with his
father, Joseph C. Krajsa, manages the communications arm of the
First Catholic Slovak Union of the United States and Canada.
   The union, known as Jednota, already has sent people to Europe
to arrange additional contacts and try to get issues of its weekly
newspaper into Czechoslovakia.
   The country _ one of those leading the way to Eastern Bloc
liberalization as its ruling Communist party gives up its monopoly
on power, is a union of two republics, one predominantly ethnic
Czech, the other Slovak.
   When the time is right, the 105,000-member American organization
may invest in the country to help start publishing enterprises and
send in up to 500,000 copies of its newspaper and Slovak history
and language books, the Krajsas said recently.
   ``They have no reference point,'' said the younger Krajsa, 42,
referring to the rigorous censorship and information blackout
imposed by the communist regime during the past 40 years.
   For example, one young worker at Jednota who recently emigrated
from Czechoslovakia didn't know who reformist party chief Alexander
Dubcek was until she arrived in this country. Dubcek was ousted
when his ``Prague Spring'' reforms were crushed by a Soviet-led
invasion in 1968.
   ``We're seeing what we can do and how we can help educate their
people as fast as we can,'' the son said, adding that Jednota has
the computerized publishing equipment to quickly print materials in
the Slovak language.
   He said the United States should send Czechoslovakia facsimile
machines, computers and other information-age equipment the rest of
the world takes for granted.
   In addition, university chairs in English should be established
at Slovakian universities. A Slovak chair at the University of
Pittsburgh was recently established and its first project was a new
text to teach Slovak, the son said.
   With obvious pride, he noted that the popular uprising that took
``10 years in Poland and 10 weeks in Germany took 10 days in
Czechoslovakia.''
   The country, formed out of the wreckage of the Austro-Hungarian
empire after World War I, was considered the most democratic in
eastern Europe until a portion of it was surrendered to Hitler in
1938 and fell entirely to the Nazis soon afterward. Communists
overwhelmed a post-World War II coalition government in 1948.
   ``They're used to seeking freedom,'' said the elder Krajsa, 72,
who has worked for Jednota for 30 years.
   The newspaper and commercial printing division are located in a
modern building and warehouse on a hillside outside Middletown. The
union's headquarters is in Independence, Ohio, near Cleveland,
where the union was founded in 1890 by the Rev. Stephen Furdek from
eight independent Slovak Catholic societies and lodges.
   The younger Krajsa manages Jednota Press, the commercial
printing division. The father is editor of the 38,000-circulation
newspaper.
   Seeing their homeland move to the verge of new freedom, while
gratifying, is not surprising, the Krajsas said.
   ``History shows that it happens,'' the elder Krajsa said.
   Adds the son: ``I feel very excited for them.''
</TEXT>
