<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0422EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RocketLaunch     12-12 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocket Launch,0289</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Navigation Satellite Orbits the Earth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $65 million navigation satellite
was rocketed into orbit, joining the Air Force's network of
spacecraft that guide bombers, warships, missiles and ground troops
with precision accuracy.
   The fifth of a series of Navstar spacecraft was boosted into
space Monday by a Delta 2 rocket. The satellite settled into an
orbit reaching 11,000 miles high.
   ``Everything appears to have gone very well with the flight,''
said Lt. Col. Ron Rand, the Air Force launch commentator.
   After about a month of checkout by ground stations, the new
Navstar will join the four earlier spacecraft in providing U.S. and
allied military units information that allows them to pinpoint
their locations within 50 feet anywhere on Earth in any weather.
   Planes, ships, submarines, tanks and field soldiers can tune in
on the network's positioning radio signals with receivers as small
as a hand-held telephone. In some places the signals can be
accurate within 10 feet.
   The 3,675-pound satellites also keep track of the speed of
military vehicles within a fraction of a mile per hour and tell
them the time, accurate to within a millionth of a second.
   Military users receive information from a coded channel.
Civilian users such as operators of boats and private aircraft also
have access to the system, but they monitor an open channel
providing less accurate information, to within 300 feet of their
position.
   Users must wait until one or more of the satellites is within
radio range, leaving occasional gaps in coverage. There will be no
interruption when the Air Force completes the 21-satellite network
by 1992. Launches are planned about once every two months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
