<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Crosby     12-12 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Crosby,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bing Crosby's Son Dies at 51, Death Called Likely Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lindsay Crosby, son of the late entertainer
Bing Crosby, was found dead in his suburban home in an apparent
suicide. He was 51.
   Crosby, whose body was found Monday afternoon, died after
apparently shooting himself in the head, authorities said.
   An autopsy was scheduled for today.
   A friend discovered the body on a bedroom floor in the home in
Calabasas; a small-caliber rifle was found nearby, said Los Angeles
County sheriff's Deputy Bill Linnemeyer.
   Lindsay Crosby was the youngest of four brothers born to Bing
and Dixie Lee Crosby. Dixie Lee, whose real name was Wilma Wyatt,
died of cancer in 1952.
   Bing Crosby died at 73 of a heart attack in 1977.
   Lindsay Crosby was married three times, to dancer Barbara
Frederickson, secretary Janey Schwartz and most recently to former
Miss Alaska Susan Marlin, and had four sons. He and Miss Marlin
separated in the late 1970s.
   Lindsay and brothers Gary, Phillip and Dennis once formed a
nightclub act, the Crosby Boys, that ran until 1959. Lindsay then
went to work reading scripts for his father.
   Lindsay took a tempered view of revelations in brother Gary's
1983 book, ``Going My Own Way,'' which portrayed Bing Crosby as a
stern disciplinarian, but he said he supported publication of
Gary's book.
   ``I never expected affection from my father so it didn't bother
me,'' he said in an interview.
</TEXT>
