<FIRST>r a PM-LostAtSea     12-12 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lost At Sea,0611</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coast Guard Rescuers Challenge Human Limitations and the Sea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The image that lingers is of flares _ five of them
were spotted during the Coast Guard's search for five lobstermen _
that came and went like shooting stars.
   The rescuers, who gave up their search after 11 days, are now
haunted by the reminder that out on the sea ``it's just you and the
will to live.''
   Each flare sighting raised hopes that turned to frustration as
hundreds of searchers scanned thousands of miles of ocean without
success. When the search for the Stonington, Conn.-based, Heidi
Marie was finally suspended Dec. 1, disappointment and questions
about the failed effort remained.
   ``It's not as easy as seeing a flare and then finding it,'' said
Coast Guard Lt. Christopher Stickney, one of the pilots who logged
hours in the air during the search.
   ``You turn the plane in that direction but you really have no
idea how far away it is,'' he said. ``You only see the flare
momentarily, almost like ... if you were in your car and saw
lightning in the distance.''
   With every passing hour, the odds against finding survivors grew
slimmer.
   ``You just feel this incredible pressure because you're trying
constantly to get caught up with the situation because the search
area grows larger and larger, the potential drift areas grow and
the information going into designing the mission grows,'' Stickney
said.
   During the height of the search, Stickney spent his on-duty
hours absorbed in mathematics and probabilities. He and his flight
crew focused solely on resisting the lull of mile after mile of
greenish-gray sea and preventing their vision from blurring before
an endless stretch of horizon.
   ``You're right on the edge and you just keep thinking `I've got
to stay alert, I've got to concentrate,' because the next time you
glance left you could spot a life raft,'' Stickney said.
   But sometimes the fates conspire against Coast Guard missions.
Turbulent air jostles planes or 20-foot seas and wind-whipped water
obscure the view. Sometimes, as was the case with the Heidi Marie,
what seems a hot trail suddenly turns cold.
   The search planes are equipped with high-tech radar, infrared
heat-detecting sensors and data marker buoys to track conditions at
sea. But mostly the rescuers rely on their eyes, pilots scanning
from the cockpit and observers peering through 3-foot windows.
   Their backs get sore and their eyes strain against
late-afternoon shadows and hours of staring into the glare of
clouds, then snow, then brilliant blue sky.
   Because the Heidi Marie's life raft was made of cloth, it was
undetectable on radar. Because it was so small, their field of
vision was limited to about a mile off either wing.
   The weight of constant risk also tires Coast Guard searchers.
   ``The only thing separating us, the searchers, from them, the
people in the raft, is a few hundred feet of water,'' Stickney
said. ``It could be us lost out there and it could be our wives
waiting for the phone to ring.''
   The five missing lobstermen's families are no longer waiting.
The days and nights of waiting are over.
   The rescuers now live with the imagined faces of unknown sailors.
   ``It isn't a pretty picture to think of what they were going
through,'' said Lt. Bennett Bonomi, a pilot who was among those
searching for the Heidi Marie. ``The sea is so big ... and you're
at the mercy of the elements. It's just you and the will to live.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0032 </DOCNO>
