<FIRST>r i PM-India-Kidnap     12-12 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Kidnap,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Site Chosen For Swap Of Top Minister's Kidnapped Daughter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARUN JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAMMU, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Negotiators have picked an isolated site to
trade the kidnapp;ed daughter of a senior Cabinet minister for
jailed Moslem militants, a top state official said today.
   Disagreements over the site of the exchange had stalled the
exchange and an end to the kidnapping, the first crisis for the
10-day-old government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh.
   Chief Secretary Moosa Raza, the top-ranking bureaucrat in
Jammu-Kashmir state, said negotiators for the government and the
militant Kashmir Liberation Front at midday finally resolved
differences and agreed to an isolated site.
   He declined to give specifics, but said the exchange could take
place at ``any moment.''
   Militants have demanded freedom for five to eight militants
being held in prisons in exchange for Rubaiya Sayeed, the
22-year-old daughter of Home Minister Mufti Homahhad Sayeed.
   Ms. Sayeed, a medical intern, was abducted at gunpoint on Friday
in Srinagar, the summer capital of Jammu-Kashmir state. Srinagar is
about 95 miles north of Jammu, the state's winter capital.
   The front was formed in 1965 and is demanding that
Jammu-Kashmir, the only Indian state with a Moslem majority, either
become independent or part of neighboring Pakistan, an Islamic
nation.
   As negotiations continued, the government moved three of the
militants from a Jammu jail to Srinagar.
   The Kashmir Liberation Front is demanding the release of Abdul
Hamid Sheikh, the group's top leader who was arrested last month
after being wounded in a clash with police. He is in a Srinagar
hospital.
   But Sheikh asked relatives to tell the government he did not
want to be part of any deal, police sources said. Sheikh said the
government, once certain Ms. Sayeed was safe, would only arrest him
again, the sources said.
   The other militants are Noor Mohammed Kalwal, Mohammed Altaf,
Javed Ahmed Zargar, Sher Mohammed Azad and Ghulam Nabi Butt. The
name of the seventh militant was not immediately known.
   All have been arrested during the past year and are suspected of
subversive and secessionist activities, although none have been
charged.
   Ms. Sayeed's abduction occurred three days after her father was
appointed home minister, a key post that oversees the country's
internal security.
   He is the first Moslem to hold the job. The appointment was seen
as a part of Prime Minister V.P. Singh's efforts to appease Moslems
who have borne the brunt of Hindu-Moslem religious riots this fall.
   The kidnapping came a day after Sayeed was appointed the head of
a government committee set up to try to end separatist campaigns in
Jammu-Kashmir and neighboring Punjab, where Sikh militants are
demanding an independent nation.
   Moslems make up 64 percent of the state but nationwide comprise
only 11 percent of the population. Hindus comprise 80 percent of
India's 880 million people.
   Kashmir is claimed both by India and Pakistan, and the two
countries have fought three wars over the territory since they
gained independence from Britain in 1947.
</TEXT>
