<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--MultipleTransplant     12-12 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Multiple Transplant,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Heart-Liver-Kidney Recipient Back on Ventilator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who underwent the world's first
heart-liver-kidney transplant was placed back on a ventilator after
developing inflammation of her pancreas.
   Cindy Martin, 26, of Archbald, remained in critical condition
early today at Presbyterian-University Hospital.
   Her condition had been listed as serious during the weekend,
before the inflammation developed.
   The pancreas is a gland that secretes a digestive juice into the
small intestine. Doctors believe the inflammation is related to the
Dec. 3 transplant operation, hospital spokeswoman Lisa Rossi said.
   Doctors said Mrs. Martin's transplanted organs were functioning
well, however.
   ``It is a temporary setback, but it seems to be getting
better,'' Ms. Rossi said. ``There is concern another infection
might develop.''
   Mrs. Martin had undergone a heart transplant in 1985, but
suffered chronic rejection and eventually developed hepatitis and
kidney dysfunction.
   She suffered from an inherited heart disease.
