<HEAD>Man Pleads Innocent to Threatening Johnny Carson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man authorities say stalked Johnny
Carson for two years pleaded innocent to charges of sending tapes
and letters threatening to kill the talk show host unless he paid
him $5 million.
   Ken Orville Gause of Milwaukee entered the plea Monday in
Municipal Court to one felony count each of making terrorist
threats and sending threatening letters. He was held in lieu of
$250,000 bail pending a preliminary hearing Thursday.
   Gause, 36, was arrested Dec. 5 in the lobby of KNBC-TV studios
two hours before the taping of ``The Tonight Show.'' Authorities
said he was carrying a sock filled with gravel but never got close
enough to Carson to hurt him.
   Gause had threatened Carson in letters and tape recordings for
the past two years and had the celebrity's address in his
possession when he was taken into custody, authorities said.
   He could be sentenced to seven years in prison if convicted on
both counts.
