<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0555EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r e BC-Theater 1stLd-Writethru a0758 12-12 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0758,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>`City of Angels,' a New Musical, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with other critics' reviews; no PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spotlight searches the big city skyline as a
high-powered jazz prelude, including some fine scat singing, fills
the theater. Then gun shots and sirens. Finally, the tough-guy
monotone of a private detective right out of Raymond Chandler or
Dashiell Hammett is heard.
   It's the opening of ``City of Angels,'' the hard-boiled, private
eye musical that barreled into Broadway's Virginia Theater on
Monday night. It's an ambitious show, even an innovative one, from
creators Cy Coleman, Larry Gelbart and David Zippel.
   That's not to say ``City of Angels'' is perfect. The evening
runs on too long, and the main character needs more definition _
and a little more heart. But you won't find a more original musical
on Broadway.
   The place is Los Angeles, the time the late 1940s. A
disillusioned Hollywood screenwriter named Stine would rather write
mystery novels about a fictional gumshoe named Stone than toil as a
hack for an unscrupulous movie producer. But he needs the money.
After all, Stine says, didn't Fitzgerald and Faulkner work in the
movies?
   But then, did their creations sing and dance? ``City of Angels''
brings Stine's fictional detective to life. The audience sees both
Stine's real life and the world he is forced to create for the
silver screen.
   Stine, played with nerdish charm by Gregg Edelman, has a
soulmate in Stone. James Naughton gives the show's best performance
as the rakish detective. ``You're nothing without me,'' the two men
sing together in one of the musical's more persistent melodies, and
the show confirms their dependence on each other.
   Gelbart has concocted an ingenious, often very funny book. It's
a split-level story that satirizes the world of Hollywood film
making as well as the heros and convoluted plots of detective
fiction.
   All the other major performers play two roles. Stine's
long-suffering wife (Kay McClelland) resembles a torch singer the
detective Stone desires. Stone's Gal Friday (Randy Graff) is
similiar to the woman who works for that big time movie producer
(Rene Auberjonois). The producer, in turn, also appears in even
more grotesque form as a character in Stine's movie script.
   Auberjonois gets most of Gelbart's best zingers as the
egomaniacal producer who wants to rewrite Stine's script, while
Graff and McClelland suffer beautifully in song.
   ``City of Angels'' is Coleman's most tightly constructed score,
a big improvement over his much more conventional melodies for last
season's flop ``Welcome to the Club.''
   The numbers, lushly orchestrated by Billy Byers, suggest the
1940s, from big ballad crooning like ``Stay With Me'' to a torch
number like ``With Every Breath I Take,'' to an old-fashioned
musical comedy song like ``You Can Always Count on Me.''
   Zippel's lyrics evoke the same period, lushly romantic in the
ballads and sharp and sassy in the comedy songs.
   Director Michael Blakemore and his production team _ set
designer Robin Wagner, costume designer Florence Klotz and lighting
designer Paul Gallo _ have separated the worlds ingeniously.
Stone's film world is black and white; Stine's real world is in
living color. And occasionally they collide, most effectively at
the end of the show on an impressive soundstage where reality and
fantasy merge. It's then that Stine the author decides to say
``no'' to what Hollywood is doing to Stone the detective.
   Like its hero, ``City of Angels'' takes a chance. From Coleman's
scintillating, thematically linked score to Gelbart's ingenious,
multi-layered story, the show doesn't play safe. And that's more
than you can say for most of the musicals in town.
   In other reviews:
   The New York Times' Frank Rich wondered: ``How long has it been
since a musical was brought to a halt by riotous jokes?'' He
praised Gelbart for his ``endlessly witty wordplay'' and composer
Coleman for ``a delirious celebration of jazz and pop styles.''
   The New York Post's Clive Barnes praised the cast as good and
said the play had ``taste, resonance and imagination.'' But, ``The
one thing it doesn't completely do is work. ... What we have here
are a bunch of ideas searching for fulfillment,'' he wrote.
   The Daily News' Howard Kissel said he ``didn't have a good
time'' at the ``contrived parody.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0557EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Marcos-Murders     12-12 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marcos-Murders,0456</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official Testifies Marcos Agents Would Have Tracked Victims</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Filipino dissidents slain in a Seattle union
hall would likely have been targets for monitoring or harrassment
by agents of former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos, a
Philippine congressman testified.
   Witness Bonifacio Gillego, who worked 20 years in Philippine
intelligence before retiring in 1960, testified Monday in a
wrongful-death lawsuit by the survivors of Silme Domingo and Gene
Viernes. The men, opponents of Marcos' regime, were shot to death
in offices of the Alaska Cannery Workers Union in June 1981.
   Three men were convicted of murder on the theory that Domingo
and Viernes were victims of an internal union dispute involving
work assignments and gambling in Alaska fish canneries.
   But the U.S. District Court lawsuit, which seeks $30 million,
accuses the late Philippine president, his widow, Imelda, and
others of orchestrating the deaths because of Domingo's and
Viernes' anti-Marcos activism.
   Gillego testified that the two men would have been tracked by
Marcos' intelligence agents in the United States.
   He said that generally, those agents' tactics ranged from
``gentle persuasion to ... action that would even include extreme
measures.''
   Asked if that included executions or ``disappearances'' of
anti-Marcos activists, Gillego replied, ``That is correct.''
   Gillego had been part of the anti-Marcos opposition keeping
track of Philippines intelligence activities, and lived underground
in the Philippines and in exile in the United States after Marcos
declared martial law in 1972.
   After Marcos was overthrown, he was named executive director of
President Corazon Aquino's Overseas Philippine Presidential
Commission on Good Government, which was charged with recovering
Marcos' wealth in the United States.
   Marcos attorney Richard Hibey objected to much of Gillego's
testimony as hearsay, since Gillego lacks personal knowledge about
the particular case. But Judge Barbara Rothstein allowed most
answers, as long as they were labeled as Gillego's expert opinion.
   Gillego testified about several documents seized from Philippine
government files after Marcos' overthrow in February 1986. He
described them as typical of the kind of intelligence reports
prepared by Philippine consulates in the United States and sent to
Manila.
   Domingo's name appeared in several documents, Gillego testified,
including one identifying him as Washington coordinator of the
anti-Marcos Union of Democratic Filipinos, Gillego said.
   Domingo's and Viernes' union was a local of the International
Longshoremen's and Warehousemen's Union, which Gillego described as
a ``prime target'' of Marcos intelligence because its members had
been known to refuse to load or unload commodities from countries
whose politics they opposed.
   Their elections as union officers ``would be an important event
... that would be easily reported'' by Philippine intelligence
agents, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Peru     12-12 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Peru,0446</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shining Path Kills 49 Peasants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maoist Shining Path rebels raided five Andean
villages and massacred 49 peasants, including 30 in one village
where the rebels herded people into the town square before opening
fire, police said.
   The attacks in Ayacucho province Sunday night and Monday where
among the Shining Path's deadliest since it launched its insurgency
in 1980. The raids came after the government _ for the first time _
supplied firearms to peasants to defend themselves.
   In Lima, a military court on Monday found two police officers
guilty of murder in the killings of up to 70 Shining Path inmates
after a prison riot was crushed by security forces in June 1986. It
cleared 76 other defendants.
   The court ruled that 60 to 70 of the 124 guerrilla prisoners
killed during rioting at the Lurigancho penitentiary in June 1986
were shot to death after they surrendered.
   A panel of three generals convicted police Col. Rolando Cabezas
and Lt. Javier Marquina. Cabezas was sentenced to 15 years in
prison and Marquina to seven years.
   Defense lawyers had argued that 76 other officers and troops
acted on orders of their superiors when they shot the prisoners.
   Early Monday, a rebel column of about 100 guerrillas attacked
four villages in the highlands around Ayacucho, 240 miles south of
Lima, and killed 38 peasants, police said. Another Shining Path
group of about 50 guerrillas killed 11 men in a raid on a town
Sunday night, police said.
   They gave this account:
   The bloodiest attack was on Paccha, a village 35 miles south of
Ayacucho. The raiders ordered most of the 800 residents into the
town square, read a ``blacklist'' of names and then killed 30
people, including several women.
   Shortly before, the rebels killed eight people in nearby
villages.
   The second rebel group attacked Vicus, a village 50 miles
northeast of Ayacucho, killed 11 men and burned down 15 houses.
   Among those kiled in Vicus was the leader of a recently
organized civil defense force, police said. The Shining Path
considers members of peasant defense forces traitors.
   On Friday, President Alan Garcia went to Ayacucho to present 200
shotguns to a civil defense organization in Rinconada Baja, a
village 25 miles from Vicus. It was the first time the government
has supplied firearms to peasant patrols, most of which are armed
with lances and machetes.
   The army has encouraged villagers to form civil defense groups,
but has been opposed to providing the volunteers with guns, fearing
the weapons would fall into the hands of the guerrillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
