<FIRST>r i PM-Bulgaria-Accident     12-12 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bulgaria-Accident,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>15 Killed, 100 Injured In Train Derailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fast-moving passenger train derailed
rounding a curve in eastern Bulgaria today, killing at least 15
people and injuring 100, state radio reported.
   The radio said the high speed could have been the cause of the
accident but said work was being done on the tracks and warning
signals had been set up near the accident site.
   It said the train, en route from Sofia to the port city of
Varna, was traveling at 60 mph when it headed into the curve near
the town of Romen, about 100 miles east of Sofia. The engine and
three passenger cars derailed.
   The report came only hours after the accident happened, in a
marked change from previous reporting when at least one day passed
before state media reported on such accidents.
   It said a commission had been set up to investigate the
accident. The report gave no further details.
</TEXT>
