<FIRST>r a PM-Tartikoff-NBC     12-12 0319</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tartikoff-NBC,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>NBC Will Have Special News Report With Drug Miniseries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NBC will air a special news report on the
1985 slaying of a U.S. drug agent following the first installment
of a miniseries on the case.
   Tom Brokaw will be host of the news special Jan. 7.
   ``There's no more important subject in America today than the
war on drugs,'' NBC Entertainment president Brandon Tartikoff told
NBC affiliate stations Monday. ``I think this miniseries will focus
that nation's attention on it. It will make an important
statement.''
   ``Drug Wars,'' a three-part, six-hour miniseries based on the
book ``Desperadoes'' by Elaine Shannon, is about the slaying of
Enrique Camarena of the Drug Enforcement Administration in Mexico
and the effort to bring his killers to justice.
   It stars Steven Bauer as Camarena, Elizabeth Pena as his wife,
and Craig T. Nelson and Treat Williams as drug agents.
   ``I don't think it's any different than when we did an AIDS
tie-in after `Early Frost' or a report on abortion after `Roe Vs.
Wade,''' Tartikoff said of the tie-in. ``I think viewers have a
clear idea of the separation of news and entertainment. I think it
will be controversial, but the controversy won't be over confusing
viewers.''
   Tartikoff also said ``Murder in Mississippi,'' based on the
slayings of three civil rights workers in 1964, will air Feb. 5,
and ``Grand,'' a half-hour comedy, will debut Jan. 18 after
``Cheers.'' It replaces ``Dear John,'' which moves to Wednesdays.
   Set in a Pennsylvania town, ``Grand'' is sort of a comedic
version of ``Upstairs, Downstairs.'' The show is from Carsey-Werner
Co., which also produces the Thursday night series ``The Cosby
Show'' and ``A Different World.''
   ``The time period was determined after we saw the pilot, which
is a different kind of show that needs some nurturing and is
deserving of special attention,'' Tartikoff said.
</TEXT>
