<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     12-12 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Parties Formed in Serbia, Defying Communist Rule</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bulgaria, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two independent opposition parties
today announced their formation in Serbia, defying hard-line
Communist policies in the largest Yugoslav republic.
   Also today, the national Communist Party called for
reconciliation between Serbia and reformist Slovenia. The party's
ruling Politburo also said the situation in the country is
``characterized by strained ethnic relations and tendencies toward
the country's disintegration.''
   Thirteen prominent Belgrade intellectuals announced they were
forming the Democratic Party, while a group within the official
Serbian Socialist Youth Organization is establishing the Movement
For the Democratic Renewal.
   Serbia's Communist authorities headed by president Slobodan
Milosevic have in the past vehemently opposed introduction of
Western-style political pluralism in the southern republic.
   Several independent political and human rights groups have been
banned in Serbia and some of the activists are being prosecuted for
taking part in the illegal work of the organizations.
   It is unclear how the two new parties will operate in view of
continuing opposition from the authorities.
   Snezana Aleksic, an ideologist for Serbia's Communists, told a
gathering Monday that the formation of independent political
parties will lead to the breakup of Yugoslavia.
   In contrast, the authorities in the northern republics of
Slovenia and Croatia have lent their support to the establishment
of opposition parties that are to contest the first-ever multiparty
elections early next year.
   Croatia's Communist leadership, at its congress under way in
Zagreb, for the first time openly urged the establishment of a
parliamentary democracy in Yugoslavia.
   Representatives of both newly formed Serbian parties said at
separate news conferences held in Belgrade that they are striving
for the full legalization of multiparty pluralism, free elections,
freedom of the press and the guaranteeing of human rights.
   A commentary by the country's leading Danas news weekly said the
establishment of independent groups in Serbia represents the first
sign of the weakening within the republic of Milosevic's brand of
Communist orthodoxy.
   Milosevic has built up his popularity in Serbia by claiming he
is fighting for ``the return of Serbian dignity'' which was
allegedly humiliated by other national and ethnic groups within
Yugoslavia, especially by Slovenes and Croats.
   In an unprecedented move in the history of this country, Serbia
this month severed all business and political ties with the liberal
republic of Slovenia, in an apparent attempt to stifle the growing
reform sentiment in Yugoslavia.
   The Serbian action brought fears of the break-up of this loose
federation of six republics, several ethnic groups and religions.
   The State Department said in Washington Monday that it was
worried by rising tensions in Yugoslavia and urged the people to
unite in support of the country's reformist Premier Ante Markovic.
   Markovic has been under strong pressure from conservatives
within the country's Communist Party who oppose his efforts to
create a market-oriented economy and to promote greater political
pluralism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
