<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-VoteCounter     12-12 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Vote Counter,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Electronic Voting Off to Bumpy Start at Soviet Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Soviet-Politics, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a Parliament that was once low-tech and
rubber-stamp, a computerized voting system got off to a bumpy start
today.
   President Mikhail S. Gorbachev had to explain the system three
times before the 2,106 attending members of the Congress of
People's Deputies got it right.
   The deputies were to insert their identity cards into hand-held
vote-counters, press a button to register their names, then press
another button indicating ``yes,'' ``no'' or ``abstain'' before
handing the machine to the next person.
   Gorbachev first asked the deputies to simply register their
names. The result was 333 for, 11 against and six abstentions. The
remaining 1,756 apparently pushed no button at all.
   Gorbachev explained the system again, and the second time, 1,985
names were recorded.
   ``Maybe some people still have to learn, but we are on the right
track,'' he said.
   As a back-up, Gorbachev instructed that a committee be formed to
count votes by hand _ the old-fashioned way _ just in case the
system fails during the 10-day session.
</TEXT>
