<FIRST>r a PM-NationalGuard     12-12 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Guard,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Investigates National Guard Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state inspector general is investigating
allegations the New York National Guard used phantom troops to
garner extra federal money.
   But Lt. Col. Peter Kutschera, chief spokesman for the New York
National Guard, said the Guard is clearing out its deadwood and
resents any implication that it intentionally padded its troop
rosters.
   The New York Post reported Monday that no-show soldiers have
been kept on the rosters for at least six years, giving the
Pentagon the false impression that the Guard is ready for war or
national disaster.
   ``The state inspector general is looking at it and because of
this pending investigation it would be inappropriate for us to
comment any further,'' said Steve Villano, spokesman for Gov. Mario
Cuomo. Villano said other investigations had been conducted.
   ``We take sharp exception to this,'' Kutschera said of the
newspaper report. ``To imply that this is a sham or conscious
effort to mislead the Pentagon isn't borne out by the facts.''
   ``The one thing that is particularly disturbing is the assertion
or implication that the New York Army National Guard is not ready
to meet its wartime mission, is not combat ready,'' he said. ``The
vast number are adjudged combat-ready by our supervisory commands.''
   The Post said the New York National Guard's budget has tripled
since 1975 to $390 million a year.
   The newspaper said a phantom force was created in 1984 by Vito
Castellano, who was commander from 1975 to 1986 and reportedly
retired under pressure. It said between 1,600 and 4,000 no-show
Guardsmen in the state still are AWOL and should be dismissed.
   No-shows are not paid, but the Post said the Pentagon provides
funds for their equipment and training, which Kutschera said was
not true.
   ``Federal money for equipment allocated to the National Guard is
not based on drill attendance but on the authorized level of
equipment in the organization itself,'' he said.
   He said that local commanders, in an effort to keep personnel
strength up, have been reluctant to discharge Guardsmen for
unauthorized absences because ``it is cost-effective to
rehabilitate or bring somebody back whom you've already spent money
on.''
   But the effort was ``not particularly successful,'' and the
Guard has been speeding up the discharge of such Guardsmen, he said.
   He said the Guard has 18,900 members, and about 1,523 missed
more than nine drills a year.
   Castellano was released from prison in July after serving one
year for taking bribes and using his position to lobby for Wedtech
Corp., the now-defunct defense contractor.
   There was no answer at a suburban telephone under Castellano's
name.
</TEXT>
