<SECOND>PM-Britain Rail Crash,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survivors Mark First Anniversary of London Rail Disaster</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 35 people killed in a three-train collision
near one of Europe's busiest rail stations one year ago were
remembered today at an outdoor memorial service and a buffet car
champagne breakfast.
   An express train from Poole, 90 miles southwest of London,
rammed into the back of another passenger train near south London's
Clapham Junction rail station on Dec. 12, 1988. A freight train on
an adjacent line then plowed into spillover wreckage and struck
some passengers who had scrambled onto the tracks.
   Four commuters who regularly ride the express train to London's
Waterloo Station gathered in the buffet car this morning for a
champagne toast to their friends who died.
   ``We are toasting missing colleagues who were with us in the
buffet and who would have preferred it this way, instead of being
somber about it,'' said Christopher Reeves, 39, an engineer who
needed seven stitches in a head wound after the crash.
   British Rail and a government-appointed inquiry blamed careless
signaling work and overworked employees for the malfunctioning
direction lights which caused the accident.
   Mourners, including people who helped in the rescue operation,
gathered in the rain to lay wreaths and pray at the base of a
marble memorial depicting rescuers' outstretched hands.
