<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1021EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland     12-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland,0430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa: Give Special Powers to Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said today
that the government should be granted special economic powers
allowing it to restructure the economy without the approval of
Parliament.
   Walesa said he was ``fully aware how controversial this proposal
is. But I am forced to make it because of the ever-worsening
situation in the country and the growing impatience of society.''
   It was not known whether the Solidarity-led government of Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki supported Walesa's position.
   The government is drafting economic reform legislation for
presentation to the Sejm, or lower house of Parliament, this
weekend.
   Parliament would have to grant the government special powers to
restructure the economy.
   Walesa argued that legislative debate was slowing the adoption
of laws necessary to end Poland's economic crisis.
   ``The situation in the country is getting worse. Time is running
out. The reserve of social trust is nearly expired,'' he said in a
statement issued by Solidarity union headquarters in Gdansk.
   ``That is why one should act quickly and with determination,''
Walesa said. ``I propose giving the government extraordinary
powers.''
   He said the powers would apply to restructuring the economy,
banking and local government, changing the property system and
ending the monopoly on state-run and cooperative enterprises.
   Walesa said Parliament should grant the powers for a specific
period of time. Lawmakers then could turn their attention to
longer-term laws, while retaining the right to correct acts of the
government, he said.
   One effect of such powers would be to lessen the influence of
the Communist Party and its formerly allied parties in overseeing
economic policy.
   Mazowiecki's government is dominated by Solidarity supporters,
who hold half of the 24 Cabinet seats; the Communists hold four.
   In the Sejm, however, Solidarity has 35 percent of the seats and
the Communists 37 percent.
   There were signs last week that some of the government's radical
economic programs would have trouble in the Sejm because of the
strength of Communist Party loyalists.
   For instance, some members of the party and its former allies
spoke against a government bill that would break up nationwide
``unions of cooperatives.''
   The unions of cooperatives set prices and act as virtual
monopolies in many economic sectors, including food sales and
retailing, and are a source of patronage dominated by party
loyalists.
   The government's reform plan calls for breaking up the
monopolies. One result would be that dairies and food stores would
have to compete against one another.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
