<HEAD>Bitter Cold in Midwest; California Braces for Santa Ana Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with cold temperatures in the Midwest,
snow in Washington, D.C., schools closing; PICKS UP 5th graf pvs, `Light
rain ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Bitter temperatures gripped the Midwest today while an arctic
front stretched from eastern New York southwest across the
Carolinas. Elsewhere, Southern California remained on alert for
damaging Santa Ana winds.
   Temperatures plunged to 32 degrees below zero in Fargo, N.D.; 24
degrees below at Jamestown, N.D.; 16 degrees below at Spencer,
Iowa; 15 below at Storm Lake, Iowa, and 10 below zero at
Burlington, Iowa.
   An even colder high pressure system was predicted for the
Midwest by midweek, with temperatures expected to bottom out
Thursday morning. A slight warming trend was expected for Saturday.
   Snow, sleet and freezing rain pelted parts of the Southeast and
the mid-Atlantic states.
   In Washington, D.C., all public schools and some colleges closed
today. The snow started before dawn, and 4 to 8 inches were
expected by tonight.
   Light rain and drizzle prevailed across Kentucky and Tennessee
into Alabama and Mississippi. Showers and thunderstorms Monday
extended across southern sections of Mississippi and Louisiana.
   Fierce winds raking Southern California on Monday flipped
big-rig trucks like toys, left Christmas tree lots in disarray and
ripped down power lines, knocking out electricity to thousands of
homes.
   The Santa Ana winds, clocked at up to 80 mph, also wreaked havoc
on motorists, stirring up blinding dust storms that cut visibility
to zero as desert sand blasts peppered windshields and paint jobs
with nicks.
   There were no reports of wind-related injuries.
   Travel warnings for trucks, trailers and motor homes remained in
effect through today, particularly on Interstate 15 and Highway 60
in the Riverside-San Bernardino area.
   Winds also buffeted the eastern slopes of the Rockies in Montana
and Wyoming.
   Light snowfall lingered today in Colorado's mountains, northwest
Texas and parts of the lower Great Lakes region and the Upper Ohio
Valley.
   Temperatures remained below freezing Monday from the High Plains
to northern New England, with highs in the teens and single digits.
   The mercury stayed below zero all day in northeastern North
Dakota and northwestern Minnesota.
   Temperatures rose above 60 degrees from the lower Rio Grande
Valley of Texas to Florida and southern Georgia. Readings in the
70s were confined to southern Florida, southern Louisiana and the
lower Rio Grande Valley.
   Temperatures also warmed into the 60s and 70s in California and
southern Arizona.
   Monday's high was 80 degrees at National City, Calif., and
Imperial Beach, Calif.
   Other reports at 3 a.m. EST today:
   _EAST: Atlanta 52 rain; Boston 22 fair; Charleston, S.C., 44
fair; Chattanooga 40 drizzle; Cincinnati 24 partly cloudy;
Cleveland 25 cloudy; Detroit 15 snow; Hatteras 39 foggy;
Jacksonville 39 foggy; Key West 66 fair; Knoxville 37 rain; Macon
48 cloudy; Miami 61 partly cloudy; New York 31 fair; Philadelphia
30 foggy; Pittsburgh 27 cloudy; Portland, Maine, 9 fair; Richmond
35 drizzle; Tampa 55 fair; Washington, D.C., 35 cloudy.
   _CENTRAL: Bismarck 5 cloudy; Chicago 11 fair; Denver 18 cloudy;
Des Moines 5 fair; Indianapolis 17 cloudy; Kansas City 3 fair;
Little Rock 30 cloudy; Louisville 29 cloudy; Memphis 29 windy;
Nashville 33 cloudy; New Orleans 49 drizzle; North Platte 7 fair;
Oklahoma City 14 fair; Omaha 5 fair; Rapid City 12 cloudy; St.
Louis 13 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 3 fair; Sault Ste.
Marie 3 partly cloudy; San Antonio 30 partly cloudy.
   _WEST: Anchorage 36 rain; Boise 19 fair; Casper 22 cloudy;
Fairbanks 27 fair; Great Falls 26 windy; Honolulu 67 fair; Las
Vegas 30 fair; Los Angeles 53 fair; Medford 29; Pendleton 27 fair;
Phoenix 43 fair; Portland, Ore., 34 cloudy; Reno 19 fair; Salt Lake
City 19 fair; San Diego 47 fair; San Francisco 43 fair; Seattle 32
fair; Spokane 22 partly cloudy.
   _INTERNATIONAL: Montreal 9 cloudy; Ottawa 1 fair; Regina 9 snow;
Toronto 7 fair.
