<SECOND>PM-BRF--Egypt-Riot,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police, Islamic Militants Clash; 40 Wounded, Hundreds Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASSIUT, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem fundamentalists armed with guns,
sticks, chains and incendiary bombs fought police while protesting
co-ed college activities. Forty people were wounded and more than
300 arrested, authorities said today.
   The clash on Monday began when militant fundamentalists who had
been holed up inside a police-besieged mosque left the building and
tried to march to the city center, said police Maj. Gen. Mahmoud
el-Fakharan.
   When police intervened to stop the demonstrators outside the
mosque, ``they came under fire from the extremists'' and a shootout
ensued, he said.
   Ten policemen and 30 militants were wounded and all the
demonstrators were arrested. Many of the injuries were bullet
wounds, el-Fakharany said.
   The streets of Assiut, 238 miles south of Cairo, were quiet
today.
   The militants were protesting the Assiut University student
union's policy allowing co-ed parties and excursions that they
consider contrary to Islamic teachings.
