<FIRST>u i PM-Czechoslovakia 2ndLd-Writethru   12-12 0911</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0521,0937</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hard-Liners Resign From Presidium, Czechoslavakia Begins Search for
President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Slovak parliament proposing
Dubcek for president. Pickup 5th graf `Prior to...'; DROPS 15th graf `Although
several...' to CONFORM; SUBS 24th graf, `But Havel ...' to CORRECT Dubcek
age to 68, sted 67.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communists responsible for 21
years of hard-line policy resigned from their last powerful posts
today, as Parliament considered how to select a new president.
   Playwright Vaclav Havel, riding a wave of popular support as
leader of the opposition Civic Forum, has offered to serve as
president until free elections can be held next year. More of his
posters appeared in the capital today.
   Slovakia's regional parliament today asked the Federal Assembly,
or national parliament, to consider former Communist leader
Alexander Dubcek for president and called him ``the most important
figure of modern Czechoslovak history,'' the government news agency
CTK said. Dubcek was ousted after ``Prague Spring'' reforms were
crushed by Soviet tanks in 1968.
   Hard-line Communist President Gustav Husak resigned Sunday after
swearing in a Cabinet that for the first time in four decades was
dominated by non-Communists.
   The new government was a historic victory for the nation's
opposition movement, which has forced the government to open
borders, promise free elections and revoke the Communists'
constitutionally guaranteed leading role in society.
   Late Monday, the Club of Communist deputies, a caucus of the
Communists who dominate the 350-member Federal Assembly demanded
the new president be chosen by nationwide referendum, CTK said.
   Prior to the announcement, it was expected that the lawmaking
body _ dominated by Communists and traditionally a rubber-stamp
body for Communist policy _ would select the interim president.
   It was unclear whether or how the deputies would vote on the
issue at the session that opened today with the resignation of
ousted Communist Party chief Milos Jakes and other hard-liners from
their last positions of power as members of the parliament's
guiding Presidium.
   Jakes and former ideology chief Vasil Bilak sat stone-faced as
their fellow deputies in the House of Nations, one of two
constituent bodies of the parliament, accepted their resignations.
   On Monday, in the first act of retribution against hard-liners
who crushed the ``Prague Spring,'' Bilak was charged for his part
in the crackdown, the state news agency CTK said.
   ``According to some opinions, his deeds can be considered
treason,'' CTK said without detailing the charges against Bilak.
   Bilak, who resigned from the party's ruling Politburo last year,
is widely believed to be the Czechoslovak Communist who lent most
support to the August 1968 Soviet-led invasion that crushed reform.
   Bilak, now 72, will not however face trial ``for this
wrongdoing,'' CTK said, because of the country's statute of
limitations for crimes committed more than 20 years ago. Although
CTK did not explain the anomaly of charging someone with a crime he
cannot be prosecuted for, it appeared to be a symbolic attribution
of guilt 21 years after the invasion.
   The Slovak Communist Party daily Pravda today said Bilak put
``shame on the party.'' It said he acquired a large villa for
$20,000 after the government renovated it for 10 times as much.
   New posters bearing a portrait of Havel and his motto, ``Truth
and Love Must Prevail Over Lies and Hatred'' appeared all over
central Prague today.
   Havel's face smiled from posters plastered to walls and windows
throughout central Prague over the caption, ``Havel na Hrad,'' or
Havel to the Castle, the presidential residence.
   On Monday, the Civic Forum opposition group issued a statement
backing Havel, but stressing any president chosen now would have to
resign before free elections.
   On Sunday, Havel addressed 100,000 cheering supporters from a
balcony overlooking Wenceslas Square.
   Small groups of demonstrators supporting Havel for president
took to the streets on Monday in Prague, Pilsen and Brno.
   Meanwhile, Havel himself began sounding more like a national
leader than a member of the opposition.
   In an interview with Soviet television also shown on
Czechoslovak television Monday, the playwright reassured leaders in
Moscow that, if elected, he would remain a member of the Warsaw
Pact.
   ``Our ideal is Europe as a peaceful community'' that ultimately
requires a ``dissolution of blocs,'' Havel said.
   But, he added, ``We understand that we shall not get any closer
to this ideal by any kind of individual split from the Warsaw
Treaty, longing for some kind of immediate and individual
neutrality.''
   Several other names have also been floated for president,
including Ladislav Adamec, the former premier who agreed to add
non-Communists to his government but then resigned, and Cestmir
Cisar, expelled from the Communist Party in 1970 after serving as
the student's candidate for president in 1968.
   But, Havel, 53, and Dubcek, 68, were seen as two most serious
contenders.
   Politburo member Ondrej Saling told reporters that a meeting
between Communists and opposition forces on Monday agreed that the
president should be a Czech with no party affiliation.
   ``In my view, the president must be someone who enjoys broad
support and guarantees stability,'' he said, seeming to describe
Havel.
   On Monday, Czechoslovaks filled the air with a jubilant
cacophony of bells, sirens and car horns in celebration of their
popular victory over the Communists.
   The three-minute blast of noise replaced a scheduled general
strike that was called off after the new 21-member Cabinet was
announced Sunday, putting Communists in the minority for the first
time since 1948.
</TEXT>
