<FIRST>r w PM-Mencken-PressClub     12-12 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mencken-Press Club,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Press Club Postpones Action on Changing Name of Mencken Library</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Directors of the National Press Club have put
off a decision on renaming the club's H. L. Mencken Library and
Reference Center while they look into revelations of racial and
religious bias in Mencken's writings, club President Peter Holmes
said today.
   ``Everyone felt they wanted to have an opportunity to read the
record and become more acquainted with Mencken and the impetus for
naming the library for him in the first place and the nature of the
brouhaha that arose with the publication of his diaries,'' said
Holmes, an editor with The Washington Times.
   The diaries, published recently, showed deep-set anti-Semetic
and anti-black sentiments by Mencken, who died in 1956.
   Mick Rood, a reporter for States News Service and a member of
the club's board of directors, said last week that he admired
Mencken's writing about language, his political commentary and his
wit. ``With the release of his diary, however, we also know of his
duplicity, his hatred and his bigotry,'' Rood said.
   Holmes said the decision Monday night to postpone consideration
of the issue was reached amiably. He said Rood told the other
directors he intended to pursue it at a meeting in late January.
   Mencken, a beloved native son of Baltimore, wrote a column for
many years for the Evening Sun of Baltimore and was an influential
man of letters in the 1920s and the 1930s.
</TEXT>
