<SECOND>PM-Houston Police,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Attends Funeral Despite `Last Wish' of Slain Officer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Kathy Whitmire attended a funeral for a
slain policeman today despite a plea from his lawyer to stay away
because the officer believed she was no friend of the Police
Department.
   Whitmire and Police Chief Lee P. Brown joined several hundred
officers at the funeral for Jim Boswell at the invitation of
Boswell's father, Cecil E. Boswell of Meridian, Miss., said the
mayor's spokesman, Paul Mabry.
   She did not immediately discuss the issue with reporters at the
service at Second Baptist Church.
   Richard Cobb, lawyer for the Houston Police Patrolmen's Union,
had written Mrs. Whitmire that it was Boswell's ``last wish'' that
``you should not be admitted to his funeral.''
   ``Officer Boswell felt very strongly that you neither respected
nor supported him or his fellow officers when he was a Houston
police officer,'' Cobb wrote.
   Boswell, 29, was shot to death Saturday by a man who approached
him for help as he wrote a traffic ticket. The four-year veteran
had told the man he would have to wait while the officer finished
writing the ticket.
   Craig Neal Ogan, 35, is being held without bail on charges of
capital murder. He was shot by Boswell's partner and remains in
fair condition under police guard at Ben Taub Hospital.
   Boswell was the second Houston officer slain in two days; on
Sunday, an off-duty officer was killed in a domestic dispute.
   Cobb's letter purported to represent Boswell's entire family,
but Mabry said the officer's father was embarrassed by the letter
and wanted the mayor to come.
   Police union president Tommy Britt said the letter had been
written at the elder Boswell's request. Britt speculated that the
officer's father had later ``succumbed to pressure'' to invite the
mayor and police chief.
   Boswell was a cartoonist for The Sentinel, a police union
publication that has been sharply critical of the mayor and
supported her challenger in last month's election.
   ``The very idea of your capitalizing on his death to serve your
own public relations ends was repugnant to him, and, consequently,
to his family,'' the letter said.
</TEXT>
