<FIRST>u w PM-USSIowa-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0420 12-12 0859</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-USS Iowa-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0420,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator Stands Firm on Blast Cause</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: TOP 11 grafs new with testimony from Milligan, comments; picks
up at pvs 2nd graf, `You know;' edits and cuts below to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The admiral who investigated the explosion
aboard the battleship USS Iowa said today he knew of no new
information that would change his conclusion that a depressed
Gunner's Mate Clayton Hartwig likely caused the blast that killed
47 sailors.
   But the statements by Navy officials in defense of their
findings failed to sway several members of the House Armed Services
investigations subcommittee, who continued to question the
service's findings in the tragedy last April 19.
   ``I believe after these hearings we all will have a much better
insight into this man (Hartwig) to see if he indeed was the type of
person who could have killed himself and 46 of his shipmates,''
subcommittee Chairman Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass., said at the
start of three days of hearings.
   ``I am not now convinced he was capable of such an act,''
Mavroules added.
   Rear Adm. Richard Milligan, who oversaw the inquiry into the
explosion that rocked gun turret No. 2 on the Iowa, told lawmakers
he knew his conclusion would be ``the source of controversy, and
for many, of pain and heartache.''
   However, he said his investigation eliminated accident and
malfunction as a cause and, in his opinion, the explosion was the
result of an intentional act.
   Milligan said that since he released the report on Sept. 7, ``I
know of nothing that would cause me to change my report.''
   Members of the House panel zeroed in on the issue of the
rotating band from the 16-inch gun, which according to the Navy
included some foreign material, likely from a detonator. Navy
officials theorized that Hartwig used some type of detonator to
trigger the explosion.
   Rep. Les Aspin, D-Wis., questioned whether the band could have
been contaminated following the explosion in the cleanup effort in
the gun turret or in the Navy's handling of the evidence.
   Capt. Joseph D. Miceli, director of the Naval Sea Systems
Command technical investigative team, said the band was not
contaminated and the foreign material had been embedded in it.
   The Navy's finding also came under siege in a Senate committee
Monday as the ship's captain refused to endorse the conclusion that
Hartwig likely caused the blast.
   ``You know, the Navy's on trial here in a way,'' Sen. John
Warner of Virginia, a former Navy secretary, said in
cross-examining FBI psychologists who depicted Hartwig as a
suicidal loner.
   Warner, ranking Republican on the Senate Armed Services
Committee, and his panel colleagues zeroed in on three FBI
officials who testified Monday that they told the Naval
Investigative Service they believed Hartwig displayed numerous
symptoms of a person contemplating suicide.
   The hard-nosed interrogation came after Iowa Capt. Fred
Moosally, in his first public testimony about the incident, told
the panel, ``I do not agree or disagree'' with the Navy's
conclusions.
   ``I embraced that it was an intentional act,'' Moosally told
reporters after his appearance. ``I cannot make the jump that it
was absolutely Petty Officer Hartwig. ... I don't think I can say
that a definite individual did it. He was a good gunner's mate.''
   Moosally, however, said he thought the ship had been sabotaged
because he didn't believe there could be any other explanation for
the April 19 explosion.
   The service, in its Sept. 7 report, concluded that Hartwig
``most likely'' caused the blast by inserting some type of
detonator between bags of gunpowder in one of the ship's 16-inch
guns.
   Navy officials acknowledged their evidence was circumstantial
because all the witnesses, including Hartwig, were killed.
   The service said the case against Hartwig was built largely on
evidence drawn from forensic tests and a psychological profile,
which was a point of contention Monday for members of the Senate
panel.
   Using information provided by the Naval Investigative Service,
including Hartwig's letters, interviews with the seaman's family
and friends and his personal history, three FBI psychologists
testified that Hartwig was ``egocentric, shy ... not sufficiently
aggressive, had a low self-esteem.''
   With members of Hartwig's family sitting nearby, the
psychologists cited various bits of information that when pieced
together, according to their assessment, form a picture of a loner
bent on self-destruction.
   The FBI officials, however, acknowledged that they had no hard
evidence that Hartwig was responsible for the explosion.
   ``His whole fabric is death and destruction,'' said Robert
Hazelwood of the FBI's Criminal Investigative Analysis Program.
   Among the information on Hartwig was a subscription to Soldier
of Fortune magazine he had as a teen-ager, a suicidal gesture he
once made to a friend at age 17 or 18, his collection of knives and
his reference to the Iowa as a ``damning pig.''
   The FBI officials also said that at the time of his death,
Hartwig had ``$34 in his bank account, few clothes and a poorly
maintained vehicle.''
   But members of the committee questioned how the psychologists
could determine that, based on traits fairly common among young
sailors, the 24-year-old Hartwig was suicidal.
</TEXT>
