<FIRST>u i PM-Egypt-Syria 2ndLd-Writethru   12-12 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Egypt-Syria, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0516,0526</SECOND>
<HEAD>Precede CAIRO, Egypt</HEAD>
<HEAD>First National Airline Flight to Syria in 10 Years</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Egyptian plane landing in
Syria; Pickup 6th graf `The Egyptian ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Egyptian airliner landed here today
for the first time in 10 years, marking an improvement in relations
between the two Arab countries at odds with each other since
Cairo's peace treaty with Israel.
   The Egypt Air Boeing 737 carried a special party of officials
lead by Maj. Gen. Samir Rashad, Egypt's deputy minister of
transport.
   The two countries still do not have diplomatic relations, but
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Syrian President Hafez Assad
decided during a telephone call Monday to resume air links.
   Syria and Libya are the only Arab holdouts against
rehabilitating Egypt by restoring diplomatic relations severed to
protest Cairo's 1979 peace treaty with Israel. The other 15 Arab
states that broke off ties for the same reason have since restored
them.
   But small steps toward full normalcy have been evident in recent
months in Egypt's relations with Syria and Libya.
   Mubarak visited the Libyan town of Sirte today for talks with
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi, the Middle East News Agency said. It
was their fourth meeting this year and the news agency report
indicated economic cooperation would be a main topic.
   The Egyptian news agency said the air agreement with Syria was
reached in a telephone call Mubarak made to President Hafez Assad
of Syria.
   The accord takes effect today, the agency said, and Mubarak
ordered ``prompt implementation.'' It did not say how many weekly
flights EgyptAir and Syrian Arab Airlines, the national carriers,
would operate between Cairo and Damascus.
   Air services were halted immediately after the diplomatic
rupture.
   Middle East News Agency also reported that Mubarak would be
sending a special envoy to Assad in Damascus within the next few
days. Government sources said the emissary was expected to be
Foreign Minister Esmat Abdel-Meguid.
   Resuming air services is the first normalization measure since
Mubarak and Assad met privately in May during an Arab summit in
Casablanca, Morocco.
   Sixteen months earlier, the two leaders had talked privately on
the sidelines of an Islamic summit in Kuwait. That meeting, in
January 1987, was the first for the two since Mubarak took office
in 1981.
   Egypt's relations with Libya thawed faster this year than with
Syria.
   Mubarak and Gadhafi also met in Casablanca during the May
summit. Then they met twice in October, first in Egypt's
Mediterranean city of Mersa Matruh, close to the border between the
North African countries, and the next day in Libya's port of Tobruk.
   Gadhafi and Mubarak agreed to closer economic ties in
agriculture, petroleum and industry. Low-level Egyptian and Libyan
delegations exchanged visits to promote cooperation, including
possible joint projects.
   In June, Egypt and Libya resumed direct air services and
reopened frontiers closed since 1977 when the two countries fought
a five-day war.
   Gadhafi's hostility toward Egypt stemmed mainly from its refusal
to merge with Libya in 1972 and its peace with Israel.
</TEXT>
