<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1206EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Immigration-AIDS     12-12 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Immigration-AIDS,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>AIDS Commission Calls for End to Discriminatory Practices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Commission on AIDS today called
for an end to practices that discriminate against visitors to the
United States who are infected with the AIDS virus.
   The commission also called for an end to the questioning of
non-immigrants about their AIDS status while applying for visas.
   ``This would eliminate the current practice of stopping
travelers who are carrying AZT, which is the only licensed anti-HIV
drug, and blood products such as clotting factor, which is used by
hemophiliacs,'' the commission said. HIV stands for human
immunodeficiency virus, believed to be the cause of AIDS.
   ``In some cases travelers have been ejected from the United
States because it was revealed, by inference or direct questioning,
that the traveler had HIV infection,'' the commission said.
   Current U.S. visa practices have been criticized by a number of
scientific, medical and humanitarian organizations.
   The commission said that when HIV testing is part of the
immigration process, the federal agencies must ensure that
standards are enforced for counseling, confidentiality and
referrals for health care.
   The National Commission on AIDS is an independent body created
by Congress to oversee efforts against the disease and to make
recommendations for national policy.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious,
incurable disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering
it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus
is spread through contact with blood or with semen from infected
persons. No one is known to have recovered from the disease.
</TEXT>
