<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1212EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DesegregationRuling     12-12 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Desegregation Ruling,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>$130 Million Desegregation Settlement Approved</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON FOURNIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge approved a $130 million
settlement of a 7-year-old school desegregation case but put the
money in a court-supervised account to make sure it's spent on
addressing racial discrimination.
   ``It is now abundantly clear that the settlement funds cannot be
trusted to the parties,'' U.S. District Judge Henry Woods said
Monday.
   Under the settlement, the state agreed to pay $130 million to
help achieve racial balance in three school districts in Pulaski
County, which includes Little Rock, the scene in 1957 of a landmark
federal-state showdown over segregation.
   The money will be used to implement a plan to assign students
among the districts to promote racial balance; to reimburse the
costs of raising the level of education in Little Rock, and to pay
other desegregation costs.
   In approving the settlement, Woods blasted school districts for
suggesting that the money be used to pay debts unrelated to
desegregation, and he cut the plaintiff's attorney fees sharply,
from $3.15 million to $850,000.
   Woods ordered that the largest desegregation settlement in state
history be put in an account monitored by a court-appointed
supervisor.
   ``The amount of money is meager enough,' he said. ``To put money
in the hands of those who feel no compunction even to say they
intend to spend the money to compensate the victims of racial
discrimination would be a grave injustice.''
   The Little Rock School District, which is mostly black, had sued
the neighboring, mostly white North Little Rock and Pulaski County
districts, alleging that the placement of new schools had prompted
white flight from the Little Rock schools. The districts have a
total enrollment of about 58,000.
   The settlement was reached in March. In a special session in
July, the Legislature agreed to spend $129.75 million over 10 years
for desegregation.
   The Little Rock-area districts in 1982 began magnet schools,
which attract both blacks and whites by offering a specialized
curriculum, and busing to achieve racial balance began in 1972.
   In 1957, then-Gov. Orval Faubus refused to allow nine black
students to enter Little Rock's all-white Central High School.
President Eisenhower sent federal troops to keep the peace and
enforce court-ordered desegregation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
