<SECOND>AM-BRF--Benin,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Benin Bans Public Demonstrations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COTONOU, Benin (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has banned public
demonstrations and warned that police will use force to keep order,
one day after 40,000 took to the streets and demanded that
President Mathier Kerekou resign.
   Similar demonstrations also took place Monday in the capital
city of Porto Novo, Ouidah and Abomey, with reports of violence and
one death.
   The ban was announced by radio Monday evening following the
march by 40,000 in Cotonou, Benin's economic capital.
   Last week, Kerekou announced the government was scrapping its
Marxist-Leninist ideology and would draft a new constitution
liberalizing the economy and guaranteeing human rights.
   The government has been unable to pay bills, including the
salaries of thousands of government employees.
   Western economists say Kerekou's efforts to impose centralized
controls on the economy has hampered growth. In recent months,
several scandals have further tarnished his image, including the
arrest of two associates on drug trafficking charges.
   Benin, a former French colony, is one of the world's poorest
nations, with a per capital income of $310 and a foreign debt of
nearly $1 billion.
</TEXT>
