<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1225EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Famine-Ethiopia     12-12 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Famine-Ethiopia,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kenyan Says Ethiopia Will Allow Relief Food to Famine Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Ethiopia has agreed to
establish a corridor for emergency food aid into its embattled and
drought-stricken north, Kenya's president said Tuesday.
   President Daniel arap Moi said he had asked Ethiopia's two main
rebel groups to do the same and ``to stop fighting when this food
aid is being delivered. I hope they will do so.''
   He said the rebels had not responded to his request.
   Moi said he asked Ethiopian President Mengistu Haile Mariam ``to
create a corridor for food aid to pass to the people of Tigre and
Eritrea. He has accepted that request.'' It was not clear if Moi
was referring to people in government-held areas, in war zones or
in both.
   The United Nations says the drought in Ethiopia's northern
provinces of Eritrea, Tigre, Gonder and Wollo threatens as many as
4 million people with starvation, and it has urged international
donors to provide 600,000 tons of emergency relief food. Ethiopia's
government disputes the U.N. figure and claims the real number of
people threatened with famine is 1.8 million.
   About half the people threatened with famine live behind rebel
lines. Relief agencies fear mass migrations of the hungry to
government-held areas in search of food.
   Such migrations in the 1984-85 famine led to vast, overcrowded
and unsanitary camps where as many people died from disease as from
hunger. As many as 1 million people are believed to have died in
that disaster.
   An Ethiopian government spokesman attending preliminary peace
talks that opened Tuesday in Rome between Ethiopia's government and
the rebel Tigre People's Liberation Army confirmed that a corridor
would be opened and said a date for the start of relief shipments
along the route would be decided this week.
   The spokesman, who declined to give his name, would not give any
details on the proposed route.
   However, a rebel spokesman also at the talks said he did not
think any such relief corridor would be opened soon.
   ``We are pushing for corridors between the rebel-controlled
areas as well as between the government-controlled areas, at least
for free passage of relief and relief workers,'' but so far to no
avail, said the spokesman, who identified himself only as Hayla.
   Neither spokesman would say whether Moi intervened in attempts
to establish the corridor.
   The idea of relief corridors into embattled areas was
implemented in southern Sudan this year when the United Nations
launched a massive aid program aimed at averting tens of thousands
of famine deaths.
   Sudan's government and the nation's southern rebels respected
the half a dozen corridors, or routes, established for the delivery
of relief supplies into southern Sudan for about six months before
the de facto cease-fire dissolved in renewed fighting.
   Moi's announcement came on the opening day of a second round of
preliminary peace talks in Rome between Ethiopia's government and
the rebel Tigre People's Liberation Front aimed at ending their
14-year-old civil war.
   The Tigreans, in a 3-month-old offensive, have pushed to within
100 miles of Ethiopia's capital, Addis Ababa, and are seen as a
growing threat to Mengistu's government.
   Ethiopia's other major rebel group, the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front, which has been fighting a secessionist battle in
northern Eritrea province since 1961, ended its second round of
preliminary peace talks with the government Nov. 29. Both sides
have agreed to begin substantial negotiations next year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
