<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Israel-Satellite     12-12 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Israel-Satellite,0170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Displays Communications Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Tuesday unveiled a full-scale
prototype of its first communications satellite, scheduled to be
launched in 1993, and officials said they expected it to boost
Israeli high technology exports.
   The 30-foot-by-30-foot, 1,320-pound Amos satellite will have
about half the capability of most Western communications satellites
and will function for 10 years, said Phil Herman, a spokesman for
the government-owned Israel Aircraft Industries. It has no military
applications, he said.
   Israel plans to launch two Amos communications satellites in
1993 and will offer to sell it to foreign countries or
corporations. The launch will be carried out by the European
Arianne space consortium.
   ``The satellite is designed for developing countries and very
large corporations that need a dedicated satellite for their own
purposes,'' Herman said.
   In September 1988, Israel launched its first space satellite,
Horizon-1, which remained in orbit for almost four months. It was
launched on an Israeli missile and was used for scientific research.
</TEXT>
