<FIRST>u w PM-Congress-China 2ndLd-Writethru a0495 12-12 0776</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Congress-China, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0495,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressional Leaders Put Override at Top of Calendar</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Top 7 grafs new with comments from sponsor of vetoed bill, Chinese
student leader, picking up at pvs 3rd graf, `Congress is;' inserts one
graf with Republican backing Bush after pvs 6th graf, `I think'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress' first order of business when it
reconvenes next month will be an attempt to override President
Bush's veto of a bill permitting Chinese students to remain in the
United States indefinitely if they fear retaliation at home, the
bill's sponsor said today.
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., said she has received assurances of
the top priority from House and Senate leaders that an override
vote would be the first order of business when Congress returns to
session in late January.
   Congressional Democrats, fuming over renewed high-level U.S.
visits with China's leaders, also are vowing to revive legislation
imposing sanctions on the Chinese government as punishment for the
killings of pro-democracy demonstrators.
   Pelosi, at a news conference, said she is gaining commitments to
override now from Democrats and Republicans and is confident of a
large bipartisan majority.
   ``I think we have enough (votes) to override,'' she said. ``We
feel the president's actions this weekend are such a slap in the
face to the forces of democracy and such an encouragement of a
tyranical regime that it is making our job easier.''
   Haiching Zhao, chairman of the National Committee on Chinese
Student Affairs, said the administration's high-level visit to
China will strengthen the hardliners in Beijing and encourage a
``slide into darkness'' in China.
   ``The situation in China has not been improved since the June
4th massacre,'' he said. ``Taken together, the veto and the visit
create a clear and present danger that the hardliners in the
Chinese government will now feel free to impose more repression and
further reprisals against the democracy movement.''
   ``Congress is in no mood to kowtow to these Chinese leaders,''
Rep. Stephen J. Solarz, D-N.Y., chairman of the Foreign Affairs
Asian subcommittee, said Monday as he predicted Congress will
override the Bush veto and adopt the legislation requiring
sanctions.
   But Congress is out of session and a legislative attack on
Bush's China policy must wait until the second session of the 101st
Congress convenes late next month.
   Republican Sen. Mitch McConnell of Kentucky joined Democrats in
the criticism.
   ``I think it's the wrong message at the wrong time, although I
know what the president was trying to do,'' McConnell said this
morning on NBC's ``Today'' show. ``We have historically, when we
have made overtures to the Soviet Union or had big meetings with
the Soviet Union, felt the need to have some gesture in the
direction of the Chinese.''
   Bush gained support for his overature to China, however, from
Rep. Jim Leach, R-Iowa. In a statement, he called the criticism
premature and said the trip was ``a risky but thoughtful
consultation'' that could lead to moderation by China.
   Democratic leaders made clear their strong disagreement with
Bush's decision to dispatch Brent Scowcroft, his national security
adviser, and Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger to
Beijing over the weekend for the first high-level meetings with
China's leaders since the crackdown in Tiananmen Square in June.
   ``I condemn the president's veto of the Chinese students bill
and this weekend's embarrassing kowtowing to the Chinese
government,'' said Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell, D-Maine.
``These actions make a mockery of our profession of concern for
human rights and are inconsistent with our stated ideals.''
   Mitchell said he will lead the fight to override the Bush's Nov.
30 veto of legislation which would permit Chinese students to
remain in the United States if they fear reprisal at home.
   ``We will make every effort to override that veto,'' Mitchell
said.
   Although the House and Senate approved differing versions of
sanctions legislation, they failed to complete action on a single
measure before Congress adjourned for the year on Nov. 21.
   Both bills would incorporate into law the steps Bush took
voluntarily after the Chinese crackdown.
   Although the legislation would permit the president to suspend
sanctions if he certified that doing so was in the national
interest, it likely would be politically difficult without
significant human rights improvement in China.
   The sanctions include:
   _Suspending insurance and financing for U.S. investment in China
by the Overseas Private Investment Corp.
   _Barring export to China of all weapons and military equipment
or equipment intended for police use.
   _Prohibiting export of nuclear supplies, equipment and
technology.
   _Barring the export of American satellites.
   _Requiring the president to seek the imposition of similar
sanctions by U.S. allies.
</TEXT>
