<FIRST>u w PM-Iran-Contra 3rdLd-Writethru a0581 12-12 0754</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran-Contra, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0581,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Has Trouble Separating Own Experiences From Poindexter Testimony</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Inserts 3 grafs of Fitzwater comment after 18th graf, On Monday;
deletes last 2 grafs pvs, redundant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former White House aide Oliver L. North told a
court today he is having difficulty separating his own experiences
in the Iran-Contra scandal from the testimony that ex-national
security adviser John Poindexter gave Congress under immunity from
prosecution.
   At a pre-trial hearing in the criminal case against Poindexter,
North said Poindexter's five-day appearance on Capitol Hill in July
1987 constituted some of the most ``powerful'' testimony of the
congressional hearings into the scandal and that he watched it
closely.
   ``I read the transcript'' of Poindexter's testimony, said North,
who Iran-Contra prosecutors want to use as a government witness in
Poindexter's trial.
   Under a 1972 Supreme Court ruling, the government may make no
use of a defendant's testimony that was compelled under a limited
grant of immunity from prosecution. That includes testimony given
by other witnesses who may have been influenced by the immunized
statements.
   Today's hearing was called so that U.S. District Judge Harold
Greene can determine whether North was tainted by Poindexter's
testimony.
   The former National Security Council aide, returning to the
courthouse where he was convicted of three felonies, initially
invoked his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination when
called to the witness stand.
   The office of independent counsel Lawrence Walsh then obtained
from Greene an order compelling North to testify in exchange for a
promise not to prosecute him for his statements, as long as he
tells the truth.
   North said he was unable to recall crucial details that
prosecutors want to focus on in their case against Poindexter.
   He said he was unable to remember telling Poindexter about false
statements in letters to Congress denying that North was assisting
the Contra rebels in Nicaragua when such aid was banned by law.
   ``Did you have discussions with Admiral Poindexter before the
letter was sent ... about the false nature of the response?'' asked
Iran-Contra prosecutor Dan Webb.
   ``I don't recall,'' North replied.
   Poindexter faces trial Jan. 22 on criminal charges of conspiracy
and two counts each of obstructing Congress and making false
statements in connection with Iran-Contra.
   Poindexter told Congress that he made no effort to prevent North
from destroying a notebook containing information about a November
1985 shipment of Hawk missiles to Iran.
   Poindexter also testified that he withheld information from
Congress on National Security Council activities to aid the Contras
in order to avoid publicity and more restrictive legislation. In
1985 and 1986, Congress banned military aid to the rebel force by
U.S. intelligence agencies.
   The former national security adviser is accused of falsely
telling Congress that no one in the U.S. government knew until 1986
that the 1985 shipment to Iran contained Hawks. He also is accused
of falsely denying to Congress that North and the NSC staff didn't
solicit funds or offer tactical advice to the Contras.
   North was convicted May 4 of aiding and abetting an obstruction
of Congress, accepting an illegal gratuity and of destroying
government documents.
   He was sentenced July 5 to 1,200 hours of community service and
a $150,000 fine. North is appealing the convictions and the fine
while serving the community service in an anti-drug program.
   On Monday, independent counsel Lawrence Walsh disclosed that
President Bush had turned aside Walsh's request for a face-to-face
meeting with the president.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said today that the
decision against a meeting with Walsh ``was the recommendation of
counsel (White House counsel Boyden Gray), which the president
accepted and agrees with. We should not be involved in the legal
process and the court system.''
   Fitzwater said the cases themselves and legal ramifications
``are subjects that should be discussed between the attorney
general, who is the president's lawyer, and the independent
counsel.''
   ``On substance, our responsiblity is to protect classified
information an to protect methods and sources and so forth that are
part ofthat and we feel we have to meet that responsiblity and have
done so,'' Fitzwater said.
   In a report to Congress, the Iran-Contra prosecutor revealed
that he wrote Bush on Oct. 19, saying that the administration was
engaging in ``interference'' by invoking national security concerns
in the case against a former CIA station chief, Joseph Fernandez.
   ``Without your help the rule of law will be subordinated to the
intelligence effort,'' wrote Walsh. ``The tail has begun to wag the
dog.''
 
</TEXT>
