<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1349EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SantaExpress     12-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Santa Express,0319</SECOND>
<HEAD>Santa Express Heads Out for Another Fund-Raising Effort</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VICKSBURG, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Once again, Bob Carver will spend his
Christmas vacation working _ driving a tractor-trailer rig on the
open road while playing Santa to raise money for the Salvation Army.
   Over the past seven years, Carver has logged nearly 80,000 miles
on his ``Santa Express'' during his vacation from the U.S.
Waterways Experiment Station.
   ``I love to drive a truck and this project promotes good will,''
Carver said. ``Probably the biggest kick I get is watching the kids
when they see the truck or me with my Santa's hat.''
   Every year at this time, he takes a temporary job with a
trucking company hauling cargo long distance. Sponsors pledge to
pay so much per mile of his trip to the Salvation Army. Sometimes
he is greeted by children at his destination and dons a Santa
outfit for them.
   Carver, a licensed commercial driver as well as a research
engineer, donates his trucking pay check to the Vicksburg Salvation
Army. That has amounted to almost $27,000 over the past seven years.
   This year, he will be accompanied by his wife, Ruth, who also
drives a truck. The couple married in October.
   ``We'll have a good time and my five-year-old grandson, Chris,
is going with us. I can help Bob with some of the driving,'' said
Mrs. Carver, who drove a truck for five years.
   The Carvers will leave Monday en route to Boston in an
18-wheeler which has ``Santa Express'' signs on the doors. They
plan to be back in Vicksburg in time for Christmas.
   This year, White Heavy Express of Pearl is sponsoring the long
haul. Carver said several businesses in the Jackson area have
pledged 2 cents per mile and he hopes to get Vicksburg businesses
to do the same so he can raise about $3,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
