<FIRST>r i AM-India-Kidnap     12-12 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Kidnap,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disagreement Over Meeting Site Holds Up Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASKARI ZAIDI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SRINAGAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kidnappers who agreed to release a
Cabinet minister's daughter in exchange for jailed Moslem
separatists demanded that the site for the swap be changed,
officials said Tuesday.
   Thousands of people gathered in the neighborhood called Bauri
Kadal, in this northern city near the Pakistan border, anticipating
the release of the militants. Some demonstrators set off
firecrackers and a few groups shouted anti-India slogans.
   The separatist Kashmir Liberation Front, which claimed
responsibility for kidnapping Rubaiya Saeed, 22, on Friday, is
demanding the release of five to seven militants, including Abdul
Hamid Sheikh, the group's leader.
   After initial haggling, the two sides agreed at midday to
conduct the swap at an isolated site, but the kidnappers later
reneged on the agreement, according to a top Jammu-Kashmir state
police officer in Jammu, about 95 miles south of Srinagar.
   The kidnappers want the jailed militants released at Bauri
Kadal, said the officer, speaking on condition of anonymity. They
promised to free Ms. Sayeed later at an unspecified place, he said.
   The state's chief secretary, Moosa Raza, refused comment on
this. ``We have a lot of proposals but I cannot disclose them
now,'' he said.
   Ms. Saeed was kidnapped at gunpoint in Srinagar. Her father is
Home Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, who oversees internal security.
   The abduction triggered the first crisis for the 10-day-old
government of Prime Minister V.P. Singh, who last week appointed
Sayeed, a Moslem, as part of an effort to appease Moslems in this
mainly Hindu nation.
   The Kashmir Liberation Front, which wants Jammu-Kashmir to
either become independent or part of Islamic Pakistan, commands a
large following in the Moslem-dominated Srinagar.
   The front, formed in 1965, has often attacked the government and
sponsored successful strikes in Jammu-Kashmir, India's only Moslem
majority state.
   Kashmir is claimed both by India and Pakistan, and the two
countries have fought three wars over the territory since they
gained independence from Britain in 1947.
</TEXT>
