<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Smuggling     12-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Smuggling,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>American Gets Suspended Sentence For Smuggling Soviet Gold, Jewels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American was convicted of trying to smuggle
more than $92,000 worth of gold, jewels and currency out of the
Soviet Union but received a suspended sentence Tuesday, Tass
reported.
   Martin Mendelson, 24, of Washington, D.C., was caught at
Leningrad airport Sept. 25 trying to fly to Finland without
declaring money, ``items of gold and silver and jewels worth a
great sum,'' the official news agency said.
   He had been held in jail since then but was released Tuesday
after a court gave him a three-year sentence and ordered some of
the valuables confiscated, Tass said.
   Mendelson, a tour guide for the New York-based Russian Travel
Bureau, had been trying to get the valuables out of the Soviet
Union for Maya Bogdadlishvili, 31, of Moscow, Tass said. She also
was given a suspended sentence.
   Tass said the court took into account the fact that the
defendants pleaded guilty and had no prior convictions.
   Soviet customs procedures have become less strict in the last
year. Travelers arriving at Moscow's Sheremetyevo Airport even have
the option of passing through a ``nothing-to-declare'' customs line.
   They are still required to declare valuables and foreign
currency, and the restrictions on what travelers can take out of
the Soviet Union have been tightened lately to prevent sorely
needed consumer goods from leaving the shortage-ridden country.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
