<FIRST>u i AM-Poland     12-12 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland,0547</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa: Give Special Powers to Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa proposed
Tuesday that parliament grant special powers to the non-Communist
government to allow it to restructure the economy quickly.
   Walesa's apparently unsolicited proposal came as Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki's Solidarity-dominated Cabinet was completing a
package of economic reform legislation for presentation to
Parliament Sunday.
   Instead of Parliament debating each new law, Walesa proposed in
effect that it give the government broad powers to implement
whatever kind of reform rules it sees as necessary.
   ``The government has not had a chance yet to think about the
(Walesa) statement,'' said deputy government spokesman Henryk
Wozniakowski. ``We are glad for the support which Lech Walesa
extends. ... However it is hard to say how useful this proposal
is.''
   Communist Party spokesman Jan Bisztyga, while not specifically
ruling out Walesa's proposal, said Parliament would be the
``appropriate forum'' for considering economic changes
   Walesa said he was moved to propose special powers in order to
speed up economic reforms.
   ``The situation in the country is getting worse. Time is running
out. The reserve of social trust is nearly expired,'' the union
leader said.
   Prolonged legislative debate would only slow the adoption of the
necessary laws, he said.
   ``That is why one should act quickly and with determination,''
Walesa said. ``I propose giving the government extraordinary
powers'' to address several key issues.
   The powers would apply to legal regulations on restructuring the
economy, changing the property system, breaking up the monopoly of
state-run and cooperative enterprises, and changing the tax and
accounting system, banking and local government structures, Walesa
said.
   He said he was ``fully aware how controversial this proposal is.
But I am forced to make it because of the ever worsening situation
in the country and the growing impatience of society.''
   He said the powers should be set by Parliament for a specified
period and for specific areas of activity. Its two houses _ the
Sejm and Senate _ could then work ``quietly'' on longer term laws,
while retaining the right to correct acts of the government.
   One effect of such powers would be to lessen the voice that the
Communist Party and its formerly allied parties in the parliament
in approving or rejecting specific aspects of economic policy.
   Mazowiecki's government is dominated by supporters of
Solidarity, who account for 12 seats in the 24-member Cabinet. The
Communists have four.
   In the Sejm, however, Solidarity has only 35 percent of the
seats with the Communists holding 37 percent.
   There were signs last week that some of the government's radical
economic programs that threaten the position of party members would
have trouble in the Sejm.
   For instance, some members of the Communist Party and its former
allies spoke against a government bill to break up nationwide
``unions of cooperatives'' dominated by party loyalists.
   The cooperative unions set prices and act as virtual monopolies
in many economic sectors such as the dairy industry and retail food
sales. The government wants to break up the monopolies so that the
dairies and food stores would be forced to compete against one
another.
</TEXT>
