<FIRST>r a AM-DadSentenced     12-12 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dad Sentenced,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dad Sentenced to Prison for Slapping Gas-Sniffing 4-Year-Old</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEARCY, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been sentenced to four years in
prison for slapping his 4-year-old son twice for repeatedly
sniffing gasoline to get high.
   Richard Lewis Vardaman, 42, of Georgetown, was sentenced after
pleading guilty to one count of battery.
   Circuit Judge Cecil Tedder suspended two years of the sentence
on the condition that Vardaman obtain ``intensive psychological
treatment within 60 days'' of his release.
   Defense attorney Bill Mills said he was concerned how the stiff
penalty would affect other parents.
   ``If your child bruises easily and something else happens to
him, are you going to be willing to take him to a hospital for
treatment?'' he asked.
   Prosecutor Chris Raff said Monday that the sentence imposed Dec.
6 was appropriate.
   ``It was a serious case of child abuse,'' Raff said. ``It was
not normal discipline. I think the proof justified the sentence.''
   Mills said a representative of the state Human Services
Department's Division of Children and Family Services had testified
for Vardaman that it was an isolated incident.
   Vardaman, a riverboat pilot, was working on a river somewhere,
``waiting until they find room for him at the penitentiary. He's
resigned himself to the fact he's going to jail,'' the lawyer said.
   In late May, Vardaman caught his son and another boy sniffing
gasoline from a can at the Vardaman home.
   ``He popped both of the boys on their rear ends and told them
not to be doing that,'' Mills said.
   Vardaman found his son sniffing gas again the next morning, from
the gas tank of a lawn mower, Mills said. That afternoon, he said,
Vardaman found his son sniffing gas again.
   ``He slapped him once on each side of the face that time,''
Mills said.
   The boy was ``acting drunk,'' Mills said, and Vardaman and his
wife took him to White County Memorial Hospital at Searcy.
   The boy was acting normal by the time they reached the hospital,
and an emergency room nurse and a doctor noticed facial bruises and
called the police.
   Mills said photographs of the boy taken at the hospital were
shown to the judge. ``They looked pretty bad. The child has a ruddy
complexion and his face was puffy in the picture,'' he said.
</TEXT>
