<FIRST>r i AM-Chile     12-12 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile,0576</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Police Guard Polling Places Before Thursday's Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDUARDO GALLARDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and police guarded polling
stations and strategic points nationwide in preparation for
Thursday's election of a successor to military President Gen.
Augusto Pinochet.
   The campaign officially ended at midnight Monday, and polls
continued to show the opposition with a big lead. Pinochet's
government secretary-general, army Col. Cristian Labbe, promised
``a transparent and normal election.''
   The military is charged with ensuring order during elections,
and 35,000 armed forces members on Tuesday began guarding more than
1,000 polling places and scores of other strategic installations
thoughout the country, including power and communications plants
and public offices.
   The 30,000-man national police also reported stepped-up security
in anticipation of the vote, and Col. Luis Retamal, the force's
spokesman, urged citizens to behave in an orderly manner.
   Army Gen. Carlos Parera, commander of the Santiago garrison and
entrusted with the election security in the area, suspended all
permits to carry weapons until Friday.
   He also said the sale of alcoholic beverages will be banned on
election day, and all public events will be suspended. Theaters
will be closed, he said.
   Similar orders were issued by military commanders throughout the
country.
   Pinochet, the right-wing army commander who seized power in a
bloody 1973 coup, was obliged to call the election after losing a
referendum in October 1988 on a military proposal that he remains
in power until 1997.
   Chile's 7.5 million voters will be asked to pick a new president
and 158 members of the two-chamber Congress. It is the first such
vote in nearly two decades.
   Favorite in the presidential race is Patricio Aylwin, who leads
a 17-party opposition coalition of leftist and centrist groups who
backs improvement in civil liberties and human rights.
   Aylwin, 71, holds a solid lead in all opinion polls over Hernan
Buchi, 40, the government standard-bearer and an ex-finance
minister considered the architect of the country's free-market
economy.
   Wealthy entrepreneur Francisco Javier Errazuriz, an independent,
is expected to finish third. He has promised free health care and
education to all Chileans.
   A last-minute national poll made public Tuesday by the Center
for Studies of Contemporary Reality, a private social research
organization related to the Roman Catholic Church, gave Aylwin 57
percent of the vote, 17.8 percent to Buchi and 15 percent to
Errazuriz.
   But Buchi has rejected the polls' predictions, and in his speech
at Monday's rally said, ``We will give them a big surprise.''
   His campaign headquarters, while admitting Aylwin has a
commanding lead, predicted Tuesday that the front-runner will not
receive more than 50 percent of the vote required to ensure
victory, thus making a runoff election necessary in January or
February.
   Jaime Ravinet, a close aide and spokesman for Aylwin, said ``our
victory is ensured,'' and called all his supporters to a ``big
celebration rally'' in Santiago on Friday afternoon.
   Hours before the remarkably peaceful campaign ended Monday
night, tens of thousands of people filled several blocks of a wide
Santiago avenue in the final Buchi rally. The rally ended with a
series of running skirmishes between police and both supporters and
opponents of Buchi.
   Police, who used water to scatter the demonstrators, said 34
demonstrators were injured, one of them seriously, and 64 were
detained in the incidents, which lasted through late Monday.
</TEXT>
