<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Patriarch     12-12 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Patriarch,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>Roman Catholic Patriarch Warns of Rising Tensions in Holy Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem said
Tuesday that tough Israeli tactics against the Palestinian uprising
could backfire and create increasing insecurity for the Jewish
state.
   Archbishop Michel Sabbah, the first Arab to head the Catholic
church in Jerusalem, said in an interview that he has expressed
this view in meetings with the Ministry of Religious Affairs, his
channel to the Israeli government.
   ``We tell them they are doing wrong,'' Sabbah said. ``Through
all this violence ... they are not achieving any gain for the
Israelis themselves. Instead they are doing the opposite, making
martyrs among the Palestinians. That just helps build strength
among the Palestinian people.''
   Sabbah argued the secure borders desired by Israel cannot be
achieved by continued occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip,
home to 1.7 million Palestinians.
   The territories were captured by Israel from Jordan and Egypt in
the 1967 Middle East War and have been torn for the last two years
by a Palestinian revolt against Israeli rule that has taken more
than 800 lives.
   Asked if he favors an independent Palestinian state, he said
that ``this is a political, a technical issue'' to be left for
negotiations.
   ``The problem is to live free, without being under submission to
anyone else,'' he said. ``Leaders can decide if this requires a
state, a confederation, a federation.''
   Sabbah, 56, was appointed patriarch by the Vatican less than a
month after the Palestinian uprising began in December 1987 and is
responsible for the 65,000 Roman Catholics who live in Jordan,
Cyprus, Israel and the West Bank.
   He was born in Nazareth, now part of Israel, and educated at a
seminary in the West Bank village of Beit Jala and St. Joseph's
University in Lebanon. He earned a doctorate in Arabic linguistics
at the Sorbonne in Paris.
</TEXT>
