<FIRST>r w AM-US-Ethiopia     12-12 0553</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Ethiopia,520</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Promises More Than 100,000 Tons of Food for Ethiopia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Tuesday promised more
than 100,000 metric tons of new food aid to Ethiopia to help soften
the blow of a drought that threatens to be as bad as the 1984
disaster in which an estimated 1 million people died.
   And Mark L. Edelman, acting director of the U.S. Agency for
International Development, welcomed reports that Ethiopia's
hard-line Marxist government will allow a corridor for food aid to
flow to people in the embattled northern provinces of Eritrea and
Tigray.
   ``If it is (true), I am absolutely delighted,'' said Edelman.
``I congratulate President Mengistu for doing it.''
   A severe drought in the two provinces, coupled with what Edelman
called the government's discredited agricultural policies and the
continuing civil war, have placed 5 million people at risk of
starvation, he said.
   ``We are trying to save the people of Ethiopia from their own
government,'' Edelman added.
   ``These numbers suggest we are dealing with a situation at least
as bad as in 1987 and possibly as bad as 1984,'' when a massive but
belated international relief effort failed to head off the deaths
of an estimated 1 million Ethiopians, he said.
   This time, Edelman contended, the U.S. relief agency is ``ahead
of the curve.'' Some 53,800 metric tons of food is arriving from
the United States this month; the additional 111,400 tons approved
Tuesday will put the value of U.S. food aid committed since Oct. 1
at $70 million.
   The aid is to help meet a total need of up to 750,000 metric
tons of food to offset the drought's effects. The Ethiopian
government and the United Nations have put out a worldwide appeal
for help.
   Any relief effort is complicated by the war raging across
northern Ethiopia, where two rebel groups control much of the
territory and where a large expanse extending into two other
provinces, Wello and Gonder, also is contested. Relief officials
are seeking to get all parties in the conflict to establish
corridors where relief vehicles can safely pass battle lines so
that food shipments can reach the drought-stricken area.
   Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi said Tuesday the Addis Ababa
government has agreed to the establishment of corridors, and said
he had asked the rebel groups to do the same.
   The primary corridor sought is a road extending sought from the
Red Sea port of Massawa, which is controlled by the Mengistu
government, into Tigray. A secondary corridor would be established
from the Red Sea port of Aseb southwestward through Wello.
   Edelman said the announcement was being made because it has
recently become apparent that ``the need is going to be much
greater than we thought.''
   ``We do not believe it will be possible to avert starvation in
northern Ethiopia or to prevent large movements of people out of
drought-stricken areas unless such a plan can be implemented,'' he
said.
   Such migrations in the 1984-85 famine led to vast, overcrowded
and unsanitary camps where as many people died from disease as from
hunger.
   ``Now is the time for the government of Ethiopia and the world
community to join together in an urgent, concerted effort to
prevent the human tragedy of another famine in Ethiopia,'' he said.
</TEXT>
