<FIRST>u i AM-Czech-Bilak     12-12 0503</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Bilak,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bilak Denies Responsibility for 1968 Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Czechoslovakia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vasil Bilak, the hard-line
Communist viewed by many here as the most culpable for the 1968
invasion, denied Tuesday that he invited in Soviet-led troops to
crush the ``Prague Spring'' reforms.
   Bilak was charged Monday on two unspecified counts that the
state news agency CTK said were connected with the events of 1968.
   ``According to some opinions, his deeds can be considered
treason,'' CTK said, but added that Bilak would not face trial
because of a 20-year statute of limitation on the alleged crimes.
   Bilak, 72, is a deputy in the national Parliament. During a
break in a parliamentary session, he blamed the Soviet Union for
the invasion, which involved troops of the Red Army and four other
Warsaw Pact nations.
   ``I did not invite them. Do you think I'm so strong that I can
invite five armies and they will come?'' he said.
   Bilak added: ``If I invite you to dinner and you say `No,' then
you don't come. The responsibility is on the one who comes, not the
one who invites. They didn't have to come.''
   He also said the historic context of the invasion had been
forgotten.
   ``It was the peak of the Cold War,'' Bilak said. ``It was
horrible.''
   In similar comments to CTK, Bilak said the invading countries
``faced the threat of World War III.''
   Until the recent reforms, Czechoslovakia maintained _ in
accordance with Soviet views at the time _ that the invasion was
necessary to stop a counterrevolution.
   It has since been declared a mistake and a commission of
historians will investigate it.
   Bilak told CTK that in 1968 it ``was said in Moscow they cannot
tolerate liquidation of something for which 20 million people
died,'' a reference to the Soviets who died defending their country
in World War II.
   The Communist Party daily Pravda in Bilak's native Slovakia said
Tuesday that he brought shame on his party by acquiring a luxurious
villa for a small price after the state invested ten times the sum
to renovate it.
   The villa stands in the exclusive Slavin district of Bratislava,
near the home of Alexander Dubcek, the leader of the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms.
   Bilak was Slovak Communist Party chief under Dubcek, who was
national party head at the time.
   Pravda also noted that Bilak's villa once belonged to Slovak
allies of the Nazis.
   Such gibes once were reserved for opposition leader Vaclav
Havel. His family built a Prague ballroom complex containing an
office used by the Nazis, a fact frequently mentioned in past media
attacks on Havel.
   Asked about the current reforms that have overturned the
hard-line policies he propagated as party ideology chief until
October 1988, Bilak said the move toward democracy was good and bad.
   ``When the people ask for more democracy, more freedom, that's
OK. But when they persecute one another, it subverts the very thing
that is being asked for,'' he said.
</TEXT>
