<HEAD>Officer Reprimanded for Display of Support for Lozano</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rookie police officer was reprimanded for
covering his badge with black tape as a show of support for a
colleague convicted of manslaughter. The symbol usually is reserved
for slain officers.
   ``I felt it was a dishonor to those police officers who had lost
their lives in the line of duty,'' said Police Chief Perry
Anderson. ``To see an officer wearing that for any other reason _
for any other expression _ is unforgiveable.''
   Alejandro Mendez was cited Friday for ``unbecoming conduct'' in
support of William Lozano, convicted last week in the deaths of two
black men.
   The shooting deaths provoked three days of rioting that left one
man dead and more than $1 million damage. Lozano is scheduled to be
sentenced Jan. 24.
   Other officers say Mendez is among many in the police department
who have rallied to Lozano's defense.
   Some officers have signed a petition urging Dade Circuit Judge
Joseph Farina to allow Lozano to remain free on bond pending
appeals.
   ``The police department has to be impartial,'' said Anderson.
``To put something on that's not authorized, to make an officer
stand out to show that he favors or disfavors any kind of action,
would go against the grain of professionalism.''
   Mendez, 22, apologized to the chief.
   ``I didn't mean anything disrespectful,'' he said.
   But the Hispanic Officers Association intends to fight the
reprimand.
   ``I think they're taking away the kid's constitutional right to
express his feelings,'' said Martin Garcia, president of the
368-member association of Miami officers.
