<FIRST>r w AM-EnvironmentalCrimes     12-12 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Environmental Crimes,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Proposes Jailing Those Responsible for Environmental Disasters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen introduced legislation Tuesday
that would jail those responsible for environmental disasters that
cause death, injury or severe damage.
   ``Those who might wreak havoc on our environment should be
scared,'' said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y.
   The bill sponsored by Schumer and Rep. George Gekas, R-Pa.,
would establish punishments ranging from 15 years in jail and a
$250,000 fine for a first offense to 30 years in jail and a $2
million fine for subsequent offenses.
   The bill also would allow the court to sentence an organization
or company convicted of an environmental offense to probation and
require an independent environmental audit. The audit would
identify pollutants and recommend prevention measures the court
could require the defendant to implement.
   The National Resources Defense Council, in testimony before
Schumer's Judiciary subcommittee on criminal justice, said the
legislation is desperately needed and should be made even stronger.
   The American Petroleum Institute, however, called the
legislation flawed and uncessary.
   ``While from time to time it is suggested that enforcement of
one statute or another could be more vigorous, we are not aware of
any suggestions that the current criminal provisions, on the whole
are inadequate to deter irresponsible behavior that endangers the
environment,'' said API Vice President G. William Frick.
   George Van Cleve, deputy assistant attorney general in the
Justice Department, said the Bush administration favors stiffening
punishments for violations of anti-pollution laws.
   However, he said the administration has ``some problems of a
general character'' with the bill, suggesting intergrating concepts
offered by the bill into existing laws.
</TEXT>
