<HEAD>Israeli Patrol Wounds 12 Palestinians in Gaza</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers on a foot patrol shot and wounded 12
Palestinian stone-throwers Tuesday in the Rafah refugee camp in the
occupied Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said.
   In the occupied West Bank, protests flared when the army lifted
a 12-day curfew on Nablus and its surrounding refugee camps and
troops shot and wounded a 25-year-old Palestinian, Arab reporters
said.
   An army spokesman said six Palestinians were reported wounded in
Gaza and that it was investigating the incident in Nablus.
   The army clamped a curfew on Nablus following fierce clashes
after troops killed four Palestinian activists on Dec. 1.
   The army said the four were leaders of the Black Panthers, a
Palestinian gang accused of killing 16 Arabs suspected of
cooperating with Israeli authorities.
   On Tuesday, nearly 120 Palestinians paraded through the casbah,
a marketplace where the group operated, waving the outlawed
Palestine Liberation Organization flag and chanting ``Long live the
Black Panthers!''
   In the old city of Nablus, masked men marched with loudspeakers
shouting warnings to Palestinians who cooperate with Israel, Arab
reporters said.
   The reporters said a patrol fired on protesters in the Rafah
camp, home to 50,000 Palestinians, and wounded 12, including a
10-year-old.
   During the 2-year-old Palestinian uprising against Israeli rule,
Israeli troops and civilians have killed 631 Palestinians; 43
Israelis have died, and Palestinians have killed 155 of their
fellow Arabs on suspicion of collaborating.
   On the political front, Foreign Minister Moshe Arens said
Tuesday he was ``very disappointed'' with Egypt's conditional
acceptance of U.S. Secretary of State James A. Baker III's proposal
for restarting the Mideast peace process.
   ``It was a message from the PLO and not an independent Egyptian
position,'' Arens told reporters in Tel Aviv.
   Arens says peace talks will fail if Israel is found indirectly
negotiating with the PLO through Egypt. Israel views the PLO as a
terrorist organization.
   Arens is to visit Washington in January to meet with Baker and
Foreign Minister Esmet Abdel Meguid of Egypt to discuss the
composition of a Palestinian delegation to negotiations with Israel.
