<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0442</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bill Cosby Leads NBC to Another Ratings Victory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Cosby, who says he wants to come back
for another season at NBC, led the Nielsen television ratings again
for the week ended Dec. 10, according to figures released Tuesday.
   Cosby has told NBC that, contrary to published reports, he was
not considering taking his top-rated comedy series to CBS as part
of the network's attempt to buy Carsey-Werner Co.
   ``The Cosby Show'' was first, closely followed by NBC's
``Cheers.'' ABC's ``Roseanne'' was third.
   NBC won another sweeping victory in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey
with an average rating of 14.2. ABC was second with 11.9 and CBS
third with 11.3. A rating is the percentage of the nation's 92.1
million homes tuned to a show.
   The network is also ahead for the season. The ratings: NBC 15.0,
ABC 13.3, CBS 12.2.
   The Top 10 holds no surprises. NBC's entire Thursday schedule,
plus two comedies from Saturday, are included. ABC has one show and
CBS has two.
   Here's the Top 10: NBC's ``The Cosby Show,'' NBC's ``Cheers,''
ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``A Different World,'' NBC's ``Dear
John,'' NBC's ``The Golden Girls,'' CBS' ``60 Minutes,'' CBS'
``Murder, She Wrote,'' NBC's ``L.A. Law,'' NBC's ``Empty Nest.''
The ``Murder, She Wrote'' episode was a rerun.
   ``Dear John'' may take a dip in the ratings when NBC moves it to
Wednesday in early January and gives its time slot to a new comedy,
``Grand.'' NBC Entertainment president Brandon Tartikoff said at a
televised briefing for affiliate stations Monday that he felt
``Dear John'' was strong enough to survive the move. He added he
felt it would be compatible with ``Night Court.''
   Three of CBS' Monday night comedies showed improved ratings.
``Designing Women'' moved up to 18th place. ``Newhart'' was 21st
and ``Murphy Brown'' was tied for 26th.
   Fox Broadcasting Co.'s highest-rated show continues to be
``Married ... With Children,'' which was 47th. The Fox shows are
down in the ratings since their late summer surge when Fox ran
original shows against network reruns.
   The ``ABC Saturday Mystery Movie'' presentation of ``Christine
Cromwell'' came in 77th, which put it near the bottom.
   ABC was first again in the news ratings with 11.2. CBS was
second with 10.2 and NBC was third with 9.9.
   The lowest-rated network show was ABC's ``The Koppel Report.''
Here are the five bottom network shows: CBS' ``Saturday Night With
Connie Chung'' and ``Snoops'' tied, CBS' ``Top of the Hill,'' ABC's
``Mr. Belvedere,'' ABC's ``Living Dolls'' and ABC's ``The Koppel
Report.''
</TEXT>
