<SECOND>AM-Jordan,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Divert Marchers from U.S. Embassy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMMAN, Jordan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 350 people tried to march on the U.S.
Embassy Tuesday to protest American support of Israel, but police
diverted the procession. There was no violence.
   It was the fourth night in a row that police allowed
demonstrators to assemble and march without a government permit.
Jordan has been under martial law for 22 years and public
demonstrations are banned. The series of marches reflected
government moves to relax restrictions.
   The largest march was held Monday with about 1,000 people
participating.
   The demonstrations have been held to mark the second anniversary
of the Palestinian uprising against the Israeli ocupation of the
West Bank of the Jordan River and Gaza Strip.
   On Tuesday the demonstrators gathered at the Professional Unions
building. Waving Palestinian flags and chanting ``PLO _ Israel
No!'' the crowd moved about 200 yards toward the American Embassy
about two miles away before police barred its way.
   The procession then turned toward the Palestinian-populated
Jebel Hussein neighborhood, with police clearing the streets, and
the marchers dispersed after several hours.
   ``We just want to tell the whole world that there is a
Palestinian society in Amman that's feeling the same as our people
on the West Bank,'' said Bannan M. Kassem, one of the marchers.
   Young men addressed the crowd, vowing support of the uprising
and denouncing U.S. support of Israel and the Israeli peace plan.
   Mohammed Saeed, a veteran Communist Party member who took part
in the march, said there have been occasional demonstrations in
Amman over the years but the last time he could remember so many
marches on consecutive nights was in 1956.
   Prime Minister Mudar Badran and King Hussein have promised to
ease martial-law measures and the government has loosened controls
on the news media.
</TEXT>
