<FIRST>r a AM-Menorah-Vermont     12-12 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Menorah-Vermont,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Rules Display of Menorah Unconstitutional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ruled Tuesday that the
display of a 16-foot menorah in a Burlington, Vt., park is
unconstitutional because it violates the separation of church and
state.
   In a 2-1 decision, the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
reversed a lower court's decision allowing the city to issue a
permit to a Jewish group to erect the menorah in a park next to
City Hall.
   The menorah, the symbol of the Jewish religious holiday
Hanukkah, was displayed during the holiday season in 1986, 1987 and
1988. The 16-foot-high, 12-foot-wide candelabrum bore a sign saying
it was sponsored by Lubavitch of Vermont, a group of Orthodox Jews.
   The appeals judges based their decision on a U.S. Supreme Court
ruling in July that a creche inside a Pittsburgh courthouse was not
permissible but a menorah in front of a nearby government building
was because it was paired with a Christmas tree.
   Judges Edward J. Lumbard and Wilfred Feinberg said the high
court's ruling ``teaches that the display of a menorah on
government property in this case conveys a message of government
endorsement of religion.''
   In a dissenting opinion, Judge Thomas Meskill said he did not
agree that the placement of the menorah next to City Hall gave the
impression that the display was government sponsored.
   ``Rather, the denial of permission to display the menorah would
constitute unnecessary hostility toward religion,'' Meskill said.
   Burlington City Attorney Joseph E. McNeil said he had not yet
seen the decision and could not say whether the city would appeal.
   The ruling stemmed from a lawsuit brought by a lawyer, a rabbi
and a Protestant minister living in Burlington which challenged the
display.
   ``Our reasoning was that it was a clear violation of church and
state, mainly because of its position with City Hall in the
background,'' said plaintiff Mark A. Kaplan, a lawyer who is on the
board of directors of the Vermont chapter of the American Civil
Liberties Union.
   The appeal followed a ruling in December 1988 by U.S. District
Judge Franklin S. Billings Jr. of Vermont who said the city could
issue a permit for the display.
   Kaplan, whose office is adjacent to City Hall Park in
Burlington, said the menorah is not on display now.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
