<FIRST>r a AM-HomelessSearch     12-12 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Homeless Search,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Hands Out Money to Homeless in Search of Possible Relative</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent corporate lawyer handed out $100
bills to the homeless as he searched in vain through a group living
under a freeway for a woman who may be a distant relative.
   ``I've got to find her,'' said Joe Jamail, who is best known for
winning a multibillion-dollar lawsuit for Pennzoil Co. ``I don't
want to sound like I'm some sort of grandstanding ham, but I want
to help that woman.''
   Joanne Jamail, 73, apparently was placed in a motel the night
before by a church group trying to get her out of the cold,
according to other homeless people at the highway encampment.
   Jamail first learned about the woman after she was interviewed
last week by The Houston Post under the freeway, where she has
lived for five months.
   ``I really need to find her if I can,'' Jamail said Monday. ``I
think I found Joanne a job working as a nanny for a friend of mine,
but I need to find her as soon as I can.''
   The 90-pound woman told the Post that her late husband, John
Joseph Jamail, had told her he was a distant cousin of Jamail.
   Jamail said Monday he had never heard of the couple, but that he
was eager to meet the woman to explore the possible family ties.
   The woman said she had to move out of her Galveston boarding
home after Hurricane Chantal tore the roof off this summer. She
said she couldn't find another place to live on her $205-a-month
Social Security check, and eventually wound up in Houston.
   She never called Jamail because she didn't want to ``impose'' on
him, she said.
   A circuslike atmosphere surrounded Jamail as he clutched a
fistful of $100 bills during his brief visit Monday to the downtown
area where the woman had lived.
   As he gave one man a bill for an apartment deposit he said, ``If
that's not enough, you let me know. And you let me know the minute
you hear or see Joanne.''
   Jamail represented Pennzoil when it won an $11 billion jury
award in its lawsuit against Texaco Inc. The two companies later
agreed on a $3 billion settlement.
</TEXT>
