<FIRST>u w AM-Salvador-Casolo     12-12 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Casolo,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Ambassador Urges Casolo to Cooperate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Salvadoran ambassador to the United States
said Tuesday that American Jennifer Casolo would likely be released
if she cooperated with police in an investigation of a suspected
rebel arms cache.
   Ambassador Miguel Angel Salaverria told reporters after a
briefing with Rep. Nancy Johnson, a Republican from Casolo's home
state of Connecticut, that the woman may have been unaware of arms
hidden in the backyard of her San Salvador apartment.
   But he said, ``She needs to say who she rented the house from.
... The more she cooperates, the easier it will be to end the
case.''
   Rumors of Casolo's impending release reached Washington Tuesday
_ generated by comments from her Salvadoran lawyer _ but the judge
handling the case said there was a ``misunderstanding'' and he had
made no such decision.
   In another development, White House press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater apologized for remarks made last month shortly after
Casolo's arrest by Salvadoran police.
   ``It's fairly clear that these weapons were found there,''
Fitzwater said at the time. ``I mean, we're not talking about a
small package of pistols here. ... This is hardly a case of someone
having a few things flipped in their shopping bag on the way home.''
   Congressional Democrats blasted Fitzwater for making comments
they said indicated to the Salvadoran government that the Bush
administration supported prosecution of the case.
   On Tuesday, Fitzwater denied that he had suggested Casolo was
guilty but added, ``I certainly apologize to anyone who feels that
they were offended by that.''
   Casolo, 28, went to El Salvador in 1985 to work for Christian
Education Seminars, a group dedicated to influencing U.S. policy by
organizing tours for Americans to learn about the civil war there.
   She and two Salvadoran friends were arrested Nov. 26 after a
police raid at her house. From the walled garden behind the house,
police said they uncovered 103 mortar grenades, 213 blocks of
dynamite, 405 detonators, 150 feet of slow-burning fuse and 21,945
rounds of ammunition for Soviet-made automatic rifles.
   She is being held for 90 days pending an investigation into
possible links between her, the explosives and Salvadoran rebel
forces.
</TEXT>
