<FIRST>r w AM-Grain-Soviets     12-12 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grain-Soviets,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Buy More Corn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Private exporting companies have sold the
Soviet Union an additional 103,632 metric tons of U.S. corn for
delivery in 1989-90 under a long-term supply agreement, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   The department said the corn was shifted by exporters from
``unknown destinations'' to the Soviet Union.
   Orders since Oct. 1, the beginning of the agreement's new year,
now total 160,700 tons of soybeans, 705,000 tons of soybean meal,
and 7,300 tons of barley.
   U.S. grain sales to Moscow in 1988-89 were a record of more than
21.7 million tons, more than 16.3 million tons of corn and nearly
5.4 million tons of wheat.
   In addition, 1988-89 sales included 298,700 tons of soybeans,
1.35 million tons of soybean meal and 1.02 million tons of grain
sorghums.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 103,632 tons of
corn would be about 4.1 million bushels.
   The new sales were made by unidentified private exporting
companies, which are required to report large sales to the
department. No selling prices or further details were released.
   Corn prices have been averaging about $2.22 per bushel at the
farm level, according to the department's five-day average, meaning
that the latest sale could have a farm value of about $9 million.
</TEXT>
