<SECOND>AM-UN-Nicaragua,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Pollwatchers Hit Use of TV by Sandinistas, Opposition</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Nicaraguan government and the
opposition have waged a dirty election campaign over the airwaves,
a U.N. report said Tuesday.
   U.N. pollwatchers, led by former U.S. Attorney General Elliot L.
Richardson, said the Sandinista government identifies ``the entire
opposition coalition'' with ousted strongman Anastasio Somoza's
National Guard and with ``counterrevolution, war and death.''
   The report criticized the opposition for contending that ``fraud
will be the only possible explanation for defeat'' in the election
set for February.
   ``In this atmosphere of anticipated fraud and the mixing of war
with politics, the electoral process is liable to lose its central
position,'' said the report by Richardson.
   ``If armed conflict emerges, even implicitly, as a possible
solution, the electoral process is bound to be perceived as a
secondary solution,'' he warned.
   On Sunday, an opposition rally in Masatepe, Nicaragua, broke
into a riot in which one person was killed and more than 20
injured. Foreign observers blamed the violence on Sandinista
provocateurs.
   ``Policy debate or genuine political proposals take backstage to
volleys of accusations and epithets,'' Richardson said in his
report, filed beforele
registered to vote, 88.5 percent of the potential electorate.
   Richardson credits Nicaragua's Supreme Election Council with
maintaining an ``impartial and flexible attitude'' in interpreting
election laws governing the campaign.
   The Sandinistas came to power in a July 1979 revolution that
overthrew the Somoza regime.
