<DOCNO> AP891212-0138 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Anti-DrugActivists     12-12 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Anti-Drug Activists,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Community Activists Share Tactics at Anti-Drug Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Community activists from across the nation
Tuesday swapped experiences and strategies from their often
isolated wars on narcotics at a conference dedicated to creating
``drug-free'' neighborhoods in the 1990s.
   The three-day conference ending Wednesday includes workshops on
substance abuse and prevention, drugs in schools and anti-drug
legislation.
   More important for some of the estimated 500 people in
attendance, it was an opportunity for encouragement and frank talk
about the challenges of battling an epidemic.
   ``The purpose is to indicate that no one in any state, in any
city, in any municipality is working on this problem by
themselves,'' said the Rev. Joseph Kakalec, a Philadelphia
activist. ``To encourage each other to go back to the communities
and take back the neighborhoods.''
   Jaci Feldman, director of drug programs for the National
Training and Information Center, said she hopes activists will
return to their communities with new tactics for the grassroots
drug war.
   Those attending the conference sponsored by the Chicago-based
center also worked on model legislation that, among other things,
would require a percentage of money seized from drug dealers be
returned to community organizations.
   Elsewhere, national drug czar William Bennett made rock n' roll
the medium of his anti-drug message Tuesday when he jammed on an
electric guitar for about 200 twisting and shouting junior high
students in Manchester, N.H.
   ``This combines two very interesting aspects of society _ the
principle of law and the principle of rock n' roll,'' Bennett told
the students as he joined a Manchester Police Department rock band
that carries an anti-drug message to schools.
   Bennett made sure the seventh and eighth graders from St. Joseph
Regional Jr. High School would remember him when he picked up the
rhythm guitar for a version of ``Twist and Shout'' with the band
``Friends in Blue.''
   At an earlier appearance in Concord, N.H., Bennett said he
approved taking custody away from addicted parents in extreme cases.
   ``Obviously, you give parents _ you give anybody _ the chance to
recover, to get better,'' Bennett said in an interview. ``But,
supposing the parent isn't getting better, shows no interest in
improving, going into treatment and it's adversely and dramatically
affecting the well-being of the child? The state can intervene.''
   At the Chicago meeting, groups new at fighting narcotics dealing
and veteran organizations discussed their problems and victories.
   Donna Jones, leader of a fledgling anti-drug group in Waterloo,
Iowa, talked with Herman Wrice, a Drexel University professor who
with several others began marching on crack houses in Philadelphia
two years ago.
   Mrs. Jones' group held their first anti-drug march a week ago
with about 100 people. Wrice began attacking crack houses with a
sledgehammer and a handful of supporters and now has a coalition
that involves at least 60 organizations who walk drug-infested
neighborhoods each week.
   It will take the involvement of community residents, not police
or the courts to rid the neighborhoods of drugs, Wrice said.
   ``You can stay inside your home and pretend how dangerous it is
and they'll (drug dealers) come to your house and take you on,'' he
said.
   The National Training and Information Center has previously
worked with organizations on issues including housing, utilities
and health care.
   Last spring, the non-profit center began administering a
federally funded program in nine cities to develop community
strategies for battling drugs. Representatives from each group
attended the conference to discuss their progress.
   Ms. Feldman said community residents were ignored for too long
in the drug war.
   ``They are the eyes and ears of their community, they know
what's going on in their community,'' she said.
   But increasingly authorities are encouraging the involvement of
community activists, and the involvement is growing, Ms. Feldman
said.
   ``What I've been hearing the last two days is `I'm tired of
feeling like a prisoner in my own home ... I have to get out of my
house and do something,''' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
