<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Libya     12-12 0226</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Libya,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Prosecutor Widens Chemical Arms Plant Probe</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANNHEIM, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal prosecutors have expanded
their investigation into allegations that West German companies
helped Libya build a chemical weapons plant outside Tripoli, an
official said Tuesday.
   Peter Wechsung of the federal prosecutor's office in Mannheim
said criminal probes were opened against three high-level employees
of Salzgitter Industriebau AG.
   He told The Associated Press that Andreas Boehm, Salzgitter's
project manager for what Libya describes as a civilian
pharmaceutical plant, is suspected of violating West German laws
forbidding export of materials that can be used for chemical
weapons.
   Formal probes were opened against two other employees suspected
of giving false testimony to investigators.
   Wechsung said prosecutors are ``proceeding from the assumption''
that the plant was designed for making chemical weapons. He said it
was ``hardly conceivable'' no one among about 100 people involved
in the project at Salzgitter knew the plant's ``real function.''
   The United States said last year that the plant in the Libyan
desert at Rabta, about 60 miles from Tripoli, was intended to
produce poison gas.
   West German investigations of the Imhausen Chemie company, based
at Lahr in the Black Forest, led to charges against company
president Juergen Hippenstiel-Imhausen. Washington said the firm
masterminded the project.
   Salzgitter was mentioned as one of the companies providing
materials for the Libyan project.
</TEXT>
