<FIRST>r w AM-CableInquiry     12-12 0201</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Inquiry,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Opens Study</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission on
Tuesday formally opened its congressionally mandated study of
competition in cable television and said it plans to complete the
job three months early.
   The 1984 legislation directing the commission to undertake the
study required a report by Oct. 28, 1990. The commission said
Tuesday it intends to submit its results by July 31.
   The commission adopted a ``notice of inquiry,'' the step by
which government regulatory agencies tell their regulated
industries what they plan to do.
   The notice adopted Tuesday asked for facts and studies about the
industry, recommendations for new rules or changes in existing
rules and recommendations for legislation.
   It also sought comments on, among other things, rates and the
possible regulation of rates, quality of service, competition and
the desirability of a possible requirement that every community
with cable service be assured that two companies would compete to
offer it.
   There have been complaints in Congress that cable companies have
been jacking up their rates to excessive levels.
   The National Cable Television Association said it welcomed the
notice and believed ``the industry has a positive story to tell.''
</TEXT>
