<HEAD>Fishing Boat Finds Part From Missing Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NARRAGANSETT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Part of a door frame from a commuter
plane missing with eight people aboard was dragged up in a fishing
boat's net Tuesday, rekindling hope of finding more of the plane,
which disappeared two weeks ago.
   ``It has been identified as a piece of a door frame from that
aircraft,'' said Ted Lopatkiewicz, a National Transportation Safety
Board spokesman in Washington, D.C.
   The aluminum piece was found in about 130 feet of water, he
said. The Coast Guard said it was just outside an area of Block
Island Sound where a sonar-equipped boat had spent six days
searching for the plane.
   Lt. Hank Leeper, who has been in charge of the search, said
divers were ready to check the bottom if scanning by a
sonar-equipped boat indicated there was larger wreckage.
   The New England Airlines plane has been missing since taking off
from Block Island on Nov. 28 for a 17-mile flight to the mainland.
   Debris found later, including part of a cabin panel and the
bodies of two dogs belonging to a passenger, indicated the
twin-engine plane broke up.
