<FIRST>r i AM-Paraguay     12-12 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paraguay,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers Fire on Striking Workers; 2 Killed, 10 Wounded</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEDRO SERVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers opened fire Tuesday on
striking workers from the giant Itaipu Dam hydroelectric project,
killing two and wounding 10, the private station Radio Nanduti
reported.
   There was no immediate word from the government.
   The station's correspondent on the scene, 240 miles east of the
capital Asuncion, said the incident occurred when strikers tried to
prevent workers from entering the complex, jointly owned with
Brazil, on the Parana River.
   Hundreds of soldiers and anti-riot police from nearby Ciudad del
Este tried to disperse the strikers, who responded by throwing
stones.
   The strike began 15 days ago over pay and benefit demands by
employees. The strike was declared illegal by the Labor Ministry,
and dam officials said employees who refused to work would be fired.
   The incident was denounced by opposition political leaders.
   ``Not even in the worst periods of government by (former
President) Alfredo Stroessner did the army repress in this
manner,'' said Mina Feliciangeli, president of the leftist Workers
Party.
   Stroessner ruled this landlocked South American nation for
nearly 34 years until he was overthrown in a Feb. 3 coup. Coup
leader Gen. Andres Rodriguez was elected president last May 1.
   Itaipu Dam, one of the largest hydroelectric projects in the
world, has cost $18 billion since construction began in 1974 and
the first energy was delivered two years ago.
   At the peak of construction, the project employed 20,000 people.
Currently, 5,000 workers from both countries are employed.
</TEXT>
