<FIRST>u i AM-Bulgaria 1stLd-Writethru a0604 12-12 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0604,0787</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politburo Member Asks Why System Breeds Dictators, Bulgarians Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with denunciation of former party
leadership, quotes, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SOF4</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Congress, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly elected Politburo member Alexander
Lilov told a major Communist assembly on Tuesday, ``The most
important question to ask is why the system breeds dictators and
why it tolerates them for so long.''
   His surprising comments came as he and others denounced the
demoted party leadership at a key session of the Bulgarian
Communist Party's policy-setting Central Committee. New personal
attacks were made against disgraced longtime leader Todor Zhivkov
as thousands rallied for further reforms.
   About 20,000 Bulgarians stood in a candlelight vigil in the
plaza outside, making clear they would keep up pressure for fast
and effective political change despite new party chief Petar
Mladenov's promises of reform.
   Mladenov proposed on Monday, opening day of the closed-door
meeting, that the party give up its guaranteed monopoly on power
and talk with independent groups. He also proposed free elections
by May 1990.
   The developments came a month after Zhivkov was ousted after a
35-year regime. Mladenov, formerly foreign minister, took office
when Zhivkov and his Stalinist old guard were forced out Nov. 10.
   Georgi Grigorov, newly elected first secretary of the Sofia city
committee, told Tuesday's meeting the party was ``beheaded in terms
of personnel'' _ in desperate need of competent economic managers
and ideologists.
   Lilov, voted into the ruling Politburo on Friday after Zhivkov
kept him away from the power center for years, said Zhivkov's
legacy was ``a degradation of party principles and ethnics,'' the
state news agency BTA reported.
   He renewed calls for punishment of Zhivkov and his closest
associates.
   ``The culprits for this crisis'' should be named and ``held
politically and, in some cases, criminally liable,'' BTA quoted
Lilov as saying, meaning they should be tried in court.
   Premier Georgi Atanasov echoed Mladenov, who on Monday gave a
grim account of Bulgaria's crisis-ridden economy. Bulgaria, with a
population of 8.9 million, is saddled with an overall Western debt
of about $10 billion.
   ``We can hardly point to a sub-branch and even a single
production which is competitive on the free international
markets,'' said Atanasov, who took over as prime minister in 1986.
   The candlelight vigil was the third such quiet demonstration in
two days.
   Some put their candles on window ledges of the Central Committee
headquarters _ ``because it's right under their noses,'' two young
men explained. A guard soon came, blew out the candles and threw
them away.
   One demonstrator declared: ``It's right under their temple.
Let's hope sooner or later we are going to bring that temple down.''
   Earlier Tuesday, 3,000 assembled in the plaza for a daylight
vigil.
   Deyan Kiuranov, a spokesman for the influential environmental
group Eco-Glasnost, said Tuesday the party ``regained some face''
through Mladenov's speech. On Monday, Eco-Glasnost became the first
officially registered independent group in Bulgaria.
   Kiurianov told Western reporters he thought independent groups
would accept Mladenov's offer of immediate dialogue.
   At a rally on Sunday, more than 50,000 people cheered calls for
the entire Central Committee to resign.
   Independent groups that sponsored the demonstration have called
for ``round table'' talks with the Communist leadership, like those
held in Poland last spring and East Germany this month.
   Kiuranov also is active in the new Union of Democratic Forces
alliance of 10 independent groups, and said it would ``play a very
active political role'' in the elections Mladenov proposed.
   He conceded little time remained for the opposition to organize,
but predicted early elections would ``act as a unifying force'' for
his alliance.
   Some people questioned in the street were skeptical of
Mladenov's ability to separate himself from the Zhivkov regime,
where he spent 18 years as foreign minister.
   ``I could trust Mladenov if he gained the peoples' trust,'' said
a housepainter, who would not give his name. If the new leader
``doesn't get rid of those around him, the people won't trust
him,'' he said.
   Many people, conditioned by the distrust and fear of two
generations, refused to speak.
   Mladnov proposed Monday that a special party congress be held
March 26 and the current term of the entire party leadership end at
that time, which would be tantamount to collective resignation.
   Kiuranov described that as ``a halfway step'' to meeting
opposition demands, ``but also a halfway step to counter them.''
   Since taking office, Mladenov has reorganized the party's ruling
Politburo twice to remove hard-liners who served under Zhivkov.
</TEXT>
