<HEAD>Excerpts from Statement by Central American Presidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Central America, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are excerpts from the
statement issued Tuesday at the end of a conference by five Central
Central American presidents, as translated from the Spanish by The
Associated Press:
   Presidents Oscar Arias of Costa Rica, Alfredo Cristiani of El
Salvador, Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala, Jose Azcona Hoyo of Honduras
and Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua:
   _Ratified ``their most energetic condemnation of armed and
terrorist actions mounted by irregular forces in the region'' and
reiterated ``their deepest conviction that it is imperative for
people to understand the use of force and terror to attain
political objectives must be discarded.''
   _Expressed their support of Salvadoran President Alfredo
Cristiani and his government as a product of ``democratic,
pluralist and participative processes.''
   _``Energetically demanded'' that the Salvadoran rebels _ the
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front or FMLN _ ``renounce all
violence that directly or indirectly affects the civilian
population.''
   _Reiterated their ``vehement call to the FMLN to immediately
cease hostilities in this brother nation and incorporate themselves
into the process of dialogue.''
   _Reiterated ``the importance of international cooperation as a
parallel and indispensable element in the political attempt to
pacify the area'' and asked the secretary general of the United
Nations ``to establish the necessary links for more direct
involvement in the peace effort of those states with interests in
the region.''
   _Declared the recently dispatched U.N. observer force should
``accelerate its activities to prevent the delivery of arms to the
FMLN and the Nicaraguan Resistance'' and should ``immediately
initiate actions to demobilize the FMLN'' and Nicaraguan rebels.
   _Noted that Nicaragua had reitereated its offer ``to allow
Contras (rebels) who repatriate before Feb 5, 1990, to register (to
vote) in order to exercise their suffrage in the Feb. 25 general
elections.''
   _Offered their support for Nicaragua's call for U.S. funds for
the Contras to be used to ``carry out the demobilization,
repatriation or voluntary relocation in Nicaragua or third
countries of members of the Nicaraguan Resistance and their
families.''
