<FIRST>r w AM-US-Czechoslovakia     12-12 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Czechoslovakia,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human Rights Talk Postponed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prague's rollback of communist rule prompted
cancellation of a planned U.S.-Czechoslovak meeting on humanitarian
affairs next week, both sides said Tuesday.
   The session may be rescheduled once Czechoslovakia's new
government _ the first in 40 years not under communist domination _
frames its policies, they said.
   Deputy Foreign Minister Evzen Vacek was to have met next Monday
with Richard Schifter, assistant secretary of state for
humanitarian affairs and and other U.S. officials in a continuing
dialogue on human rights issues.
   ``We suggested they not meet'' until Czechoslovakia completes
its internal changes, said State Department spokesman David Burgess.
   At the Czechoslovak Embassy the meeting was described as
``postponed,'' and spokesman Karel Tregler said ``It is necessary
to re-prepare negotiations ... the humanitarian cases have been
solved.''
   Schifter told Czechoslovakia's government director of religious
affairs, Vladimir Janku, at an October meeting, that the price for
improvement of relations with the United States was that ``human
rights conditions improve dramatically'' in the Central European
country.
   This has indeed been happening the past month, said a State
Department expert.
   ``Many of the human rights considerations have been dealt with
constructively ... they have achieved a fantastic amount in a few
weeks. The situation is very improved, they have freed many
political prisoners, codified free speech and religion,'' he said,
talking on condition of anonymity.
   Czechoslovakia's former government entered the U.S. talks as
part of a campaign to attract American investment and technology
and to receive U.S. tariff concessions on its goods known as Most
Favored Nation treatment, similar to those sought by the Soviet
Union.
   The campaign has continued amid political change in Prague. A
deputy trade minister, Jiri Nemec, restated his country's desire tp
strengthen economic relations during talks last week at the State
and Commerce departments, the embassy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
