<FIRST>r a AM-SubCommanders     12-12 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sub Commanders,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Nuclear Submarine Commandos Replaced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four nuclear submarine commanders have been
replaced this year over leadership difficulties, according to a
Navy spokeswoman.
   Two of the commanders, including USS Houston commanding officer
John H. Sohl III, were relieved for cause, a formal procedure that
can bar future sea command.
   Sohl was relieved of his command Friday and given a punitive
letter of reprimand after his submarine cut its towed sonar cable
while attempting to avoid striking an obstacle, Lt. Susan Haeg said
Monday.
   Sohl also was aboard the submarine when it snagged the tow cable
of a civilian tug off Long Beach in May. One of the tug's three
crew members died.
   Also relieved from his post was Cmdr. John C. Bickford,
commanding officer of the Gurnard. The submarine ran aground off
San Diego in May.
   The commanders of two other nuclear-powered attack submarines
were transferred to other duties ahead of schedule because of poor
performance, Rear Adm. David Oliver said Monday.
   He would not name them because the action had not involved
punishment.
   Oliver reached his decision on Bickford after reviewing the
Gurnard's grounding. He also relieved the quartermaster who was on
duty at the time, but would not identify the sailor.
   The Houston was involved in incidents almost monthly starting in
May, including the sinking of the tug Barcona, a flooding incident,
a small fire and an incident with a torpedo.
   Besides the high number of command changes during his command of
Submarine Group 5, Oliver said he has formally requested that
navigation teams assigned to nuclear submarines undergo a thorough
overhaul of duties and personnel.
   Oliver said his reorganization proposal includes the removal of
certain types of enlisted sailors from submarine navigation teams
and new methods for keeping the vessels safe from navigation
dangers.
</TEXT>
