<HEAD>Jamaica's Gas Station Strike Makes for Long Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strike by gasoline retailers closed
most filling stations across this Caribbean nation for the second
day Tuesday, causing long lines at the few stations open and a drop
in student and worker attendance.
   The Jamaica Gasoline Retailers' Association and the government
are at odds over paying retroactive profit margin increases of four
cents a gallon.
   Gasoline costs $1.67 a gallon here.
   Energy Minister Hugh Small said the strike would harm the winter
tourist season and was ``jeopardizing the standard of living of all
people in Jamaica.''
