<FIRST>r i AM-Pantheon     12-12 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pantheon,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Revolutionary Priest, Two Others, Enshrined in Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of revolutionary priest Henri Gregoire
were enshrined in the Pantheon Tuesday along with those of a
philosopher and a mathematician in the last official event of
France's bicentennial year.
   President Francois Mitterrand attended the ceremony in the
former Left Bank church where France honors its heros, but the
event was boycotted by French church leaders who feel the priest
was something less than a hero.
   The priest, better known as Abbe Gregoire, was known for his
fight against slavery, but he also proposed the abolition of the
monarchy and backed a controversial oath to the state that the
clergy were forced to take.
   Moved to the Pantheon at the same time were Jean-Antoine
Caritat, Marquis de Concorcet, a friend of Voltaire and other
philosophers; and Gaspard Monge, inventor of descriptive geometry.
Both were active in the French revolution.
   Pope John Paul II was represented by the papal nuncio, Lorenzo
Antonetti.
   The French church has not forgotten the revolution's massacres
of priests and desecration of churches.
   ``The Abbe Gregoire defended a conception of the church which
differs from the Catholic tradition,'' Cardinal Jean-Marie
Lustiger, archbishop of Paris, said in a newspaper interview before
the ceremony.
</TEXT>
