<FIRST>u i AM-France-Comoros 1stLd-Writethru a0688 12-12 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-Comoros, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0688,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Navy Ships in Comoros Area Leave on Mystery Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout UPDATING with French ships leaving for unknown
destination, other developments. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four French naval vessels that make up the special
evacuation force for the Comoros left France's Indian Ocean port of
Mayotte early Wednesday for an unknown destination, Agence
France-Presse reported.
   The French assembled the vessels and a force of about 800
sailors and soldiers to evacuate the 1,600 French citizens who live
in the Comoros if necessary.
   President Ahmed Abdallah Abderrahmane of the Comoros was
assassinated on Nov. 26. Since then, the archipelago off East
Africa has been under the control of the 600-man presidential
guard, led by French mercenary Bob Denard and about 30 Europeans.
   Defense Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenement said Monday that
France, the former colonial power, had no intention of intervening
militarily in the Comoros, but was preparing for any eventuality.
   Wednesday's sailing clearly was aimed at putting pressure on
Denard and his men. Both France and South Africa, the countries
providing the largest amount of aid to the islands, have cut off
all aid to the Comoros until Denard leaves. Denard has denied
involvement in the assassination.
   The naval group included the supply ship Marne, serving as
flagship; the escort vessel Protet; the light supply vessel La
Grandiere, and the destroyer La Boudeuse, the French news agency
said. It quoted a French military spokesman in Mayotte as saying
the ships left there at 4 a.m. (8 p.m. EST Wednesday).
   Mayotte is in the Comoro chain but is administered by France.
   The spokesman, Col. Philippe Charrier, did not reveal the
mission of the military force.
   AFP quoted military sources in Mayotte as saying the force would
anchor about 45 miles off Grande Comore island, site of the
archipelago's capital, Moroni.
   It was Denard who installed Abdallah in power in a 1978 coup,
and who has been a force in the Comoros ever since.
   The French news agency said France, working with South Africa,
has opened discreet negotiations with the French mercenary to
obtain his departure.
   Denard hinted at a news conference Tuesday night that he would
leave the Comoros, saying he could not ``resist two superpowers,''
referring to France and South Africa. He said Abderrahmane was
killed accidentally by his bodyguard, a Sgt. Jaffar.
   The conservative newspaper Le Figaro reported Tuesday that the
60-year-old Denard said he and his men will be happy to leave the
Comoros if the price is right and the arrangements are honorable.
   Since the assassination, Justice Said Mohammed Djohar of the
Supreme Court has been acting president. He has made no public
appeal for French aid to drive out Denard and his men.
</TEXT>
