<FIRST>d e BC-Dance     12-12 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dance,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ailey Company Dances Exciting New Work</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American premiere of ``Episodes'' by the
Alvin Ailey American Dance Theater on Tuesday was total excitement
_ fast, violent movement and embraces that last a second before the
partipants saunter away.
   Ulysses Dove, former dancer in the company, who made his
choreographic debut with the company in 1979, choreographed
``Episodes.'' It was originally performed by the London Festival
Ballet and Ballet Francais de Nancy. Dove rechoreographed it for
the Ailey dancers.
   The original score is by Robert Ruggieri. It is full of
explosive percussion and references to ``musique concrete.''
Dancers are dressed sexy, men in black, bare-shoulder leotards,
women in short black skirts, bare legs and feet, hair flying around.
   Sometimes the four women look like Tina Turner in full concert
frenzy. Sometimes the five men look like advertisements for muscled
shoulders and arms.
   ``Episodes'' begins with two men exploding onto the stage,
jumping in, then whirling, to crashes of drums. A woman jumps in,
caught by one of the men. When she stretches her palm toward his
face, he falls to the ground. A man decks a woman by touching his
hand on her shoulder. All the way through, violence is only
suggested.
   Images stay in the memory. As a man walks away after a brief
embrace, the woman twirls in front of him. He picks her up like a
sack of flour and hands her off to another man.
   Sometimes lighting by John B. Read, is semidark, other times
there are three circles of light for dancers to explore, other
times an X of light crosses the stage.
   There are episodes in ``Episodes'' when hands are held like
fists but it seems more tense than angry. There is one instance of
jealousy when a woman steps between a man and a woman approaching
him but generally ``Episodes'' is unemotional. Dove started it on a
high pitch and keeps it there. Dancers are lucky there are nine so
two or three can run, change direction and dart forward while the
others, presumably, are panting in the wings.
   It certainly is exciting.
   Dancers were Renee Robinson, Elizabeth Roxas, Neisha Folkes,
Debora Chase, Desmond Richardson, Stephen Smith, Dwight Rhoden,
Wesley Johnson III and Dereque Whiturs.
   The evening began with ``Landscape,'' which Ailey choreographed
in 1981 to Bela Bartok's ``Piano Concerto No. 3,'' and ended with
George Faison's 1971 ``Suite Otis,'' danced to recordings by Otis
Redding.
   The company is at the City Center through Dec. 31.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0171 </DOCNO>
