<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Summit 1stLd-Writethru a0759 12-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0759,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Summit to be Held in Cartagena in February</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with background, details from Washington,
minor editing. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A drug summit to be attended by
President Bush and the leaders of the three major Latin American
drug-producing countries will take place next February in
Cartagena, Colombia, a U.S. official said Tuesday.
   An advance team left Washington late Monday to prepare for the
meeting.
   Bernard Aronson, assistant secretary of state for inter-American
affairs, told a news conference in this capital that the U.S.
government had accepted Cartagena as the summit site.
   President Virgilio Barco had suggested the Caribbean port 680
miles north of Bogota as the meeting place despite U.S. concerns
over security.
   Presidents Barco, Bush, Jaime Paz Zamora of Bolivia and Alan
Garcia of Peru will attend the summit.
   Ever since Barco declared an anti-narcotics war after a leading
presidential candidate was assassinated on Aug. 18, Colombia has
undergone a wave of killings, including a bombing last week that
claimed 63 lives.
   Officials also blame drug barons for the bombing of a Colombian
jetliner on a domestic flight Nov. 27 that killed all 107 people
aboard.
   Aronson, speaking to reporters at the residence of U.S.
Ambassador Thomas McNamara, confirmed the summit would take place
in February but said he could not give exact date, adding that the
Barco administration would have to set it.
   Bush has repeatedly praised the efforts of the Barco government
to fight the drug lords in the face of all-out violence.
   Colombia, Peru and Bolivia all receive U.S. aid that is tied to
the progress of their anti-drug efforts.
   The Bush administration would like to see more done to provide
economic alternatives to farmers whose lives depend on the coca
crop.
   The drug summit is expected to discuss crop substitution, U.S.
aid, and cooperation in the fields of money-laundering,
intelligence and extradition.
   The State Department reported to Congress last July that
negligible progress had been made in reducing coca production
despite spending of $100 million over 17 years. Production
increased every year, the department said.
   The office of William Bennett, director of the U.S. Office of
National Drug Control Policy, estimates 1988 coca production at 275
tons in Peru, 176 tons in Bolivia and 54 tons in Colombia, whose
drug traffickers process the crop grown in the other two countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
