<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrashTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0662 12-12 0580</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>NASA, Ford Officials Testify in Bus Crash Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with testimony by NASA fire safety engineer,
edits to conform. No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto XCRL2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROB WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many of the 27 children and adults killed
in a fiery bus crash could have survived if their seats had been
fire resistant and the bus's fuel tank had been improved, defense
witnesses testified Tuesday.
   Safety issues dominated the 13th day of testimony in the murder
and drunken-driving trial of Larry Mahoney, driver of the pickup
truck that collided head-on with the church bus south of this Ohio
River town on May 14, 1988.
   Eugene Sober, a fire safety engineer with the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, said the 1977 Ford bus' seat
cushions and covers burn rapidly and emit toxic smoke that kill
passengers within minutes.
   Thomas Feaheny, a former Ford Motor Co. vice president,
testified that existing technology could have prevented the fire,
but was not allowed to give any details.
   Feaheny also testified that a protective cage around the bus'
gasoline tank probably would not have prevented the blaze.
   Carroll Circuit Judge Charles Satterwhite has ruled that any
information about technology that could have prevented the bus fire
is inadmissable in the trial.
   ``Anytime there is evidence that has been excluded, obviously it
hurts us,'' defense attorney Russell Baldani said in an afternoon
press conference.
   Sober's testimony dealt with the deadly effects of flexible
polyurethane foam, the material in the cushions, and
polychlorinated vinyl, the plastic seat covering.
   ``Flexible polyurethane foam is the single largest class of
fuels involved with fatal fires,'' Sober said.
   When burned, untreated foam emits hydrogen cyanide gas and the
plastic emits hydrogen chloride gas, he said. In addition, the fire
produces carbon monoxide gas, forcing people to breathe harder and
faster.
   Sober said the fire hazards of the material used for the seats
were well known in the early 1970s.
   Foam treated with fire retardant was readily available to the
automotive industry when the school bus, later sold to the Radcliff
First Assembly of God church as surplus, was manufactured in 1977,
he said.
   Seats treated with fire retardant would have saved lives in the
crash, he said. ``There would have certainly been a lot more time
for them to escape,'' Sober said.
   Feaheny, a 26-year Ford employee, said the crash was ``the worst
single tragedy I ever heard of in the industry and it could have
been prevented.''
   He said a fire beneath the bus boiled gasoline in the metal fuel
tank ``like a teakettle'' and squirted flaming gasoline into the
bus ``like a flame thrower.''
   Under cross-examination, Feaheny said that while he never had
any direct involvement in the design and development of buses at
Ford, his overall experience in the mechanical systems of trucks
and cars provided him the basis to discuss the fuel tank safety of
the 1977 Ford bus.
   Feaheny, fired in September 1983, had sued six Ford executives
for about $30 million in damages, alleging they interfered with his
career development. A verdict in the suit went against Feaheny in
December 1986 and is on appeal.
   Baldani asked Feaheny if he had ``an ax to grind'' with Ford.
Feaheny said he did not.
   Mahoney's defense is expected to conclude Friday. He is charged
with 27 counts of murder, 12 counts of assault, 42 counts of wanton
endangerment and a count of drunken driving.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0173 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 2313EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-Brown-Desegregation 1stLd-Writethru a0761 12-12 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brown-Desegregation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0761,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Issues Opinion in Brown vs. Board of Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 11-16, `In Monday's ..., with six grafs to CORRECT
that Seymour wrote that district needed to do more to obtain integration,
sted McKay; picks up 17th graf, `In his ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court, ruling on the
landmark Brown vs. Board of Education case, said in a revised
version of an earlier opinion that this city hasn't done enough to
desegregate its schools.
   In the ruling reached Monday and released Tuesday, a three-judge
panel of the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Denver reversed
U.S. District Richard Rogers' decision in the case and sent it back
to the lower court.
   The original case led to a U.S. Supreme Court ruling in 1954
which set a nationwide precedent for school desegregation and
busing cases. But black schoolchildrens' parents sued 10 years ago
to have the case reopened.
   The 94-page majority opinion, a reworked version of a 2-1
decision last June, was accompanied by a new, 154-page dissenting
opinion that said ``substantial integration'' had been achieved in
Topeka.
   Attorneys on both sides of the case were reluctant to comment on
the decision because they had not seen it yet.
   An attorney for the Topeka school board, Joe Zima, said the
board plans to hold an emergency meeting early next week to discuss
the case and consider the next step.
   In 1954, the Supreme Court ruled that segregated school systems
were unconstitutional because separate facilities for blacks and
whites provided inherently unequal educational opportunities.
   The Topeka school district, which had set aside four elementary
schools for blacks, was ordered to put an integration plan into
effect.
   In 1979, the parents of 16 black schoolchildren sued, saying the
district had not yet eliminated all vestiges of segregation.
   Rogers ruled in 1987 that the schools were not responsible for
lingering segregation because the board of education did not intend
to keep them segregated.
   In Monday's majority decision, Judge Stephanie Seymour wrote
that the schol district needed to do more to obtain integration.
   She said that about one-fourth of Topeka's minority elementary
school pupils still attend three schools with more than 50 percent
minority enrollments.
   ``We simply see no evidence that Topeka dedicated itself to
desegregation prior to the reopening of this case,'' Seymour wrote.
   Seymour said Rogers erred by limiting the district to having to
show it acted as it did for non-discriminatory reasons.
   ``As 30 years of desegregation law have made clear, the
Constitution requires more than ceasing to promote segregation,''
she wrote.
   The opinion was also signed by Judge Monroe McKay.
   In his dissenting opinion, Judge Bobby Baldock argued, ``The
school board has demonstrated concern for improving the racial
composition in the Topeka schools while retaining the neighborhood
school concept.
   ``In some places the two are not compatible, but in this system
substantial integration has been achieved.''
   Plaintiffs' attorney Rich Jones said the dissenting opinion
would be important because it would help the district decide what
to do.
   Zima said the district could ask all 10 judges on the appeals
court to hear the case, ask the Supreme Court to hear the case or
go before Rogers to help fashion a remedy for the problems cited by
the appellate court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     12-12 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0537</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators who reexamined the dogsled trek
of Robert E. Peary over the Arctic ice say he discovered the North
Pole exactly where, when and how he claimed _ the snow, cold,
``dead reckoning'' navigational methods and skeptics
notwithstanding.
   ``The family is vindicated!'' declared Peary grandson Edward
Peary Stafford, a retired Navy commander, after the Navigation
Foundation, at the behest and expense of the National Geographic
Society, accepted Peary's account in every detail.
   People who still disagree, said Stafford, ``should join the Flat
Earth Society.''
   But National Geographic President Gilbert Grosvenor said he
suspects doubters will persist, as they have for 80 years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite criticism of Romania's policies, U.S.
officials say they will send weapons-grade uranium to the hard-line
East Bloc country as soon as it comes up with a suitable way to
ship the material.
   Opponents of the sale, which was approved in 1988, call it
``crazy'' and say Romania can't be trusted with the dangerous
material. The 16.4 kilograms of uranium are slated to be used at
the Triga research reactor near Bucharest.
   ``In light of the Romanians' increasing isolation and
instability, this is not the time to be sending Romania the means
to make an atomic bomb,'' said Gary Milhollin, director of the
Wisconsin Project on Nuclear Arms Control, a group that opposes
nuclear proliferation.
   ``I think it's crazy,'' said Vladimir Tismaneanu, a resident
scholar at the Foreign Policy Research Institute in Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, rejecting criticism from
Democrats, says China's record of human rights abuses should not be
a barrier to better relations with the United States.
   ``We have contacts with countries that have egregious records on
human rights,'' Bush said Monday, explaining his decision to send a
high-level delegation to Beijing seeking ``new impetus and vigor''
in Sino-U.S. relations.
   He pledged to ``keep looking for ways to find common ground''
despite the Chinese army's killing of hundreds of pro-democracy
demonstrators in June.
   ``Generally speaking, I realize the difficulty of this
relationship but I don't want to make it any worse,'' Bush said.
``I'd like to think it would improve.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Bolivian interior minister who allegedly
hired Nazi war criminal Klaus Barbie to teach torture techniques to
death squads arrived here to face drug charges after being spirited
out of his country.
   Luis Arce Gomez, known as the ``minister of cocaine'' in Bolivia
after he allegedly created an elite paramilitary squad to
confiscate cocaine from drug dealers who refused to pay him bribes,
landed in Miami on Monday night on a U.S. Drug Enforcement plane,
said Justice Department spokesman Dan Eramian.
   Federal officials late Monday refused to comment about the
timing of his arraignment or any other details of his extradition.
The case was surrounded by tight security ordered from Washington,
said sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   ``The arrest of Arce Gomez sends a message that the president
will work with other governments to pursue vigorously individuals
who traffic in drugs,'' the White House said in a statement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
