<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1144EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APonTV-Forsyth Adv13   12-12 0789</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP on TV-Forsyth, Adv 13,0810</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv13</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wednesday PMs, Dec. 13, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>USA Network Airs Frederick Forsyth Thriller</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY SHARBUTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sudden attack of democracy in Eastern Europe
probably has ruined things for spy novelists who may now have to
come in from the Cold War. But the better ones still can make do.
   Exhibit A: Frederick Forsyth and his ``Just Another Secret.''
It's a tale he wrote as the basis for a two-hour USA Network movie
that the cable network has on display tonight and again on Sunday.
   Starring Beau Bridges as a CIA agent sent to East Germany after
a five-man CIA cell there mysteriously vanishes, it's a crisp,
workmanlike exercise in spying, amour, double- and triple-agenting,
blackmail and even betrayal.
   In the script by Murray Smith, our hero, probing the mystery of
the missing cell, comes across a plot by hard-line Stalinists. They
intend to assassinate Mikhail S. Gorbachev in East Germany during a
secret trip there by the Soviet leader.
   The United States, of course, will be blamed and, as one British
agent says, ``it could send the Cold War right back to the Ice
Age.'' Or, Bridges snaps, ``it could start a hot war.''
   The story's time, Forsyth explains in a preface, is ``just
before the Gorbachev-inspired reforms, when the Berlin Wall really
was impregnable and East Germany was a hard-line fortress under the
heel of the secret police.''
   Having asked you to forget current events, which are no fun for
espionage freaks, anyway, his show gets cracking immediately in the
best twist-and-turn tradition with its fine, predominantly British
cast.
   Ace spy Bridges, of course, is exhausted from a recent trip into
murky Beirut. Relaxing with his wife and kids at a barbeque at his
suburban Virginia home, he tries to get out of the missing-cell
mission. Sure.
   Next stop: East Berlin. He goes there disguised as a flutist in
a West German chamber music ensemble, swaps identities with a
stagehand, then has to kill a drunken cop, lest he be exposed.
   This touches off a hunt by an honest, dogged police lieutenant
(Kenneth Cranham) who thinks this only is a murder case.
   With the cops in hot pursuit, Bridges meets a lovely woman
(Beatie Edney), an artist-waitress who gives him a place to stay.
She readily _ too readily, cynics might say _ believes his tale
that he's a musician down on his luck.
   For some reason, he suspects she's an agent for the bad guys. Is
she? Or is she a Western snoop? Only her spymaster knows. But if
you don't think she and the Yank won't make love, you probably
believe in the tooth fairy.
   There also is a key figure, a cipher clerk (Erich Hallhuber) for
the East German Security Service. He's a homosexual whom Bridges
has been told is ripe for ``burning,'' or blackmail.
   The burning, part of Bridges' search for the missing agents, is
done and proves a turning point. It leads to his discovery of the
assassination plot in which the missing agents will ... ah, but
we've said too much already, as they are wont to say in The Agency.
   Now, the problem is how Bridges can sound a warning in a world
of perfidy.
   It's a tough problem made tougher by the traditional clash of
British and American spy agencies and agents that also occurs here.
   But something must be done to foil the sinister, hard-eyed,
high-level Soviet and East German plotters who call Gorbachev a
``traitor.'' It's fun watching the doing.
   It must be said that ``Just Another Secret,'' filmed in
Yugoslavia and the first in a series of Forsyth stories to be
filmed for the USA Network, is no ``Day of the Jackal.'' There are
no great surprises, no razor-edge tensions.
   But it's a well-done, fast-paced effort, akin to a good read on
a quiet day. You suspect you know how it'll come out, but you don't
mind.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television...
   REUNION _ If spy movies aren't your cup of TV, try ``Julie and
Carol: Together Again,'' a classy, sprightly ABC special tonight
that reunites Carol Burnett and Julie Andrews in song and some
comedy. The two, who first taped a special togther in 1962, are in
fine form on this outing, particularly when they demolish
``Feelings'' and ``Memories,'' two awful, oversung songs that are
sorely in need of demolishing.
   MADDIE MEETS DAVID: THE RERUN _ The Lifetime cable network next
February will start reruns of ABC's ``Moonlighting.'' That is the
famed series in which Cybill Shepherd and Bruce Willis cooed,
battled and sometimes went over budget from 1985 until May this
year.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Dec. 13</NOTE>
</DOC>
