<DOCNO> AP891212-0177 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionintheNews Adv15   12-12 0812</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion in the News, Adv 15,0836</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv15</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs Dec. 15, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Holidays Seen Spurring Schools To Teach About Religion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   If your public school is wondering how to observe coming
religious holidays without getting tangled in church-state issues,
a broad coalition of experts offers some tips.
   The key advice is that religious holidays present a special
opportunity for schools to do something they've generally neglected
_ to teach about religions, but not to celebrate them.
   Information about them, on which a severe educational gap lately
has been recognized, may focus on their origins, histories, how
they're observed and their meanings, the guidelines say, adding:
   ``If the approach is objective and sensitive, neither promoting
nor inhibiting religion, this study can foster understanding and
mutual respect for differences in belief.''
   The guidelines, called ``Religious Holidays In The Public
Schools: Questions and Answers,'' was produced by representatives
of l6 religious and educational groups embracing conservatives and
liberals rarely in accord.
   Charles C. Haynes, director of the Americans United Research
Foundation in Silver Spring, Md., and former professor of world
religions, sparked academic, interfaith effort.
   ``If public schools are going to survive, they're going to have
to find an appropriate place for religion in the functioning of the
schools,'' he said in a telephone interview.
   ``Without it, public education is going to suffer and be torn
apart.''
   Concerning numerous recent studies that have shown general
disregard of religion in public schools and in textbooks and
widespread ignorance of religion, he said:
   ``In many schools fear of controversy has led to silence about
religion. The irony is that silence about it has led to more
controversy and division. It's not approppriate simply to remove
religion.
   ``Evidence is that the proper role of religion in school begins
to restore faith in the public schools.''
   However, that role is not religious advocacy or devotions in
schools, but the extension of knowledge about religions and
understanding of their ideas and practices, the guidelines
emphasize.
   They say that this month with Christians celebrating Christmas
and Jews celebrating Hanukkah, it would ``be unrealistic'' to ban
all seasonal activities, but they should focus on educational
purposes ``for all students.''
   ``Holiday concerts may appropriately include music related to
Christmas and Hanukkah, but religious music should not dominate,''
the pamplet says, advocating a mix of non-religious holiday music
with the religious.
   ``Any dramatic productions should emphasize cultural aspects of
the holidays. Nativity pageants or plays portraying the Hanukkah
miracle are not appropriate in the public school setting.''
   ``It's important that the approach be broad,'' Haynes said,
``but to exclude traditional carols would be absurd. We should not
be afraid for students to be exposed to this sort of music.''
   Demands for the pamphlet, turned out in October, exhausted the
initial 75,000 printing, and another 50,000 is being printed by the
foundation, part of the broad coalition producing the document.
   It was a follow-up to another how-to brochure turned out by the
coalition in mid-1988 on ways to teach about religion in public
schools, something urged by the U.S. Supreme Court in 1962-63 when
it banned devotionals there.
   Demand for that first pamphlet has passed the 200,000-mark, and
further printings have been ordered.
   Haynes, who left his post at Randolph-Macon College six years
ago to work on restoring teaching about religion to public
education, said, ``The school people are so grateful that this
problem is getting attention.''
   He said that banning the subject has ``marginalized religion''
and students ``get the same message from television and elsewhere,
that religion is funny and marginal,'' although it's the ``center
of life'' to most people.
   In a more religiously pluralistic society, he said schools must
become a place where a student's religion, whatever it is or none,
``is respected and understood and where he can learn what other's
believe.''
   ``You just can't leave it at the school house door,'' Haynes
added. ``Somehow it's got to be acknowledged, talked about and
recognized.''
   He said religious illiteracy has grown through school avoidance
of the subject, causing difficulties in ``how we live with each
other.''
   Religion ``plays a central role in the lives of people
throughout the world, but we're not preparing people to deal with
that reality. The potential for divisions is tremendous.''
   If religion is included educationlly, he said, it can relieve
intergroup pressures and ``can do a lot to create a climate that is
more inclusive for dealing with other issues.''
   With growing academic recognition of the unsound educational
effects of simply shunning religion, he said steps are being taken
to remedy the situation.
   Texbooks are being revised to include more about religion, and
teacher institutes are being held to equip teachers for handling
the subject, Haynes said. ``The change is happening a lot more
rapidly than I anticipated.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs Dec. 15.</NOTE>
</DOC>
