<FIRST>a e BC-The'80s-Entertainment Adv16   12-12 0587</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Entertainment, Adv 16,0713</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Rapping Away the '80s</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The 1980s was the decade of music videos on
television, boffo bucks for Hollywood, endless TV talk shows and an
entertainment hybrid called performance art. In a decade of few
artistic leaps, one original form did emerge: rap music. AP Arts
Editor Dolores Barclay takes a light look at the entertainment
world through the rhythm of rap, the beat of the '80s.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   
   Decade ... slow fade
   Check it out 'bout who got paid.
   Fame,
   Fortune and a lot of pride
   Gave them all a 15-minute ride.
   Warhol made the promise.
   He said,
   15 minutes, 15 minutes.
   Everybody famous for 15 minutes.
   
   Got it Michael?
   Got it Madonna?
   Geraldo, Oprah and Letterman, too?
   Check it out with Meryl and the Star Wars crew.
   And Elvis ...
   Everywhere
   In the '80s.
   Decade of fame and a money game.
   
   Greed is good, Gordon Gekko said
   Just ask the Stones and the Grateful Dead
   And Cosby,
   Carson,
   Jane and Sly,
   Sent their bank rolls right through the sky
   In the '80s.
   
   Money for millions from ``We Are the World.''
   And millions gone in ``Heaven's Gate,''
   And ``Ishtar,'' the movie you loved to hate.
   But Jason, Freddy and the Pinhead man
   Rolled in the green while critics panned.
   Slice and dice and blood on the screen
   Be-bopping beauties died with a scream,
   Bunnies boiled in a lot of steam
   Hollywood-style ...
   In the '80s.
   
   Prince and the Boss made the scene.
   15 minutes, 15 minutes.
   Elvis. Again.
   Tracy Chapman making tracks
   Speeding up the charts in a car that's fast
   Talking Heads, and ``War.'' U2
   Stirred up vinyl in a heavy brew.
   Guns N' Roses and Run-D.M.C.
   Outpaced a new singer named Eddie Murphy
   In the '80s.
   
   Warhol's world was on the go
   For ``Irises'' and Vincent Van Gogh.
   Big bucks for oil, graffiti and stone
   Keith Haring's little men wouldn't leave us alone.
   In the '80s.
   What was art? No one really knew.
   So ``performance art'' just grew and grew
   For 15 minutes.
   So clap your hands and pat your back,
   Grab that fame and don't look back.
   In the '80s.
   
   Fifteen minutes for ``60 Minutes.''
   Fifteen minutes for Cher and Roseanne,
   ``Miami Vice'' and ``Batman.''
   Fifteen minutes for MTV, Jack Nicholson and Pee-wee.
   Fifteen minutes for a Turner named Tina, a rabbit named Roger
and little E.T.
   Kiss that fame
   Feed that fortune.
   In the '80s.
   
   Today ... gone away
   Jane, Jane Pauley.
   Here ... everywhere,
   Chevy Chase and Shirley,
   MacLaine
   On another plane
   In the '80s.
   
   Got a Jones ... Indiana
   Splash ... Darryl Hannah,
   Lisa Bonet.
   Made it big, had a name.
   Spielberg ... had it made.
   And Lloyd Webber.
   Phantom, Cats and
   The Little Mermaid.
   In the '80s.
   
   Readin' ... Rushdie
   Groovin' ... Public Enemy.
   Kermit, Miss Piggy.
   Movie stars on the go.
   Dancers aging, gettin' slow
   Like Martha and Misha
   Rudy and Suzanne.
   Blast off Michael Mann.
   In the '80s.
   Ten years of MTV
   Cheers and Bon Jovi.
   
   Fifteen minutes for Oscar
   Fifteen minutes for Tony
   Fifteen minutes for Grammy
   Fifteen minutes for Obie.
   Decade ... gone away.
   Tomorrow ...
   We play
   Spike, Wynton and L.L. Cool J
   In the '90s.
   And Ziggy, Ziggy Marley,
   Latin pop and light metal.
   And Elvis ...
   Everywhere.
   In the '90s.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
