<FIRST>a e BC-The'80s-Movies Adv16   12-12 0829</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Movies, Adv 16,0871</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-The '80s-Entertainment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top Movies of the 1980s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the movie business, the 1980s started off with a whisper and
ended with a cheer. In recent years, the American film industry has
enjoyed its greatest box-office success ever, closing the decade
with $5 billion in revenues in 1989. It was also a decade in which
independent filmmakers flourished and animated features returned to
the big screen.
   Here is an alphabetical list of 20 top movies of the '80s as
compiled by the editors of The Associated Press:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``AMADEUS'' _ A stunning, gorgeous-looking requiem for a child
prodigy, directed with style and ferocity by Milos Forman. As
Mozart, Tom Hulce displays wit and obsessiveness. F. Murray Abraham
gives a chilling performance as Antonio Salieri. The soundtrack is
superb.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``ATLANTIC CITY''@ _ The trumps are coming, the trumps are
coming. Burt Lancaster stars as an aging numbers runner, and Susan
Sarandon plays a struggling casino dealer in Louis Malle's vision
of the seamy little city as it's about to fall into the hands of
major developers. Grand performances and an exciting, witty script
by John Guare.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``BLADE RUNNER''@ _ Fear and loathing in the future or, how to
make love to an android and where can I get a gun like that? A
highly visual and intelligent work from Ridley Scott.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``DIVA''@ _ A stolen dress, a stolen tape, a mighty voice, a
ripping caper. A stunning suspense movie that combines all the
right elements _ style, mystery, surprise, music, the offbeat and
class _ to produce a winner. It also has an magnificent soundtrack.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``EL NORTE''@ _ A man is nothing but a pair of arms. This movie
has just about everything: It's funny, provocative, thoughtful, sad
and scary.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``FANNY AND ALEXANDER''@ _ Bergman's farewell to feature films.
Death and repression, as usual, but also family love and
devotion. It is the Swedish filmmaker's most accessible film.
Visually lovely.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``GANDHI''@ _ Richard Attenborough's sweeping epic about India
and Mohandes Gandhi. Ben Kingsley's performance is a tour de force.
One of the finest movie biographies ever made.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE LAST EMPEROR''@ _ The Forbidden City's last tenant. Fifty
years of Chinese history recounted through the story of one person.
An inspired spectacle from Bernardo Bertolucci.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``LOCAL HERO''@ _ Big Oil? Big deal, in a little Scottish town.
Utterly and unselfconsciously charming. A lovely, offbeat little
comedy that sparkles.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MY LIFE AS A DOG''@ _ Love, sex and death as seen through one
boy's penetrating eyes. None of the grief in this film kept anyone
from feeling better after walking out of the theater. It was so
popular that audiences cheered the trailer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``NIGHT OF THE SHOOTING STARS''@ _ Comedy, melodrama, tragedy,
vaudeville, plus the chaos of war _ and it's not even Shakespeare.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``OUT OF AFRICA''@ _ An epic romance and adventure, with
breathtaking photography. Excellent direction by Sydney Pollack
drew fine performances from Meryl Streep and Robert Redford. A
glorious score.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``PLATOON''@ _ A grunt tells it like it was, but Oliver Stone
goes over the top for the finish. A great cinematic work with an
ensemble cast.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``RAGING BULL''@ _ Robert De Niro gets fat for Jake LaMotta _
in glorious black and white. A compelling, hard-edged film with a
knockout performance by De Niro.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``RAIDERS OF THE LOST ARK''@ _ YOW!!! A whopping good adventure
filled with humor, sophistication, surprises, thrills. Great
cinematography and nice touches from Harrison Ford.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE RIGHT STUFF''@ _ It didn't get John Glenn elected
president and millions who saw it wondered why. A winner from
Philip Kaufman based on Tom Wolfe's best seller about the early
days of the American space program. A beautifully photographed,
richly detailed epic with memorable performances.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE UNBEARABLE LIGHTNESS OF BEING''@ _ Kaufman does it again.
Love and lust in the Prague Spring of 1968, with relations
collapsing under the force of Soviet tanks. It's playful, sensual,
poetic, joyful and frightening.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``WHO FRAMED ROGER RABBIT''@ _ Bugs and Mickey together at
last! The most original movie to come from Hollywood in the entire
decade. A brilliant marriage of animation and live action and the
debut of Roger and Jessica.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``WINGS OF DESIRE''@ _ Set in Berlin, a poetic story of love
between a trapeze artist and an angel, a story brought down to
earth by Peter Falk's twinkling eyes and gravelly voice. A
wonderfully original idea and modern-day myth sprung from the head
of Wim Wenders.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``ZELIG''@ _ Woody Allen batting behind Babe Ruth, schmoozing
with F. Scott Fitzgerald and, of course, wooing Mia Farrow. A
beautiful statement on identity and the Fickle Finger of Fame. An
ingenious blend of vintage newsreel footage and vintage Allen in
black and white.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1240EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-The'80s-Music Adv16   12-12 0523</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Music, Adv 16,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-The '80s-Entertainment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top Albums of the 1980s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1980s was a time of little experimentation or adventure in
mainstream pop music. But rap came into its own, as did ethnic
music from around the world. Folk-rock also re-emerged after taking
a siesta during the '70s.
   Here is an alphabetical list of 20 top albums of the '80s, as
compiled by the editors of The Associated Press:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``APPETITE FOR DESTRUCTION,'' Guns N' Roses@ _ Heavy metal with
   something to offend everyone.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``BORN IN THE USA,'' Bruce Springsteen@ _ Patriotism and
rebellion from the promised land.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CAN'T SLOW DOWN,'' Lionel Richie@ _ Every track 
easy-listening hit for lovers and dancing.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CENTERFIELD,'' John Fogerty@ _ Old time rock 'n' roll from
the force behind Creedence Clearwater Revival.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``GET HAPPY,'' Elvis Costello@ _ A year after his notorious
racial slurs against Ray Charles, Costello's tribute to soul music,
and it's a winner in every way.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``GRACELAND,'' Paul Simon@ _ Grace and beauty from the land of
apartheid, and a showcase for African music and musicians. The
album by one of our most enduring artists heralded the
international sound of the '90s.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``IT TAKES A NATION OF MILLIONS TO HOLD US BACK,'' Public
Enemy@ _ Rappers pushed over the edge. A tough, rhythmic and
political sound that galvanizes.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``LONDON CALLING,'' Clash@ _ The purest punk sound of the '80s
with a classy hardness.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MAKING MOVIES,'' Dire Straits@ _ AOR guitar flash. Great
innovations and great sounds.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``NEW YORK,'' Lou Reed@ _ A soundtrack of the meanest streets.
It's tough, real rock.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``PICTURE BOOK,'' Simply Red@ _ A remarkable debut LP from a
hot pop, rock, jazz, reggae crew; ``Holding Back the Years'' is a
classic.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``PONTIAC,'' Lyle Lovett@ _ A magnificent mix of songs _ from
high drama to low comedy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``PURPLE RAIN,'' ``1999'' and ``SIGN 'O' THE TIMES,'' Prince@ _
If Jimi Hendrix had lived, there'd be dueling guitars with Prince.
All three are winners from one of the most creative forces in rock.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``RAPTURE,'' Anita Baker@ _ Languid rhythm and blues with jazz
as a bonus made her the flavor of the month for a long, long time.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``REMAIN IN LIGHT,'' Talking Heads@ _ Adrian Belew's guitar
work alone earns it a spot in any Top 20.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``SCARECROW,'' John Cougar Mellencamp@ _ Hard times and hope _
with quite a beat.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``SYNCHRONICITY,'' The Police@ _ World music and personal
anguish with excellent arrangements and performances.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THRILLER,'' Michael Jackson@ _ A shot heard 'round the world;
even MTV couldn't resist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``TRACY CHAPMAN,'' Tracy Chapman@ _ Big ideas softly spoken.
Stirring songs of love and social conscience for a distinctive new
voice and original songwriter.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``WAR'' and ``THE JOSHUA TREE,'' U2@ _ On those rare occasions
when the radio sounds as good as in the '60s, U2 is usually the
reason. Wouldn't they have been great at Woodstock?
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0185 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-The'80s-Theater Adv16   12-12 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Theater, Adv 16,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-The '80s-Entertainment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top Plays of the 1980s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The big British musical dominated Broadway in the 1980s,
emphasizing spectacle over song and story. Neil Simon and August
Wilson wrote multiple, highly personal comedies and dramas. And
Stephen Sondheim became the last great hope of the American musical.
   Here is an alphabetical list of 20 top plays and musicals in the
'80s:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Plays=
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``AMADEUS''@ _ Peter Shaffer's examination of genius and
jealousy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``BROADWAY BOUND''@ _ The final and most moving chapter of Neil
Simon's autobiographical trilogy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CRIMES OF THE HEART''@ _ Beth Henley's loving portrait of
three Southern sisters.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``DRIVING MISS DAISY''@ _ Alfred Uhry's Pulitzer Prize-winning
tale of an elderly Atlanta woman and her chauffeur.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``FENCES''@ _ Rising expectations divide a black family in
1950s Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``FOOL FOR LOVE''@ _ A slam-bang romance by Sam Shepard.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``GLENGARRY GLEN ROSS''@ _ David Mamet's scabrous look at the
art of selling real estate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MA RAINEY'S BLACK BOTTOM''@ _ August Wilson looks at the
survival of black artists in the 1920s.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MASTER HAROLD ... AND THE BOYS''@ _ Athol Fugard's play about
a young white South African's realization of apartheid.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``'NIGHT, MOTHER''@ _ Marsha Norman's terrifying look at
loneliness.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``NOISES OFF''@ _ A British farce to end all farces.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE HEIDI CHRONICLES'' _ Wendy Wasserstein's look at how one
woman coped with the feminist revolution.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE LIFE AND ADVENTURES OF NICHOLAS NICKLEBY''@ _ The
sprawling Charles Dickens novel brought to life on stage.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE REAL THING''@ _ Tom Stoppard ruminates on love, marriage
and infidelity.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Musicals=
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CATS''@ _ Together in one show, Andrew Lloyd Webber AND T.S.
Eliot; the granddaddy of the big British musicals.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``DREAMGIRLS''@ _ Michael Bennett's last Broadway musical.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``JEROME ROBBINS' BROADWAY''@ _ A reminder of what the Broadway
musical once was. A collection of dance numbers from some of the
master's greatest hits.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``LA CAGE AUX FOLLES''@ _ The subject was tolerance in Jerry
Herman's melodic and old-fashioned adaptation of the famous French
film.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``SUNDAY IN THE PARK WITH GEORGE''@ _ Stephen Sondheim's
heartfelt statement on the public and private life of an artist.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE PHANTOM OF THE OPERA''@ _ Thrills, chills and romance in
the best of the spectacle musicals.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
