<DOCNO> AP891212-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1246EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-The'80s-Television AdvXX   12-12 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-The '80s-Television, Adv XX,0747</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-The '80s-Entertainment</HEAD>
<HEAD>Tops in TV in the 1980s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite a rash of sleep-inducing talk shows, unimaginative
cable-TV programming and formula sitcoms, a few television
producers took risks in the 1980s and tried for something
above-average, daring, entertaining and intelligent.
   Here is an alphabetical list of 20 top television series and
miniseries, as compiled by the editors of The Associated Press:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``BRIDESHEAD REVISITED''@ _ An ambitious and thoroughly
rewarding 11-part adaptation of Evelyn Waugh's novel with a cast of
greats, including Jeremy Irons, Sir John Gielgud and Sir Laurence
Olivier.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CHEERS''@ _ A tightly produced ensemble sitcom starring Ted
Danson and Shelley Long that played for emotions as well as laughs.
Scripts stressed the human element, were adult and had
universality. The first two seasons were best.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE COSBY SHOW''@ _ A 1980s ``Father Knows Best'' in $1,000
sweaters. Intelligent and realistic scripts that stressed family
and human values.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``CRIME STORY''@ _ Michael Mann's not-necessarily-the-'60s
crime show, rippingly done in its first season. Though it followed
the ``Miami Vice'' formula, it was a hard-edged thriller.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE DAYS AND NIGHTS OF MOLLY DODD''@ _ It had a
self-conscious quality, but this show about a contemporary single
lass in the big city mirrored the hopes, fears, vulnerabilities and
fantasies of today's working woman. It was a sitcom with a
melodramatic underpinning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE EQUALIZER''@ _ What a hero! A modern-day knight with a
state-of-the-art arsenal and a Jaguar. Intelligent, original
un-Hollywood scripts and good performances from veteran stage
actors kept this show in peak form.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``FAWLTY TOWERS''@ _ A British import starring John Cleese, it
was one of the wittiest, funniest sitcoms on TV during the decade.
Call it a comedy of anxiety, or high vaudeville. But call it funny.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``FRANK'S PLACE''@ _ Small is beautiful. Noo Awlins atmosphere
so t'ick ya kin smell da erstez, dollin'. A warm and intelligent
sitcom with the talented Tim Rice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``HILL STREET BLUES''@_ Pushed limits of sexuality and
language, but with fine writing and a solid ensemble cast.
Interesting and provocative scripts the first two seasons.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MAGNUM, P.I.''@ _ What otherwise would have been a routine
action series of stereotyped characters was saved by occasionally
brilliant writing and overall by the genial and unpretentious Tom
Selleck.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MIAMI VICE''@ _ The first seasons were the best. A fresh and
exciting action-police series that reaped the benefits of MTV.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MOONLIGHTING''@ _ The first two seasons set the pace for
stylish repartee between Bruce Willis and Cybill Shepherd. It was a
fast-paced comedy-action show that left a smile.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``MURPHY BROWN''@ _ Candice Bergen is a sight for sore eyes.
She has style, wit and charm and is a welcome relief from the
overpainted, overdressed, oversexed ladies in the Aaron Spelling
stable that seemed to dominate television in the '80s. Intelligent,
funny and timely scripts help make this a winner.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``NIGHT COURT''@ _ A sitcom with a bunch of pros. Bosom jokes.
Bottom jokes. But tasteful, yes? Million-dollar laughs from a great
ensemble.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``SCTV''@ _ Canadians do the best American comedy on
television. Fresh and original ``live'' comedy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE `SLAP' MAXWELL STORY''@ _ Viewers had to supply the laugh
track _ this was no Hollywood idiot show. A curmudgeon with a
heart; a show with a conscience.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``TINKER, TAILOR, SOLDIER, SPY'' and ``SMILEY'S PEOPLE''^ _ The
Cold War was never chillier; Alec Guinness' masterwork as a master
spy.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``A WALK THROUGH THE 20TH CENTURY''@ _ Bill Moyers' superb look
at the people and events that fashioned the century.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``WISE GUY''@ _ Only the first two seasons put this in the Top
20. Who will ever forget Sonny Steelgrave and Mel Profitt? A
crime-fighting series with a contemporary bite that took story
lines beyond drugs, prostitution and gambling into the record
industry, real estate, the garment industry and corporate America.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
``THE WONDER YEARS''@ _ A look at life through the eyes of a
kid. The show hits on a gut level _ it's emotional, funny, real.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 16-17 and Thereafter</NOTE>
</DOC>
