<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     12-12 0863</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0904</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co. says it may
cut up to 25,000 jobs this year and plans to cut 8,500 in 1990, a
result of labor-saving technology and tough competition.
   AT&amp;T has been cutting jobs steadily since the Bell System
breakup of Jan. 1, 1984, when the local phone companies were split
off into seven regional companies nicknamed the Baby Bells.
   The company said Monday it estimates the total reduction in 1989
will end up at 22,000 to 23,000 jobs and but added it could range
as high as 25,000 depending on the number of voluntary separations.
The cuts are due mostly to modernization and overstaffing.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BellSouth Corp. has agreed to terminate the
proposed merger of its cellular telephone interests with those of
LIN Broadcasting Corp., clearing the way for McCaw Cellular
Communications Inc. to buy a controlling interest in LIN for $3.38
billion.
   LIN last week asked BellSouth to terminate its September
agreement for merging the cellular telephone operations in a
non-cash deal. LIN last week recommended its shareholders approve
McCaw's latest offer.
   BellSouth said Monday it was not prepared to wage a bidding war.
   __
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ The Supreme Court made employers easier
targets for class action age-bias lawsuits by allowing federal
judges to lend a hand in alerting possible victims of
discrimination.
   In a 7-2 ruling Monday, the court let judges help plaintiffs in
such suits locate other possible victims and seek their
participation.
   The decision is a boost to workers suing Hoffmann-La Roche Inc.,
which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off or
demoting some 1,200 employees at New Jersey plants.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign ownership of U.S. factories, banks and
other businesses has escalated in recent years, but most fears
about adverse economic consequences from foreign control are
unwarranted, a new study says.
   The Institute for International Economics said Monday that the
growth of foreign ownership has not translated into a loss of jobs
for Americans and that foreign firms paid their U.S. workers the
same as domestic firms.
   The institute argued against changing U.S. laws to block foreign
investment, saying that even in the area of national security,
foreign ownership was not of concern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four months after the enactment of the largest
bailout in the nation's history, President Bush is suggesting that
his savings and loan bill may not have provided enough money.
   ``It's a whale of a mess, and we'll see where we go,'' Bush said
Monday. ``We've had this one refinancing. I am now told that that
might not be enough.''
   Legislation signed by Bush on Aug. 9 provides $50 billion
through September 1991 to protect depositors at insolvent S&amp;Ls.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wyse Technology Inc., the world's
second-largest maker of computer terminals, has agreed to a $268
million buyout by a Taiwan group in a deal that could boost the
company's flagging personal computer business.
   Wyse, which is based in San Jose but does all manufacturing in
Taiwan and elsewhere overseas, began a search for buyers after
losing $21 million in the 1989 fiscal year ended March 31.
   Monday's $10-per-share buyout by Channel International Corp., an
investment group of government and local enterprises, is the
largest ever of a foreign firm by Taiwan.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks and foreign exchange houses
closed to give them time to digest the government-ordered 34.5
percent currency devaluation, along with the postponement of
payments on the nation's massive internal debt.
   Initial reaction was mixed over the plan Monday, the second
severe economic adjustment in five months. Rates were expected to
be increased for electricity, transportation and other public
services, which along with the devaluation was expected to
acclerate inflation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic advertising spending is expected to
rise a modest 6.2 percent in 1990, slightly above the 5.8 percent
growth pace this year despite slower economic growth, a prominent
media forecaster says.
   Robert Coen, who heads the forecasting unit at the advertising
agency McCann-Erickson and makes semiannual projections of ad
spending trends, said Monday he expects ad spending growth to
improve in the next decade.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Economic growth in the United States, Canada and
Britain likely will be below average among developed countries next
year, a top official of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
says.
   Arthur Dunkel, director-general of the GATT, also said Monday
that prospects were ``dim'' for reducing the current account
imbalances between major trading partners such as the United
States, West Germany and Japan and that trade-restricting domestic
policies remained widespread.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell in listless trading Monday amid investor
uncertainty about the economy and interest rates. The Dow Jones
industrials average fell 3.20 points to 2,728.24 after gaining
10.66 points in Friday's session.
   The dollar ended mostly lower in light trading.
   Bond prices fell slightly.
   Gold futures prices surged to within a few dollars of new 1989
highs; orange juice futures rose sharply on Florida freeze fears;
cotton futures rebounded; energy futures gained; pork futures fell;
cattle futures rose; and grains and soybeans were mixed.
</TEXT>
