<FIRST>r f PM-TreasuryBills     12-12 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,0168</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rates Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in Monday's auction to the highest level in two
weeks.
   The Treasury Department sold $8 billion in three-month bills at
an average discount rate of 7.60 percent, up from 7.55 percent last
week. Another $8 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average
discount rate of 7.41 percent, up from 7.30 percent last week.
   The rates were the highest since Nov. 27 when three-month bills
sold for 7.63 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.45 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.86 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,807.90 and 7.80 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,625.40.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for 1-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for
making changes in adjustable-rate mortgages, was 7.73 percent last
week, unchanged from the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
