<FIRST>r f BC-GreatNorthern     12-12 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Great Northern,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Georgia-Pacific Analysis Suggested Sales of Five Great Northern Mills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia-Pacific Corp.'s proposed takeover
of Great Northern Nekoosa Corp. could be made more affordable if
the hostile suitor sold five Great Northern mills, according to a
consultant's report unsealed Monday by a federal judge.
   Great Northern immediately accused Georgia-Pacific of a
``cover-up.'' But Georgia-Pacific disputed the contention it had a
``secret plan'' to sell the mills in Millinocket and East
Millinocket, Maine; Valdosta, Ga; and Nekoosa and Port Edwards.,
Wis.
   U.S. District Judge Gene Carter unsealed the private study,
which was included in a Great Northern counterclaim that accused
Georgia-Pacific of violating federal securities laws by trying to
keep the study secret. Lawyers had argued over the unsealing in a
closed-door session Friday.
   Georgia-Pacific fought disclosure of the document, but once it
was unsealed, the Atlanta-based company quickly issued a statement
saying that the consultant's study had been rejected as the merger
attempt was planned.
   Georgia-Pacific Chairman T. Marshall Hahn Jr. and other
corporate executives have been in Maine recently to say there were
no plans to sell any Maine assets to pay for the tender offer of
$63 per share, or $3.8 billion. Great Northern is incorporated in
Maine.
   The study, commissioned by Georgia-Pacific before it made its
initial offer of $58 per share Oct. 31, paints a different picture,
but Georgia-Pacific said it never accepted the study's
recommendations.
   Great Northern saw the study differently.
   ``The public should know this document exists in order to weigh
statements made by Mr. Hahn and Georgia-Pacific representatives
about their motives, about their plans and what went into their
planning,'' Great Northern attorney Robert A. Moore said.
   The study indicated that Georgia-Pacific could cut its merger
costs from $4.4 billion to $3.3 billion by selling the mills, Great
Northern said.
   Great Northern Chairman William R. Laidig issued a statment from
company headquarters in Norwalk, Conn., that said: ``I am appalled,
quite frankly, that even after we discovered this study,
Georgia-Pacific attempted to continue its cover-up, forcing us to
go to court to have the judge order the disclosure of our claims to
the public.''
   Great Northern's counterclaim was made in response to a lawsuit
filed in U.S. District Court here by Georgia-Pacific, which is
challenging ``poison pill'' provisions of Great Northern's bylaws
as well as Maine's anti-takeover statute, which forces hostile
suitors to wait five years before merging with a targeted company.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
