<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0151EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ComputerControversy Bjt   12-12 0751</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer Controversy, Bjt,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM-Sears Venture Discontinues Controversial Bulletin Board</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: ``Ek'' is cq. ^By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A popular home computer service has eliminated a
``bulletin board'' that fostered an electronic shouting match
between homosexuals and Christian fundamentalists, but it denies it
was pressured to do so.
   Prodigy, an IBM-Sears joint venture, said Monday the bulletin
board was cancelled because it was too lightly used, but some vocal
customers say Prodigy simply wanted to avoid controversy.
   The dispute over Prodigy's Health Spa bulletin board is the
first notable controversy to affect the service, which has grown
rapidly in the past year and now serves more than a quarter-million
users in 160,000 subscriber households.
   Prodigy officials, while dismayed about the negative publicity,
see the Health Spa fight as evidence that the service has attracted
some highly committed customers.
   ``If we weren't expanding so rapidly, I don't think we would
have gotten this kind of attention,'' said Brian Ek, a spokesman at
Prodigy headquarters in White Plains, N.Y.
   Prodigy is a $10-a-month service for personal computers that
gives users access to services for shopping, airline reservations,
news and stock trading. It also has bulletin boards, which let
subscribers post electronic messages and communicate with each
other.
   Health Spa essentially was a forum for people to post news and
exchange information on health-related topics.
   It was discontinued last Wednesday on short notice. According to
several users, the only controversial section of it was one on
``emotional health,'' which included discussions of such topics as
mental health. The section became a battleground of homosexuals and
fundamentalists and required constant supervision and occasional
censorship.
   Other sections covered topics such as health, fitness and
support groups.
   Some users said the complaints about the discontinuation were
coming from homosexuals, while others are coming from people who
used the other sections and believe they were caught in the middle.
   A Georgia user who asked not to be identified said he had
participated in the debates on the bulletin board, from the gay
viewpoint. He also said some subscribers had complained that
homosexuality was not an appropriate topic because children could
be reading.
   Prodigy's Ek said Health Spa was cut because it was lightly
used, but some protesting subscribers dispute that.
   One survey showed the emotional health bulletin board getting an
average of 20 pages a day in entries, compared to one or two pages
a day for many other bulletin boards that remain in operation, said
Larry Holliday, a New York executive. A page is a computer screen's
worth of information.
   Holliday said he did not use the emotional health section but
did use other sections of Health Spa.
   Ek said the heavy use was by a small number of people. He said
other services with few entries were kept because many people
browsed through them without making entries.
   Ek also said the monitoring to make sure Health Spa met decency
standards for a family service was time-consuming, and said
bulletin board monitors frequently had to reject submissions due to
profanity and references to sexual practices.
   ``It's a cost-benefit ratio,'' he said. He indicated possible
grounds for compromise by saying some parts of Health Spa might be
brought back in a different form.
   Prodigy differs from other computer services in that the
bulletin boards are only a small part of what it offers. It also
differs in that it carries advertising, which constantly appears on
a portion of the screen.
   Some subscribers say they believe, without specific evidence,
that Prodigy is trying to avoid any controversy or offensiveness to
please advertisers, who account for most of its revenue.
   ``We are simply the people who are offered up for sale, which is
why what we think isn't that important,'' said Cyndie Merten of San
Jose, Calif.
   Ek denies that, as well as allegations that Christian
fundamentalists brought pressure on Prodigy.
   Prodigy has not yet achieved profitability, but has the backing
of two companies with deep pockets, International Business Machines
Corp. and Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co.
   Ek said he finds it hard to understand why Prodigy has drawn
such criticism, considering that newspapers routinely screen
letters to the editor and television networks drop shows that
aren't working out.
   ``We're a family service. If we feel that there is something in
there that should not be in there for a family audience, we do not
put it in,'' he said.
   The discontinuation of Health Spa was reported Sunday by the San
Jose Mercury News.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
