<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     12-12 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell against all major foreign
currencies today in thin European trading, dealers said.
   Gold prices were mixed as selling pressure cut into early highs,
precious metal traders said.
   Dealers predicted little market activity today with traders on
the sidelines waiting for economic news expected later in the week.
   U.S. retail sales figures are due out Wednesday and U.S. trade
data for October will be released Friday.
   ``With all the indicators coming, I don't see a big trading day
today,'' said Jens-Uwe Fischer, senior trader at Manufacturers
Hanover in Frankfurt.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 0.18 yen to a closing 144.47 yen.
Later, in London, it was quoted at a lower rate of 144.30 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
prices: 1.7522 West German marks, down from 1.7660; 1.5885 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5970; 5.9930 French francs, down from 6.0370;
1.9835 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9950; 1,297.50 Italian lire,
down from 1,304.25; and 1.1630 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1632.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.6030 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5895 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $417.40 a troy ounce, up
from $416.75 bid late Monday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $416.10.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $416, up from $415.75 bid late
Monday.
   Gold in Hong Kong rose $3.55 to close at a bid $415.81.
   Silver fell in London to a bid price of $5.70 a troy ounce, down
from Monday's $5.74.
</TEXT>
