<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     12-12 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0415</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Stocks Slightly Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
today after a seven-day gain, while the Tokyo Stock Exchange's key
index rose slightly.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues gained 50.86
points, or 0.13 percent, closing at 37,803.53. It had gained 28.61
points Monday.
   The dollar closed at 144.47 yen, down 0.18 yen from Monday's
144.65-yen finish. It opened at 144.41 yen and ranged between
144.40 yen and 144.58 yen. In the previous seven trading days, the
dollar had gained a total of 1.75 yen.
   ``Trading was very quiet, and nothing really happened today,''
said Minori Takeuchi, a trader with Chemical Bank in Tokyo.
   Market players, fearing central bank intervention, were
reluctant to make major moves, she said. Spot trading volume was
$3.87 billion.
   The Bank of Japan was reported to have sold dollars at around
144.50 yen shortly after Tokyo trading opened today, following
intervention in the New York market by the Federal Reserve to curb
the dollar's rise against the yen.
   Today's sales by the Bank of Japan had no major impact on
exchange rate movements or the tone of trading, and no further
central bank intervention was observed later in the day, Ms.
Takeuchi said.
   The Bank of Japan was believed to have sold dollars on the
market several times Monday to keep the dollar within a narrow
range. The central bank does not comment on its exchange market
activities.
   On the stock exchange, trading was active in the morning and
issues related to natural resources were strong sellers, but
investors later stepped to the sidelines in the absence of
market-affecting news, said a dealer with Nomura Securities Co.
   Of the estimated first section volume of 800 million shares,
only 200 million were traded in the afternoon. An estimated 700
million shares changed hands on Monday.
   ``I'm pretty sure the index would have fallen if the investment
trust companies had not conducted index-buying in the afternoon,''
said the Nomura dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   In index-buying, an investor can buy a minimum of 1,000 shares
in all of the Nikkei's 225 items, a transaction that costs billions
of dollars.
   Such purchases in the afternoon contributed to raising the index
by some 100 points, the dealer said.
   Other dealers said investors sold steel issues, which many
market players had recently bought, to take profits.
</TEXT>
