<FIRST>u f BC-Britain-WaterPrivatization     12-12 0156</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Water Privatization,0163</SECOND>
<HEAD>Water Authority Stocks Soar When Official Trading Begins</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock in Britain's newly privatized 10 water
authorities soared to premiums of up to 64 percent when official
trading in the stocks began Tuesday on London's Stock Exchange.
   Prices then fell back and steadied, showing a maximum premium of
50 percent.
   The start of trading overshadowed other business in the London
market and the hefty price gains helped to ensure a buoyant mood.
   The privatization, which raised 5.24 billion pounds, or $8.4
billion, was 5.7 times oversubscribed with 47 percent of the total
amount of shares going to the British public. The rest was
allocated to British institutions and overseas investors.
   The government sold 2.183 million shares at 240 pence, or $3.84
each, payable in three installments.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government has
sold billions of pounds worth of state-owned companies in the past
decade to promote capitalism in Britain.
</TEXT>
