<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-France-CurrencyControls     12-12 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-France-Currency Controls,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last French Currency Controls To Be Lifted By Jan. 1</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   France's last remaining currency controls will be
lifted on Jan. 1, 1990, the Finance Ministry announced Tuesday.
   The widely anticipated move will allow French residents to hold
foreign currency accounts inside the country and open bank accounts
outside France.
   Under a timetable set up by the European Community, France and
most other Common Market countries have until July 1, 1990 to lift
their controls on capital movement. Spain, Portugal and Greece have
until Jan. 1, 1993.
   The bulk of France's currency controls covering major capital
movement by corporations were dismantled gradually in a series of
steps that began in 1984.
   The ministry said in a statement the lifting of the controls
reflects government ``confidence in the good health of the French
economy and in the stability of our currency.''
   The move also underlines ``our desire to accelerate progress
toward European monetary union,'' the statement said.
   A ministry spokeswoman confirmed that French residents will be
obliged to notify authorities when they open foreign bank accounts,
as they must do for accounts opened in France.
   Currency traders said the announcement did not have any
immediate impact on the foreign exchange market. They said the lack
of response reflected the relatively limited scope of the remaining
controls and the market's knowledge that they were already
scheduled to come down by July 1, 1990 at the latest.
   The decision by France to lift its exchange controls removes one
of the obstacles frequently cited by British Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher that has prevented Britain from seeking full
membership for its currency in the European Monetary System.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Trade     12-12 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Trade,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan's Trade Surplus Drops for Seventh Straight Month</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rapidly growing imports pushed Japan's trade
surplus sharply lower in November, its seventh consecutive monthly
decline from year-earlier levels, the Finance Ministry announced
Tuesday.
   The trade surplus, calculated on a customs-clearance basis,
shrank 46.2 percent to $3.53 billion from a year earlier, when it
registered $6.56 billion dollars, the ministry said. The surplus
also fell from October's $4.65 billion.
   Exports dropped 2.9 percent from their year-earlier level to
$22.03 billion, while imports climbed 14.8 percent to $18.50
billion, the ministry said.
   The trade surplus' latest decline from year-earlier levels was
the largest since October 1982, when it fell 54.1 percent.
   Japan's surplus with the United States declined from
year-earlier levels for the second consecutive month, falling 19.3
percent to $3.57 billion.
   Imports from the United States, buoyed by increased purchases of
aircraft, office equipment and nonferrous metals, grew 12.1 percent
to $4.08 billion. Exports to the United States dropped 5.2 percent
to $7.65 billion, largely because of falling auto shipments,
ministry officials said.
   Ministry officials attributed the decline in the overall surplus
mainly to growing imports of crude oil, both in value and volume
terms. Because of rising world oil prices, the average price of oil
jumped 38.3 percent from a year earlier to $17.41 a barrel, while
volume increased by 12.9 percent to 4.9 billion gallons, they said.
   Imports of manufactured goods also rose 13 percent from the
previous year and accounted for 50.6 percent of overall imports,
they said. It was the sixth month in a row that manufactured goods
exceeded 50 percent of total imports.
   In contrast, exports of motor vehicles fell 9.4 percent because
of sluggish demand and rising production by Japanese manufacturers
in North America, they said. Steel exports fell 23.6 percent
because of weak worldwide sales, the officials added.
   Compared to their October levels, exports declined 4.4 percent
and imports rose 0.7 percent, the ministry said.
   Although Japan's trade surplus, a target of sharp criticism from
the United States and other trading partners, has fallen for seven
months in a row, ministry officials said they were not sure whether
the decline was permanent.
   ``We have to see what the future will bring,'' said an official
in charge of trade data. ``A lot of things will depend on how oil
prices will change, and there are other elements of uncertainty.''
   After seasonal factors were taken into account, the November
trade surplus came to $4.70 billion, up from $3.77 billion the
previous month.
   Japan calculates its trade surplus figures on a
customs-clearance basis, in which freight and insurance costs are
included in import figures but not in exports.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
