<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0906EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-UAL     12-12 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UAL,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Reported Management Plan Emerges for UAL Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   UAL Corp. management has drafted a preliminary
$5.43 billion employee buyout proposal for the parent of United
Airlines, but unions representing UAL workers appear to be balking,
a published report said today.
   The plan would place a nominal value of $240 on a share of
common stock, the Chicago Tribune reported, quoting unidentified
sources. It also contemplates UAL employees owning about two-thirds
of the stock after a buyout, and public stockholders about
one-third, the Tribune said.
   Management officials made buyout proposals last week to United
Airlines' pilots' and flight attendants' unions, the paper said.
   While the UAL board of directors is scheduled to meet Wednesday,
the sources said management is not expected to present any buyout
proposal then.
   In October, a $6.75 billion, or $300 a share, buyout attempt
failed for lack of financing.
   That proposal was undercut by the Machinists' union, which
opposes a highly leveraged buyout of the airline.
   A Machinists' source told the Tribune that if speculation about
a $240 a share offer is true, ``that proposal would be rejected by
us as too high.''
   The pilots' union hasn't acknowledged receiving the rumored
proposal. The flight attendants said they had gotten it, but
declined comment until it was more thoroughly studied.
   The Tribune said its sources believed the pilots feel the
proposal falls short of some of their demands, including having a
voice in running the company.
   The sources said management increased somewhat the contract
concessions it is seeking from the flight attendants in return for
their participation in an employee stock ownership plan.
</TEXT>
