<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 0929EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-ChevyDealers     12-12 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chevy Dealers,0263</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Plants May Shut If Chevy Dealer Orders Fall</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s Chevrolet Division has
warned its dealers that unless new car orders pick up, assembly
plants may close, according to an automotive trade journal.
   Automotive News said in Monday's edition that GM issued a
special bulletin to its Chevrolet dealers saying the company
planned to build 90,843 Chevrolets in January, but orders for those
cars as of Nov. 22 stood at 24,130.
   For months, dealers have been faced with large inventories on
which they pay interest and insurance costs. Many have said they
will cut orders for 1990 models.
   Ward's Automotive Reports, another weekly automotive journal,
said in Monday's edition that dealers for the eight major U.S.
automakers had an 88-day supply of new cars on hand at the end of
November, up from supplies of 77 days the month before. GM's
new-car inventory stood at 99 days, Ward's said.
   Earlier this month, GM said Chevrolet sales for the 1990 model
year were 14.1 percent lower than sales at the same time during the
1988 model year.
   ``It is critical that all dealers immediately analyze their
product needs and submit orders immediately,'' Automotive News
quoted the GM bulletin as saying. ``Adequate order banks are
necessary to maintain uninterrupted production.''
   Last week, GM announced temporary shut downs of U.S. and
Canadian assembly plants because of sagging dealer orders. In
March, GM will close its Lakewood, Ga., plant, which makes the
full-size Chevrolet Caprice and the Buick Estate Wagon.
</TEXT>
