<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-EmersonAcquisitions     12-12 0223</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Emerson Acquisitions,0232</SECOND>
<HEAD>Buys Two Companies For $595 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emerson Electric Co., strengthening its
position as one of the world's leading electric motor makers, today
announced the purchase of Leroy-Somer SA, a French maker of
electric motors, for $460 million.
   The St. Louis-based company also announced the $135 million
purchase of McGill Manufacturing Co., a Valparaiso, Ind., company
that makes bearings and electrical products.
   Emerson, which is also a leading producer of industrial
monitoring equipment, tools and components for appliances, had
annual sales of about $7.1 billion this year.
   ``This is pretty much consistent with their strategy of the last
six years, bringing in smaller firms and improving profitability,''
said Craig Krapf, an analyst for Edward D. Jones &amp; Co. in St.
Louis. ``They've got a knack for that.''
   The Leroy-Somer acquisition, subject to approval by the U.S. and
French regulatory authorities, gives Emerson a chance to increase
its presence in the European Economic Community before 1992, when
the 12-nation bloc becomes a single unified market.
   Emerson already has some electric motor divisions in West
Germany, as well as Mexico.
   Leroy-Somer makes integral and fractional horsepower electric
motors and drives for industrial markets, with manufacturing
facilities primarily in France.
   Emerson said when the deal is finalized, it will sell
Leroy-Somer's King Bearing unit, based in the United States.
</TEXT>
