<FIRST>u f PM-AppleComputer     12-12 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apple Computer,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Apple Forecasts Profit Drop and Slower Sales Growth</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Apple Computer Inc. on Tuesday
projected a decline in earnings in the first quarter of fiscal 1990
and said sales would grow more slowly than previously predicted.
   The personal computer maker made its surprise announcement just
two weeks after a top Apple executive told security analysts in New
York that it expected worldwide sales growth of more than 20
percent.
   Apple's stock was off $3.25 a share to $36 in over-the-counter
trading early today.
   Donald P. Casey, vice president of networking and communications
systems, also told the analysts at a personal computing conference
on Nov. 29 that Apple expected sales growth in this country of 15
percent to 18 percent.
   In its announcement Tuesday, Apple said its net sales for the
first quarter of 1990, ending Dec. 29, 1989, will exceed the $1.40
billion for the same quarter in the previous year, but the increase
will be less than it expected.
   The company said it had expected a significant increase in sales
in the quarter, especially with holiday purchases. But, though
Macintosh sales have been strong overall, Apple's sales haven't
increased at the expected rate.
   In addition, Apple said it is having trouble meeting customer
demand for the Macintosh Portable because of constraints in the
supply of the products screen display.
   The revised sales figures, the company said, is likely to drive
earnings below the $1.10 per share level of a year ago.
</TEXT>
