<HEAD>Say JMB Joins Bidding for Bloomies, Hilton</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grafs 1-5 new with additional report of JMB bid for Hilton;
picks up 5th graf pvs, The firm's...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major Chicago retail-center developer, JMB
Realty Co., has joined the bidding for the high-profile
Bloomingdale's department store chain and Hilton Hotels Corp.,
published reports say.
   Officials at JMB have declined to comment publicly on its
interest in acquiring the 17-store Bloomingdale's chain, the crown
jewel of troubled Campeau Corp.'s retailing empire, but sources
were quoted by the Chicago Tribune as saying a bid had been made.
   Toronto-based Campeau has said only that it had received ``a
number of expressions of interest'' in Bloomingdale's by Friday's
deadline for bids.
   Meanwhile, the Wall Street Journal reported in today's editions
that JMB is one of at least six bidders for all or part of Hilton,
which put itself on the market in May. JMB declined to comment on
that report as well.
   JMB is a privately held corporation with real estate holdings in
Chicago and other major U.S. and Canadian cities worth more than
$20 billion.
   The firm's Chicago landmarks include Water Tower Place and 900
N. Michigan _ retail and commercial developments on the city's
downtown ``Magnificent Mile,'' its glitziest shopping district.
Bloomingdale's Chicago store is in the 900 N. Michigan building.
   The Wall Street Journal reported Monday that JMB, Bahrain-based
investment bank Investcorp International, Bloomingdale's Chairman
Marvin Traub and Ann Taylor Inc. Chairman Joseph Brooks made offers
for Bloomingdale's.
   Other possible bidders include such established retail companies
as Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp. and May Co. of St. Louis,
which have declined comment on their possible interest in the
chain, the Tribune said in today's editions.
   Campeau has said it expects to pare the list ``to no more than
five or six finalists'' who will receive more detailed information
in preparation for the sale, expected to be completed by February.
   JMB won't comment on how much it has offered for the chain,
estimated recently to be priced from $1 billion to $1.3 billion,
nor how much it would be willing to pay.
   ``It's just a bid at this point,'' one unidentified source told
the Tribune. ``If successful, however, it would put the firm in an
area (retailing) that up until now it has not been involved in a
big way.''
   Bloomingdale's went up for sale in September after Campeau said
it was being forced to restructure under the weight of $8 billion
in debt from the 1988 acquisition of Federated Department Stores,
including Bloomingdale's, and the 1986 acquisition of Allied Stores.
</TEXT>
