<HEAD>Crop Futures Slip In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices fell in early
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade, reflecting slack
foreign demand for U.S. corn and weaker European markets for
soybean oil and meal.
   A weekly Agriculture Department report on Monday showed a
lower-than-expected amount of corn inspected for export last week.
   Besides lower values overseas for soybean products, prices fell
on news of substantial planting progress in Brazil, a leading
producer.
   The wheat market gave up a portion of the moderate gains it had
tallied Monday in anticipation of expanded grain sales to the
Soviet Union.
   ``The market's just waiting for some export business,'' said
Dale Gustafson, an analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. ``We factored in a good deal of it yesterday and now we're
just waiting for it to be realized.''
   In early trading, wheat futures were unchanged to 1 cent lower
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.12{ a bushel; corn
was \ cent to 1{ cents lower with December at $2.33{ a bushel; oats
were { cent to 1 cent lower with December at $1.43{ a bushel;
soybeans were 1 cent to 3\ cents lower with January at $5.76 a
bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle futures were .22 cent lower to .15 cent higher with
December at 76.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .20
cent higher with January at 83.25 cents a pound; hogs were .25 cent
lower to .05 cent higher with December at 50.90 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .05 cent to .75 cent higher with February
at 50.50 cents a pound.
   Cattle and hog futures finished mostly higher on Monday while
pork bellies were sharply lower.
