<HEAD>End Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks rose in heavy volume Tuesday, reflecting a
strong response to the debut of trading in Britain's privatized
water companies.
   The 10 English and Welsh water companies began their first
trading day well above the 30 percent premium than many market
participants had expected.
   The government sold 2.183 million shares for 240 pence or about
$3.84 each in the $8.4 billion privatization. Trading in water
shares dominated the day, as well as the market's total volume.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 12.1
points, or 0.5 percent, higher at 2,363.5. The Financial Times
30-share index was up 9.7 points at 1,861.5 at the close. The
Financial Times 500-share index rose 5.24 points to close at
1,283.79.
   Volume totaled 800.4 million shares, with trading in the water
companies accounting for about 433 million shares of the total. On
Monday, volume totaled 349.5 million shares.
