<FIRST>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     12-12 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Dollar-Gold,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Dips as Mark Gains; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: An AMs version planned by 5 p.m. EST</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell sharply against most major
currencies in European trading Tuesday under pressure from the
strong West German mark.
   Gold prices rose.
   Trading was dominated by strong demand for marks against all
other currencies. A robust economy and a perception that West
Germany will benefit from the changes in Eastern Europe have stoked
that demand, dealers said.
   ``No one is brave enough to buck this trend. Everyone is
sticking with marks,'' said one trader in London.
   The dollar was quoted in London at 1.7335 marks, off from 1.7660
marks late Monday and the lowest level in 1989.
   The British pound rose to $1.6027 from $1.5895 late.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.18 yen to close at 144.47 yen. Later in
London, it dropped to 143.80 yen.
   The dollar dipped below 6.00 French francs for the first time
since Dec. 16, 1988, finishing at 5.9275 francs, down from 6.0370
francs late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday:
1.5765 Swiss francs, down from 1.5970; 1.9715 Dutch guilders, down
from 1.9950; 1,285.75 Italian lire, down from 1,304.25; and 1.1625
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1632.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $417.50 a troy ounce,
up from $416.75 Monday. In Zurich, gold closed at a bid of $416.75
an ounce, up $1.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold closed up $4.40 at $416.95 an ounce.
   Silver traded in London at a late bid price of $5.70 a troy
ounce, down from $5.74 Monday.
</TEXT>
