<FIRST>u f AM-ToyTrains Bjt   12-12 0835</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Trains, Bjt,0860</SECOND>
<HEAD>Toy Trains Making A Comeback This Christmas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto available</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERICH SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Toy trains, which have chugged around so
many Christmas trees in years past, are coming `round again this
year.
   After being eclipsed by video games at the beginning of the
decade, sales are up for train sets, according to manufacturers,
wholesalers and retailers.
   Some see it as a return to more traditional toys by both
children and parents, while others say buyers are attracted by such
modern versions as remote-controlled trains and sets featuring
miniature video cameras.
   ``Our business is going crazy. We're so far behind with orders,
it's unbelievable,'' said Ron Moyer, vice president at
International Hobby Corp. in Philadelphia, which distributes model
trains, accessories and building kits. ``We're working six days a
week, extra hours each day.''
   Moyer estimates International's sales are up 40 percent over
last year.
   ``A lot of people are bringing out their old train sets they had
for years and they're going to hobby stores to get the layouts
going again,'' he said.
   Orders also are up about 40 percent at Bachman Industries, Inc.,
according to Dick Maddox, vice president for sales and marketing.
   Bachman, supplied by factories in China, advised retailers this
fall that political unrest there and a fire at a factory in
Thailand caused shipping delays.
   But Maddox says demand remains strong, ``...and we still haven't
hit the hottest time for train sales, the last two weeks before
Christmas.''
   Dan Perkins, national sales manager for Global Hobby
Distributors in Fountain Valley, Calif., said he believes many
people are buying trains at his Hobby Shack retail chain for the
same reason he bought one.
   ``You have a generation of children who grew up with trains who
are now adults,'' he said. ``And they want trains for their kids.
Plus, the manufacturers are back in the swing again after a pretty
bad shakeout a few years ago. ...Sales are up 20 to 30 percent over
last year, and last year was a growth year.''
   Bachman took aim at a new market this year with its ``Big
Hauler'' sets, trains built to the extra-large ``G'' scale, about
twice the size of yesteryear's toy trains.
   Maddox estimates his company will sell $15 million worth of the
big trains this year and he thinks he had to turn away as much as
$10 million in orders.
   ``It will never never replace HO scale trains as a hobby, but it
will become the standard for those who want to set up trains under
the tree as part of the tradition,'' he said. ``Little kids can
play with it. It's big enough for them to handle it.''
   In Moorestown, N.J., manufacturer Tyco also is having a banner
year. Company spokesman Bruce Maguire said trains are doing well
because of the same type of nostalgia buying that has made some of
the company's dolls successful this year.
   ``Among the more popular dolls that are making comebacks are
dolls that mothers had when they were girls,'' he said. ``They are
now buying them for their kids.''
   Prices of train sets vary widely. Advertising circulars for the
``Toys `R Us'' chain last week showed train sets from $24.99 to
$199.99. Serious hobbyists can spend hundreds of dollars on a
single locomotive.
   ``In general, basic is what sells,'' Maguire said. ``Good old
American train sets, good old dolls. They're going to sell year in
and year out. Kids stil want them and parents still want their kids
to have them.''
   Art Peisner, president of Lionel, said there are few reliable
statistics for the industry but he believed sales were higher now
than in decades. Lionel train sales are up ``significantly,
certainly double-digit'' this year, he said.
   Lionel _ which markets a locomotive equipped with a video camera
_ has introduced oversize ``G'' gauge and collector-oriented
standard gauge trains. But Peisner says the company's biggest
success remains the mass marketing of train sets, complete with
track and electric transformer.
   ``The focus of our advertising is many adults _ what some people
would refer to as yuppies _ who have children now of age who are
potentially interested in trains,'' Peisner said.
   ``We're trying to remind them of the wonderful times they had
when they were kids, playing with their trains and more importantly
playing with their fathers. Now, we're advising them to enjoy the
experience from the other end with their sons _ or their
daughters.''
   Peisner estimates the train industry's share of the roughly
$12.5 billion retail toy market is about $300 million. Video games
such as the popular Nintendo account for several billion dollars on
top of the overall market and Peisner has no illusions that trains
someday will take the lion's share of the market.
   ``No, I think train sets are an important and growing set of the
toy market, but trains are not an everyday part of a kid's life
today, they way they were back in the 50s,'' he said.
</TEXT>
