<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-CottonLawsuit     12-12 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cotton Lawsuit,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Accuse Memphis Cotton Merchant of Missing Margin Call</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lawsuit accusing The Julien Co. of
failing to meet a $4.35 million margin call on the New York Cotton
Exchange claims the leading cotton merchant is in financial trouble.
   Julien Hohenberg, founder and president of the Memphis company,
was unavailable for comment Tuesday at his office or residence.
   The lawsuit, filed Monday by PainWebber Inc., says The Julien
Co. failed to meet the margin call on Dec. 8, one day after a
similar call for $2 million.
   PaineWebber said it froze The Julien Co.'s account but was left
with a shortfall of $2.3 million.
   The lawsuit follows last week's sharp drop in cotton prices, and
market observers say that may have been partly caused by a major
merchant selling holdings to meet a margin call.
   ``Until this past week, The Julien Co. has always been very
prompt in satisfying margin calls,'' said the lawsuit, filed in
Shelby County Chancery Court.
   Brokers often allow a customer to trade on credit but if prices
fall below the customer's collateral he can be asked to meet that
margin by coming up with additional money.
   The Shelby County court issued orders barring The Julien Co.
from disposing of its assets, other than what is necessary in the
ordinary course of business.
   ``PaineWebber alleges upon information and belief that The
Julien Co. has recently incurred other substantial liabilities in
addition to its liabilities to PaineWebber,'' the lawsuit says.
   Industry observers say cotton prices have been low even though
the nation's cotton surplus is relatively small. Cutbacks in
purchases by textile mills and a large domestic cotton crop this
year may have attributed to that market sluggishness, the observers
say.
   The Julien Co. is a leading cotton merchant. Memphis has been a
center of cotton trade since Mississippi River paddlewheelers
brought in cotton from plantations throughout the Delta, and Julien
Hohenberg's family has been in the business since 1879.
   His family's business, Hohenberg Bros., was sold to Cargill,
Inc., in 1975 and became that company's cotton subsidiary.
Hohenberg, who had been president of the family business since
1961, continued to run Hohenberg Bros. until 1985 when he retired
and formed The Julien Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891212-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     12-12 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0421</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was mixed in moderate trading
today with blue-chip issues outperforming the rest of the field.
   At 2 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of 30
industrials was up 4.27 to 2,732.51.
   But declining issues outnumbered advances in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 723 up, 733 down and
504 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 115.48 million shares with two
hours to go.
   ``The big blue-chip names are OK,'' said Ralph J. Acampora,
technical analyst with Kidder, Peabody &amp; Co. ``It's under the
surface where the deterioration is.''
   Traders said the market generally was biding time until the
release on Friday of reports on the producer price index for
November and the October trade deficit. Friday also brings
expiration of stock-index futures and options.
   One apparent boost was the semiannual forecast by the National
Association of Purchasing Management that the economy would avert a
recession in 1990, although growth was expected to be only moderate.
   In the national over-the-counter market, Apple Computer was down
3 to 36\ in heavy trading. The company projected an earnings
decline and slowing sales growth for the first quarter of fiscal
1990.
   The announcement dragged down other technology issues, as well
as the broader over-the-counter market.
   Among other computer issues, Intel was down ] to 32, Compaq fell
1 to 80| after a weak earnings forecast, International Business
Machines was unchanged at 96[, Hewlett-Packard down { to 45\,
National Semiconductor down \ to 6} and Digital Equipment down [ to
83~.
   Among heavily traded Big Board stocks, Phillips Petroleum gained
1] to 25~ after announcing a major stock buyback Monday; Exxon
gained | to 50]; American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was up { to 44~,
one day after announcing job cuts that could total more than 30,000.
   Land's End slipped 2| to 21[ after reporting it expects fiscal
year earnings to be 13 percent lower than a year earlier. The
mail-order retailer tumbled 4| Monday after the announcement.
   Energy issues fared well as cold weather arrived in many parts
of the country. Atlantic Richfield was up 1} to 111}, Mobil traded
1\ higher to 62| and Pennzoil gained 1 to 87\.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
.45 to 193.28. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .73 at 375.77.
