<HEAD>Crop Futures Close Mixed In Quiet Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed narrowly
mixed Tuesday in quiet trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as
players waited for any news of export sales.
   Corn futures were pressured by a weekly Agriculture Department
report showing a lower-than-expected amount of corn inspected for
export last week.
   With bitter cold temperatures freezing shipping waterways in the
Midwest and Northeast, fears of a further export slowdown prompted
additional selling of grain futures.
   Lower European values for soybean products weighed on soybean
prices, as did news of substantial planting progress in Brazil, the
world's second-largest soybean producer.
   Wheat futures ended mostly higher, extending the gains tallied
Monday in anticipation of expanded grain sales to the Soviet Union.
   At the close, wheat futures were { cent lower to 1 cent higher
with the contract for delivery in December at $4.14 a bushel; corn
was 2\ cents lower to } cent higher with December at $2.32} a
bushel; oats were } cent lower to \ cent higher with December at
$1.44{ a bushel; soybeans were 2\ cents lower to 1} cents higher
with January at $5.76} a bushel.
