<FIRST>u f AM-PurchasersOutlook Bjt   12-12 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Purchasers Outlook, Bjt,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Next Year's Economic Growth Seen Moderate, But Optimism Fades</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Purchasing managers of the nation's corporations
think the economy will avoid a recession next year but optimism has
ebbed to the lowest level since the early 1980s, according to a
forecast released Thursday.
   The economy will be weak in the first half of 1990 and improve
during the remainder of the year, producing moderate growth
overall, the National Association of Purchasing Management's
semiannual forecast said.
   Inflation will ease further next year and should finish this
year milder than previously expected.
   Although a recession isn't forecast, more corporate purchasing
executives have indicated concern about economic conditions now
than ever before in the 27 years hhe association has asked its
members how they feel about the future.
   And fewer purchasers are optimistic than at any time since
September 1981 _when the economy was struggling in a recession.
   ``The exceptionally high level of concern about the economy in
1990 is overshadowed by the overall forecast of growth, albeit
moderate,'' said Robert J. Bretz, chairman of the association's
business survey committee.
   ``The basis for believing a recession will be averted and minor
growth achieved is the view that both exports and capital
expenditures will continue to be relatively strong against a
backdrop of a sharply lower rate of inflation,'' Bretz said.
   The threat of a recession or a severe slowdown heads the list of
concerns expressed by the purchasing managers. High labor and
benefit costs were the second most-mentioned worry, followed by
rising interest rates.
   Corporate purchasers monitor conditions closely because they
must make spending decisions based on such assumptions as how
business will be, how much inflation will erode buying power,
whether the cost of borrowing money will rise.
   The association's forecast, released at a news conference, said
64 percent of the members expect business to be better rather than
worse in 1990 than in 1989.
   Economic growth will average 5 percent next year, before
adjusting for inflation, with the second half of the year improving
from a weak first six months. Rising capital expenditures,
expanding exports and slowing imports will contribute to the
increase in economic output.
   Inflation will continue easing next year after registering lower
readings than expected in 1989, the forecast indicated. Purchasers
said their prices increased an average of 2.6 percent in 1989, down
from the 3.7 percent increase originally predicted for the year and
from the 5 percent reported for 1988.
   Next year, prices were predicted to rise an average of just 1.6
percent.
   ``Clearly this projects a continuing moderating trend in the
rate of inflation,'' Bretz, director of materials management at
Pitney Bowes Inc., said at the news conference.
   Ample supplies and reduced demand are keeping inflation in
check, Bretz said.
   For the overall outlook for the next 12 months, 64 percent of
the purchasers expressed concern. That was up from 57 percent when
the last survey was taken in May and the highest proportion in the
27 years the association has been asking its members to say whether
they feel ``worried-pessimistic,'' ``concerned'' or
``satisfied-optimistic.''
   Only 31 percent of the purchasers said they were satisfied or
optimistic about next year, down from 42 percent in May and 48
percent a year ago. That was the smallest percentage to express
that view since September 1981.
   The purchasers' group gathers information for its semiannual
reports from responses to questions put to purchasing executives in
more than 300 industrial companies nationwide.
   The Tempe, Ariz.-based group also does monthly reports on
business. The November report showed the manufacturing side of the
economy continued to decline for the seventh straight month.
</TEXT>
