<FIRST>u f PM-Helmsley 2ndLd-Writethru   12-12 0628</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0647</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hotel Queen Gets Four Years for Tax Evasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs. UPDATES throughout with quotes from judge, Helmsley.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY30</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sobbing Leona Helmsley was sentenced today to
four years in prison and fined $7.1 million by a judge who said
``naked greed'' prompted her to evade income taxes by billing her
hotel empire for personal items.
   ``No person, no matter how wealthy and prominent, stands above
the law,'' said U.S. District Judge John M. Walker Jr. told the
notoriously picky and sharp-tongued executive.
   ``Your conduct was a product of naked greed ... You believed you
were above the law and displayed no remorse or contrition,'' Walker
said.
   Walker also imposed 750 hours of community service at Hale
House, a home for infants born addicted to drugs, three years
probation and repayment of close to $2 million in unpaid taxes.
   He ordered the 69-year-old Mrs. Helmsley, who moments earlier
tearfully pleaded for mercy, to pay the costs incurred by the
federal probe and prosecution of the charges. Walker allowed Mrs.
Helmsley to remain free on an unspecified bail pending appeal.
   Mrs. Helmsley, her 80-year-old husband Harry seated three rows
away, was wracked with sobs as she told Walker, ``I'm more
humiliated and ashamed than anybody can ever imagine.''
   ``I am guilty of a serious crime. I feel like I'm in the middle
of a nightmare,'' she said.
   Mrs. Helmsley said she and her husband had been virtual
prisoners in their home for the past three years and said the media
had ripped open the grave of her late son during their coverage of
the trial.
   ``I beg you, don't let me lose Harry, too,'' she said, sobbing,
her cheeks flushed and stained with tears. ``Our whole life has
been work and each other. Please don't. We have nothing else.''
   Her attorney, Gerald Feffer, told Walker earlier that his client
had become a ``lightning rod'' for hate mail, death threats and
anti-Semitic remarks.
   ``She has been ridiculed, abused and humiliated in an
unprecedented way, having nothing to do with her wrongdoing,''
Feffer said.
   Two former Helmsley executives were also sentenced. Co-defendant
Joseph Licari received 30 months in prison, three years probation
and a $75,000 fine. Co-defendant Frank Turco received a two-year
term, three years probation and a $50,000 fine.
   Mrs. Helmsley was found guilty of evading federal taxes from
1983 through 1985, most of it by fraudulently billing $3.1 million
in expenses from the Helmsleys' Greenwich, Conn., mansion, Dunellen
Hall, to their $5 billion real estate empire.
   Among the expenses were more than $1 million for a pool
enclosure with a marble dance floor; jade figures worth $500,000,
and a $130,000 indoor-outdoor sound system. Other personal expenses
included groceries and $8 in underwear.
   The Helmsleys have extensive real estate holdings and own 27
hotels. Helmsley was indicted along with his wife but found
mentally incompetent to stand trial.
   In magazine ads that are still published, Mrs. Helmsley is
portrayed as the ``queen'' of the Helmsley luxury hotels, a regal
perfectionist with an eagle eye for the slightest thing out of
place.
   In court, she was depicted as an abusive, penny-pinching tyrant
_ part of a defense strategy of arguing that the phony billing
scheme was orchestrated by employees to avoid contact with Mrs.
Helmsley, who was labeled by her own lawyer, Gerald Feffer, as a
``tough bitch.''
   According to testimony, Mrs. Helmsley ordered that bottles be
returned for the nickel deposit and once told her housekeeper, ``We
don't pay taxes. Only the little people pay taxes.''
   Feffer had argued the Helmsleys did nothing wrong in billing
their companies for part of their household expenses because they
used the estate for business.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
