<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-12 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0517</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off On Mark's Strength; Gold Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Germany's mark dominated foreign exchange
trading Tuesday, strengthening on firm interest rates in that
country and talk of a reunified Germany that helped sharply depress
the dollar and other currencies. In both New York and Europe, the
dollar hit a one-year low against the mark, traders said.
   ``The scenario here is that interest rates in Germany will stay
firm ... while U.S. rates are trending down because the economy is
slowing,'' said Earl I. Johnson, a currency trader at Harris Trust
&amp; Co. in Chicago.
   ``It's not so much the dollar's weakness as it is the mark's
strength. The mark is the place to be right now.''
   The mark has risen sharply in recent weeks amid rapid political
and economic reforms in East Germany. Traders speculate that West
Germany's economy will flourish, pushing interest rates higher, as
boundaries between east and west diminish.
   High interest rates tend to support a currency.
   The dollar was quoted in London at 1.7335 marks, off from 1.7660
marks late Monday, and in New York at 1.73225 marks, down from
1.7610. Both closing rates were the lowest since December 1988,
according to traders.
   The dollar also dipped below 6.00 French francs for the first
time since Dec. 16, 1988, finishing at 5.9275 francs in Europe,
down from 6.0370 francs late Monday. It finished at 5.9185 francs
in New York, down from 6.0200.
   Against the British pound the dollar also weakened. Sterling
rose to $1.6027 from $1.5895 in London late Monday, and $1.6085
from $1.5937 in New York.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with Monday's late
quotes, included: 1.5732 Swiss francs, down from 1.5915; 1,284.75
Italian lire, down from 1,301.00; and 1.16255 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.16375.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with Monday: 1.5765 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5970; 1.9715 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9950;
1,285.75 Italian lire, down from 1,304.25; and 1.1625 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1632.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.18 yen to close at 144.47 yen. It traded
at 143.80 yen in London, and 143.975 yen in New York, down from
144.375 Monday.
   Meanwhile, gold prices rose here and abroad.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $417.90 a troy ounce, up $1.10 from Monday.
Republic National Bank in New York quoted a late bid for gold at
$417 an ounce, up 60 cents.
   In London, gold rose to a late bid price of $417.50 an ounce
from $416.75 Monday. Gold closed in Zurich at $416.75 an ounce, up
$1.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $4.40 at $416.95 an ounce.
   But silver prices slipped. On New York's Comex, silver bullion
for current delivery settled at $5.672 a troy ounce, down from
$5.692. In London, the late bid for silver was $5.70 an ounce, down
4 cents.
</TEXT>
