<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1931EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-FarmCrops     12-12 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Farm Crops,0431</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Cotton Crop Shrinks From Last Year</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1989 cotton crop is expected to be
slightly less than 12.1 million bales, down 22 percent from last
year's harvest but virtually the same as estimated in November, the
Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   In its new estimate based on field conditions as of Dec. 1, the
department's National Agricultural Statistics Service said a 20
percent drop in the acreage for harvest and slightly lower yields
account for the decline from 1988 levels.
   ``The Delta states experienced favorable weather during harvest
and show and increase from last month,'' the report said. ``In
Texas, an October freeze lowered expected yields.''
   Orange production was forecast at 194 million boxes, unchanged
from the previous forecast two months ago based on Oct. 1
indications but 6 percent below last season.
   ``This decline is due mostly to Florida's 11 percent decrease
from last season,'' the report said. ``Freezing weather in Florida
during late February killed some of the open bloom and damaged new
growth.''
   The report also indicated dry edible bean production this year
at 24.1 million hundredweight, up 25 percent from last year's
drought-reduced harvest but still 7 percent short of 1987
production. Acreage for harvest was up 24 percent from last year
kand the average yield, at 1,436 pounds per acre, was up 1 percent.
   Burley tobacco production was estimated at 543 million pounds,
up 14 percent from 1988 but fractionally below the November
forecast. The area for harvest is up 13 percent from last year and
the average yield is up 18 pounds per acre.
   No new estimates were issued for the major field crops such as
corn, wheat and soybeans.
   In a related report, the department's world outlook board said
prospective levels of cotton production and use in 1989 remain at
near the levels indicated last month, although production prospects
are up on a few foreign countries.
   ``This likely will mean reduced needs for U.S. cotton in world
markets and lower U.S. export prospects,'' the report said.
   The global outlook for wheat is ``largely unchanged'' the
November forecast, the report said. For corn, sorghum, oats and
other so-called coarse grains, 1989-90 production and inventories a
year from now are expected to be down marginally from last month's
outlook.
   ``Larger output is forecast for Canada, Eastern Europe and
Australia,'' the report said. ``However, these gains are more than
offset by smaller crops in the Sudan, Argentina, Mexico and several
other countries.''
</TEXT>
