<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     12-12 0277</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices finished mixed Tuesday
with wholesale home heating oil rising as crude oil and gasoline
declined.
   Energy market analysts said a late round of selling defused a
rally that had carried the January crude oil contract near its
highs.
   The contract for January delivery of West Texas Intermediate,
the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 5 cents to $20.65 per
barrel, erasing a portion of Monday's 22-cent increase. The
February through April contracts posted larger declines.
   The January contract for No.2 heating oil rose 0.35 cent to
67.30 cents a gallon on the New York Mercantile Exchange, adding to
Monday's gain of 0.58 cent. But contracts for delivery during
February through April fell by amounts ranging from 0.27 cent to
0.68 cent.
   The nearby heating oil contract gained support from cold weather
in the United States and abroad. Oil demand in Europe has been
bolstered by low water levels on the Rhine River, which has reduced
output of hydroelectric power.
   Among other refined products traded on the New York Merc,
wholesale unleaded gasoline for January delivery, which sank 0.25
cent on Monday, dropped another 0.37 cent to 52.03 cents a gallon.
Other contracts also closed lower.
   Demand for gasoline usually slows in late autumn and winter so
prices typically ease.
   Energy broker Eugene Croutier, of E.D.&amp;F. Man International
Futures Inc., said once January crude oil rose past $20.80 late in
the session, sellers started unloading the contract. They were
acting on the assumption that the contract would open lower on
Wednesday, as it had reached the price objective that traders were
expecting.
</TEXT>
