<FIRST>r f BC-ControlData-Soviets     12-12 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Control Data-Soviets,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seeks Permission to Sell Computers to Soviets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Control Data Corp. is seeking U.S.
government approval to sell the Soviet Union six mainframe
computers that would be used to improve the safety of civilian
nuclear power plants, company officials said.
   One of the computers would be installed at the site of the 1986
nuclear accident in Chernobyl, the company said Monday. The Cyber
962 computers would be sold under a $32 million, 1-year contract.
   The rule banning high-tech exports to the Soviet Union recently
was lifted. Computer sales to the Soviets has been a touchy issue
because of concerns by U.S. officials that high-powered computers
could be used for such military purposes as designing weapons.
   The Cyber 962 computer is about three years old and does not
represent the latest technology, said James Ousley, president of
Control Data's computer products group. It falls well below the
performance level of supercomputers, used by the United States to
design nuclear weapons.
   Control Data long has had business ties with the Soviet Union,
but it has not sold a machine there since 1978. It applied for an
export license for the $32 million deal last month.
   Representatives of the Commerce, Energy and Defense departments
and the Nuclear Regulatory Commission are expected to rule on the
request this spring.
   ``The environment is much better for a sale of this type,'' said
Ousley. He said he expected Commerce and Energy department
officials to be enthusiastic about the sale but said defense
officials may express reservations.
   Control Data would have to supply on-site inspection and build
in safeguards to ensure that the mainframes would be used for the
stated purpose, Ousley said.
</TEXT>
