<FIRST>r f AM-Videotex-Canada     12-12 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Videotex-Canada,0610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bell Canada Claiming Success for Videotex Pilot Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Videotex Outlook, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SOLL SUSSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bell Canada claims to be reaching goals for its
ALEX videotex system here months ahead of schedule and is expanding
to small business customers as well as preparing for a debut next
year in Toronto.
   The two-year pilot project offering interactive services in
words and graphics through household terminals started a year ago
with the target of 20,000 customers in the Montreal area.
   ``It's very easy to use,'' Sylvie Bastien, a Bell Canada
spokeswoman, said in offering a demonstration. ``You don't need to
be a computer expert.''
   Bell Canada had been issuing regular progress reports on the
number of subscribers to ALEX that showed a slow start but steady
rise in the project's early months. The first weeks last December
were plagued by distribution difficulties.
   Mrs. Bastien said the goal of 20,000 residential customers was
reached in June but the company will no longer release updates on
the number of subscribers because it is valuable information for
competitors.
   Bell Canada operates primarily in Quebec and Ontario, Canada's
two most populous provinces.
   Although videotex systems have had some spectacular failures in
the United States, they have been popular in other countries such
as France where the Minitel system is used extensively.
   ALEX takes its name from Alexander Graham Bell, who emigrated to
Canada from Scotland before inventing the telephone while teaching
at a school for the deaf in Boston.
   The number of services available through ALEX does not approach
the more than 10,000 offered in France, but Mrs. Bastien said Bell
Canada has been pleased with its progress in a new field.
   From about 100 services available at the outset, the number has
risen steadily to 480. Among the services offered in French and
English are real estate listings, market reports, traffic
information, horoscopes, home shopping and bill paying, and news
and weather.
   ``You see how fast it goes,'' Mrs. Bastien said. ``We're very
happy because we didn't even think we would reach 300 services in
seven months.''
   About 60 percent of ALEX's customers rent the special terminal,
about the size of a small television set, from Bell Canada for a
monthly fee of $6.75. The others obtain the ALEX software to use
the system through their personal computers.
   The system plugs into any phone line.
   The average monthly bill is about $34, Mrs. Bastien said, but a
few customers have become addicted and run up higher bills than
their budgets could sustain.
   A clock runs on the screen showing how many minutes have been
used up on any connection. Some services are free, others run from
5 cents to 38 cents per minute.
   Bell Canada only rents the equipment. The services are provided
by other companies, and the most popular are electronic mailboxes
that Mrs. Bastien described as ``pale pink _ it's nothing obscene.''
   Mrs. Bastien said ALEX was envisioned as being for residential
customers but enough requests have come in from small businesses to
prompt the expansion. Final rate approval from government
regulators was pending on the plan.
   Bell Canada has applied to expand to Toronto, Canada's largest
city and its financial center, in April. It also is seeking
regulatory approval to change the formal status of ALEX from a
two-year trial to a continuing commercial service.
   The Canadian government was involved in developing the Telidon
videotex system that is the basis for ALEX. It was turned over to
private companies for further development.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
