<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1756EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-VideotexOutlook Bjt   12-12 0864</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Videotex Outlook, Bjt,0890</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM-Sears Computer Service Seems to Be Catching On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There are better ways to get publicity, but a
fight between homosexuals and Christian fundamentalists
nevertheless has called attention to the rapid growth of a home
computer service owned by IBM and Sears.
   The Prodigy service has expanded to a quarter-million
subscribers in 160,000 homes from 30,000 homes a year ago. It
serves 21 of the nation's largest markets, up from six a year ago.
   Prodigy is a risky venture that still is losing money and might
not catch on. But analysts say it seems to stand a good chance
because its formula appeals to the do-it-yourself, do-it-now spirit
in its target market of affluent American families.
   If Prodigy does succeed, its backers will be sitting pretty _
numerous previous failures show the videotex market is costly and
difficult to penetrate. As it is, Prodigy's expansion is taking a
heavy investment by the nation's biggest computer company and its
biggest retailer.
   ``I think Prodigy has learned a lot from the people who have
gone before. They're losing a ton of money. That's in their
business plan. But it's also in their business plan for this to
catch on in a big, big way,'' said Efrem Sigel, president of
Communications Trends Inc. in Larchmont, N.Y.
   Prodigy allows people to bank, shop, trade stocks, read news,
play games, chat or teach themselves, via their home computer. It
costs a flat $10 a month.
   Other home computer services such as CompuServe, Genie, Bix and
Delphi charge by the hour and are more geared to true computer
enthusiasts.
   CompuServe, the nation's biggest service with about 600,000
subscribers, is trying to appeal to a broader audience by making
its screens more uniform and its commands simpler to understand.
CompuServe, which is owned by the H.&amp;R. Block Inc. tax service,
already is profitable.
   Prodigy's adverse publicity came in the past week after it
canceled a chat service named Health Spa, an electronic ``bulletin
board'' that allowed subscribers to post notices or communicate on
health-related issues.
   Prodigy said Health Spa was canceled because of low usage, but
some subscribers said it was because one section of Health Spa had
turned into a forum for a heated debate on homosexuality between
gays and fundamentalist Christians.
   Dozens of subscribers have been demanding the return of Health
Spa _ an unintentional testament to the popularity of Prodigy's
services.
   Chatting on ``bulletin boards'' such as Health Spa is more
popular than anyone at Prodigy had predicted, but it is a small
part of the service in comparison to services such as banking and
shopping.
   More Americans became do-it-yourselfers in the 1980s, with the
proliferation of automated teller machines, mail-order catalogs and
self-service gasoline stations.
   Prodigy is aimed at upper-income people with home computers who
want to do things themselves for reasons of convenience, variety
and control.
   One such person is Jonathan Beacher, a traveling consultant to
television stations. Beacher, who lives in the Atlanta area, says
he saved $2,500 on airline fares in the first three or four months
by booking flights himself. He also pays bills through the bank by
computer, while his wife orders groceries and his children chat
with friends, play video games and use the encyclopedia.
   To Beacher, Prodigy is a little like a microwave oven _ it's
hard to imagine life without it.
   ``Before we had a microwave oven here, we thought, `Oh my gosh,
the food will taste terrible.' But you end up doing whole new kinds
of cooking.''
   Complaints about Prodigy range from its relative slowness _ the
fancy, user-friendly graphics are a drag on the computer _ to
questions about its usefulness.
   Many people still would rather get news from newspapers, weather
from television and groceries from a trip to the supermarket.
Computer phobia is prevalent and even people who use computers at
work may not be enthusiastic about using them at home.
   Aware of the difficulties, American Telephone &amp; Telegraph Co.
seems to be steering clear of videotex even though it was freed to
enter the arena by a federal judge's order in July.
   ``Videotex is sort of the most glamorous but also the most
expensive way to get into electronic publishing,'' said AT&amp;T
spokesman Michael Keady, noting that many companies have failed in
it. Spokesman Jim Byrnes called it ``a technology in search of a
market,'' indicating AT&amp;T might be more likely to get into
audiotex, which involves voice messages.
   Ray LaMadeleine, a commercial real estate agent in Glendale,
Calif., said Prodigy is establishing a position for itself that
will be hard to dislodge if videotex does catch on _ as
International Business Machines Corp. and Sears, Roebuck &amp; Co. are
betting it will.
   ``Others who try to climb in and start from scratch, they better
be prepared to sped the same kind of bucks, because I don't think
there's any cheaper way to do it,'' LaMadeleine said.
   Prodigy will not comment on how much it has spent or when it
hopes to turn a profit.
   ``Suffice it to say that it is a long-term business
proposition,'' said Prodigy spokesman Brian Ek.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
