<FIRST>r f AM-Chrysler-Subcompacts     12-12 0353</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler-Subcompacts,0364</SECOND>
<HEAD>No New Subcompacts From Chrysler Until Mid 1990s</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. said Tuesday it will not build any
subcompact cars until the mid-1990s after it stops production of
its Dodge Omni and Plymouth Horizon.
   Chrysler marketing vice president John Damoose said the company
will offer a stripped-down version of its compact Dodge Shadow and
Plymouth Sundance until a replacement subcompact is in production.
   But he said the new subcompact probably will not go into
production until after cars derived from the LH and LX platforms
are introduced, scheduled for the fall of 1992.
   Chrysler is to halt production of the Omni and Horizon in early
February when it shuts down its Jefferson Avenue assembly plant in
Detroit. The company has said slow sales spurred the shutdown, but
the United Auto Workers union contends Chrysler wants to cut costs.
   According to Ward's Automotive Reports, a weekly industry
newsletter, subcompact cars made up 13.1 percent of the total U.S.
car market. The Omni and Horizon, the only subcompacts built by
Chrysler, comprised 8 percent of the automaker's car sales of about
959,128 through Nov. 30.
   Damoose outlined for reporters Chrysler's plans for the North
American International Auto Show in Detroit next month, where it
will feature its new Dodge Stealth sports car, the new Dodge Monaco
being built in Canada a LeBaron sedan and a new Jeep.
   Damoose said Chrysler planned to build 25,000 to 30,000 Stealth
cars to compete in the same market as the Mazda RX-7 and the Nissan
300ZX. No price has been set forthe car, which goes on sale in
October.
   He also said Chrysler production planners forecast the company
will hold its 13.8 percent share of the U.S. car and light truck
market in 1990 as sales for the entire industry tumble to about
14.2 million vehicles.
   Chrysler's 1990 sales estimate is the lowest of the Big Three.
General Motors Corp. officials estimate that about 15 million
vehicles will be sold next year and Ford Motor Co. executives put
the volume at about 14.7 million, slightly below 1989 sales.
</TEXT>
