<FIRST>u f AM-MillerRhoads     12-12 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Miller Rhoads,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>May Co. Buying Four Miller &amp; Rhoads Stores</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE GEARAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four of ailing Miller &amp; Rhoads Inc.'s
stores will be sold to St. Louis-based retail giant May Department
Stores Co. for about $22.7 million, Miller &amp; Rhoads president John
E. Stokely said Tuesday.
   The four stores, two in Richmond and two in Hampton Roads, will
be added to the May-owned Hecht Co. chain next month, Stokely said.
The purchase price does not include the four stores' merchandise,
which May has agreed to buy, he said.
   The sale is effective Jan. 15, contingent on approval from U.S.
Bankruptcy Judge Douglas O. Tice Jr. who is overseeing Miller &amp;
Rhoads' liquidation, May President Thomas A. Hays told a
Washington, D.C., news conference.
   Arlington-based Hecht's has 22 stores in northern Virginia,
Washington and Maryland. The chain is expected to make job offers
to ``a significant number'' of Miller &amp; Rhoads workers at the four
stores, Stokely said.
   ``As the largest retailer in Washington-Baltimore, we have been
serving customers for almost 130 years and we are very pleased to
be able to extend our service to the Richmond and Tidewater
areas,'' Hecht's President Irwin Zazulia told reporters.
   Hecht's plans to invest $8 million in fixtures, displays and
other upgrades at the four stores, Zazulia said. Long-range plans
include the possibility of adding a store in suburban Richmond and
another in the Tidewater area, Zazulia said.
   Hecht's also plans to open new stores in Waldorf, Md. in 1990
and Woodbridge, Va. in 1992, Zazulia said.
   An earlier news conference called by May for Nov. 28 was
postponed because May and Miller &amp; Rhoads executives needed more
time to hammer out the deal, May officials said.
   Stokely said the company continues to seek buyers for the 10
other stores in the chain, including Richmond's flagship downtown
store.
   Miller &amp; Rhoads, a major Richmond retailer for more than a
century, sought for protection from creditors under Chapter 11 of
federal bankruptcy laws in July.
   The sale of the four stores is part of a liquidation plan the
company filed Nov. 28 in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
   May, which had sales of about $11.5 billion last year, has
embarked on an aggressive expansion plan and allocated $3.7 billion
for expansion this year.
   May owns 14 department store chains, one discount chain and a
nationwide self-service shoe chain, Payless ShoeSource.
   Hecht's is third among May's department store chains in sales,
with $759 million last year.
</TEXT>
