<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-12 0651</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gold Takes A Breather, Then Edges Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Gold futures prices inched nearer to new highs for the year
Tuesday on New York's Commodity Exchange after taking a quick
breather from their energetic advance of the previous five sessions.
   On other commodity markets, silver futures slipped; oil futures
were mostly lower; grains and soybeans were mixed; and livestock
and meat futures were mixed.
   Gold futures settled 80 cents to $1.10 higher with the contract
for delivery in December up $1.10 at $417.90 a troy ounce, just
$1.80 shy of the 1989 high of $419.70 set Nov. 24.
   Silver futures finished 2 cents to 2.2 cents lower with December
at $5.672 a troy ounce.
   Gold has rallied from $401 an ounce in the past six sessions.
But the bulls appeared to be weakening early in Tuesday's
back-and-forth trading, which saw the December contract dip as low
as $415.30 before recovering late in the session.
   Analysts said investors were drawn from the gold market by
strong advances in the stock market and in the British pound and
West German mark.
   Nevertheless, they said, uneasiness about the shifting political
climate of Eastern Europe should continue to stir investment demand
for gold and support the market.
   ``At this point, the market is catching its breath and getting
ready for the next phase, the upside phase,'' said Bette
Raptopoulos, a metals analyst in New York with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   Heating oil for January delivery rose for the 10th straight
session on the New York Mercantile Exchange as bitterly cold
weather seized the Northeast. But all other energy futures prices
fell ahead of late Tuesday's weekly inventory report from the
American Petroleum Institute.
   The API said U.S. stocks of crude oil fell by 8.2 million
barrels last week. The number was far above market expectations and
is likely to prompt buying of crude futures on Wednesday.
   The API reported a reduction of nearly 3 million barrels in U.S.
stocks of petroleum distillates, which include heating oil. The
number was near the high end of market expectations.
   Gasoline stocks rose by about 500,000 barrels, as expected.
   West Texas Intermediate crude futures settled 5 cents to 42
cents lower with the contract for delivery in January at $20.65 a
barrel; heating oil was .53 cent lower to .35 cent higher with
January at 67.30 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .35 cent to
.50 cent lower with January at 52.03 cents a gallon.
   Grain and soybean futures finished narrowly mixed in quiet
trading on the Chicago Board of Trade as players awaited news of
new export sales.
   After the close, the Agriculture Department announced a sale of
about 104,000 metric tons of U.S. corn to the Soviet Union.
   The USDA also announced that talks on a new long-term grain
agreement between the superpowers would probably begin in February.
The location for the talks has not been set.
   Wheat futures settled { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
December at $4.13{ a bushel; corn was 2 cents lower to } cent
higher with December at $2.33 a bushel; oats were } cent lower to \
cent higher with December at $1.44{ a bushel; soybeans were 2 cents
lower to 1} cents higher with January at $5.77 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures were supported by strong spot markets; pork
futures were pressured by lower wholesale pork-belly prices and
signs of continuing slack demand for bacon.
   Live cattle finished .40 cent lower to .23 cent higher with
December at 76.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to
.25 cent higher with January at 83.37 cents a pound; live hogs were
.23 cent lower to .25 cent higher with December at 50.92 cents a
pound; frozen pork bellies 2 cents lower to .80 cent higher with
February at 50.37 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
