<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 1814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-IBMService     12-12 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-IBM Service,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Upgrades Service Offerings for Mainframes, PCs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On the prowl for new sources of revenue,
International Business Machines Corp. on Tuesday announced upgraded
service offerings for customers who buy its mainframe computers and
personal computers.
   The announcement comes as IBM struggles with a price war that
has slashed profits across all segments of its product line. The
company last week announced plans to cut another 10,000 jobs next
year.
   IBM's upgraded its service offerings in response to requests
from customers, said Pat Kearney, vice president for software
services for IBM's National Service Division in Franklin Lakes, N.J.
   ``For some time our customers have been asking us to provide
these services. For some time we have been saying `no' to them, if
I may be so blunt,'' Ms. Kearney said. Now, she said, IBM is saying
yes.
   IBM should be able to recruit customers easily because ``if you
don't like what you're getting you'll just stop,'' said Sam Albert,
a consultant in Scarsdale, N.Y.
   For personal computers, IBM has established a center in Tampa,
Fla., that will take calls around the clock, seven days a week,
from customers having problems with any brand of personal computer,
software or peripheral equipment such as printers.
   The service is intended for big accounts with hundreds of PCs.
IBM says it has hired or trained people who are knowledgeable about
non-IBM equipment, including machines such as Macintoshes from
Apple Computer Inc.
   For mainframes, IBM is letting customers have direct access to
an internal IBM data bank that contains typical problems with
mainframes and recommended solutions. For an extra charge,
customers can get other levels of service in which IBM would become
intimately involved in running the company's central computer
system.
   Digital Equipment Corp., IBM's closest rival, said it also has
service offerings that include maintenance of equipment from other
suppliers.
</TEXT>
