<FIRST>r f AM-Argentina-Economy 1stLd-Writethru f0127 12-12 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0127,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Banks Reopen; Immediate Gap Between Official, Free Market Austral</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: UPDATES throughout with gap between official and free market
rates widening by day's end; ADDS new information on rise in bus, plane
fares</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Banks reopened Tuesday after a
24-hour holiday ordered by the government when it devalued the
austral by 34.5 percent.
   But the devaluation intended to narrow the gap between
Argentina's official and free market currency rates had little
immediate success, as the gap widened 23 percent by day's end.
   Meanwhile, the government disclosed the last part of its
economic adjustment plan would include hikes in state-controlled
prices of public services.
   When financial institutions opened, the austral sold for about
1,000 for every U.S. dollar, the official rate set Sunday night,
when the government hiked gasoline prices by about 60 percent.
   When markets closed, foreign exchange houses offered dollars for
1,230 australs apiece.
   The gap between the official and free market rates led to the
devaluation, the second in five months.
   Businessmen in general favored the changes, which they said were
necessary for economic stability. Nevertheless, some insisted the
government of President Carlos Menem make deeper cuts in state
spending, and speed up the program of privatizations and
deregulation.
   Groups representing the important agricultural industry, which
has withheld from the central bank the dollars earned from overseas
sales of beef and grain, criticized the government for increasing
export taxes at the same time it devalued the austral.
   Farmers stood to reap windfall gains from the devaluation, which
would have put more australs in their pockets from every dollar
they turned in. Export taxes _ a major source of government revenue
_ were increased by about 11 percent.
   Starting Wednesday, the cheapest bus ticket will rise 86 percent
to 130 australs, while domestic plane fares will cost 62 percent
more.
   President Menem defended the measures, saying the goal ``is to
achieve the stability of the economy.''
   ``Of course there may be protests, but it is the only way out
for Argentina which is emerging little by little from a sad
situation of inflation and hyperinflation,'' Menem told reporters.
   Thus far, the changes had not prompted any protests by
Argentines, officials said.
</TEXT>
