<FIRST>r f AM-Earns-CampeauUnits     12-12 0413</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Campeau Units,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Combined Quarterly Losses Total $106.8 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. department store divisions of heavily
indebted Campeau Corp. on Tuesday reported combined quarterly
losses totaling $106.8 million.
   Federated Department Stores Inc., operator of Bloomingdale's,
Burdines, Lazarus and other chains, lost $70.6 million in the three
months ended Oct. 28. Allied Stores Corp., which runs Jordan Marsh,
Stern's and others, lost $36.2 million during that quarter.
   Both department store groups reported sales and losses on a
comparable division basis, restating 1988 results to exclude
holdings that have been sold.
   Federated's third quarter loss came on sales of $1.23 billion,
compared with losses of $43.4 million on sales of $1.11 billion in
the comparable quarter a year earlier.
   Allied reported third-quarter sales of $654.8 million, compared
with sales of $611.4 million a year earlier when the company had a
loss of $19.4 million.
   Commenting on their losses, the two divisions each said that
``such a negative income position would be expected for its
operations in these periods because more than half of the annual
retail profits traditionally are produced in the fourth quarter,
while interest expenses on debt remains constant throughout the
year.''
   Allied and Federated are based in Cincinnati while the parent
company has its headquarters in Toronto.
   Campeau's quarterly report, released separately in Toronto, said
the company had a net loss of $105 million from continuing
operations during the quarter, compared with a net loss of $78
million during the same quarter of 1988.
   Federated noted that on Oct. 28, it operated 131 department
stores in 19 states. Its five retained divisions include Abraham &amp;
Strauss, Bloomingdale's, Burdines, Lazarus and Rich's.
   The 17-store Bloomingdale's chain has been put up for sale as
part of a plan to help Campeau cope with a cash crunch. Campeau has
said that several parties have expressed interest in buying the
chain.
   Allied operated 127 department stores in 16 states among its
retained divisions, which are Jordan Marsh, Stern's, Maas@Jordan
Marsh Florida, and The Bon Marche.
   Federated reported a nine-month, pre-tax loss of $277.3 million
on sales of $3.28 billion, compared with a loss of $211.9 million
on sales of $3.01 billion in the corresponding period of last year.
   Allied's nine-month loss was $135.8 million on sales of $1.81
billion, compared with $158.1 million on sales of $1.7 billion last
year.
   Campeau said it lost $296 million through three quarters of this
year significantly wider than last year's nine-month loss of $14
million.
</TEXT>
