<FIRST>r f AM-Emerson-Acquisitions     12-12 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Emerson-Acquisitions,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Emerson Buys Two Companies For $595 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emerson Electric Co., a major producer of
electric motors, on Tuesday purchased Leroy-Somer SA, Europe's top
maker of electric motors, for $460 million.
   Industry analysts said the acquisition could make Emerson the
world's leading manufacturer of electric motors.
   ``My guess is this puts Emerson over the top, probably by a
decent margin,'' said Kent Newcomb, an industry analyst for A.G.
Edwards in St. Louis. ``Relative to what the company was making,
the price looks pretty high, but it's a strategic acquisition. And
it's probably cheaper than putting up the brick and mortars from
scratch.''
   In addition to acquiring Leroy-Somer of France, the St.
Louis-based company also announced the $135 million purchase of
McGill Manufacturing Co., a Valparaiso, Ind., company that makes
bearings and electrical products.
   Aside from prepared statements announcing the acquisitions,
company officials were unavailable for comment.
   Emerson, which is also a leading producer of industrial
monitoring equipment, tools and components for appliances, had
annual sales of $7.1 billion in 1989. The company had operations in
15 countries in 1988.
   Craig Krapf, an analyst for Edward D. Jones &amp; Co. in St. Louis,
said the acquisition of Leroy-Sommer is in line with Emerson's
growth strategy in the last six years.
   ``Emerson has done a fantastic job of improving profitability at
smaller firms,'' Krapf said. ``They've got a knack for that.''
   The Leroy-Somer acquisition, which is subject to U.S. and French
regulatory approval, gives Emerson a chance to increase its
presence in the European Economic Community before 1992, when the
12-nation bloc becomes a single unified market.
   In addition to its U.S. divisions, Emerson has some electric
motor divisions in Japan, Canada and Mexico.
   Leroy-Somer is a manufacturer of integral and fractional
horsepower electric motors and drives for industrial markets, with
manufacturing facilities primarily in France.
   Emerson said when the deal is completed, it will sell
Leroy-Somer's King Bearing unit, which is based in the United
States.
   McGill, the largest employer in Valparaiso, makes bearings and
electrical products primarily for industrial uses.
   ``The acquisition adds a premier brand name to Emerson's power
transmission business, and McGill's electrical products are a nice
complement to the products of our other divisions,'' said Jim Orso,
a spokesman for Emerson's public relations firm, Fleishman-Hillard.
</TEXT>
