<FIRST>u f AM-JMB     12-12 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-JMB,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Say JMB Joins Bidding for Bloomies and Hilton</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf to UPDATE with Hilton general counsel saying company
does not expect deal to close before end of the year; pickup 8th graf,
``In a.''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   JMB Realty Corp. reportedly is bidding for
Bloomingdale's department stores and Hilton Hotels Corp., and an
industry analyst said Tuesday both properties would mesh with the
international firm's expansion strategy.
   JMB, a real estate investment, management and development firm,
is one of at least six bidders for all or part of Hilton, which
went on the market in May, the Wall Street Journal reported in
Tuesday's editions.
   The Chicago Tribune reported that JMB _ which owns a glitzy
downtown mall anchored by Bloomingdale's Chicago store _ is among
several bidders for the 17-store chain.
   Burton Glazov, JMB's executive director, declined to comment on
the reports.
   Neither potential acquisition would be a first for JMB, which
owns the Liberty House retail chain in Hawaii and several hotels,
including the Ritz Carlton and Four Seasons in Chicago, and the
Century Plaza in Los Angeles, Glazov said.
   A spokeswoman for Toronto-based Campeau Corp., Bloomingdale's
parent, declined comment Tuesday on the reports.
   Hilton does not expect any deal to close before the end of this
year, said William Lebo Jr., general counsel for the Beverly Hills,
Calif.-based company. He declined to comment on the bidding or the
Journal story.
   In a statement issued Friday, the deadline for Bloomingdale's
bids, Campeau said it had ``received a number of expressions of
interest from parties seeking to acquire the 17-store chain.'' The
statement said details are confidential and that Campeau would not
further discuss the ``first stage'' of the sale.
   Campeau has said it expects to pare the list of prospective
buyers ``to no more than five or six finalists'' who will receive
more detailed information in preparation for the sale, expected to
be completed by February.
   The sale price has been estimated at between $1 billion and $1.3
billion.
   JMB is a privately held corporation with holdings in Chicago and
other major U.S. and Canadian cities are worth more than $21
billion, said spokesman Dennis Waite.
   ``A connection has existed for a while between JMB and
Bloomingdale's in that ... there was a joint venture with Federated
Department stores ... in developing shopping centers and
Bloomingdale's was anchor in some of those malls,'' Waite said by
telephone Tuesday.
   Bloomingdale's is part of the Federated chain acquired by
Campeau in 1988. JMB acquired Federated's shopping
center-development arm in 1984.
   Waite also declined to comment on the reported bids.
   Louis Masotti, a professor of management and urban development
at Northwestern University, said he had not heard about JMB's
reported interest in the two high-profile properties, but added,
``I wouldn't be surprised'' if they're true.
   ``There isn't anything for sale that they don't try to buy,''
Masotti said in a telephone interview Tuesday.
   ``They seem to be targeting the name brands that don't require a
great deal of advertising to put them in contention for national
markets but do require a certain amount of capital and management
skills, both of which JMB seems to have in abundance,'' he said.
   The Journal reported Monday that besides JMB, other bidders for
Bloomingdale's are: Bahrain-based investment bank Investcorp
International, Bloomingdale's Chairman Marvin Traub and Ann Taylor
Inc. Chairman Joseph Brooks.
   Other possible bidders include such established retail companies
as Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp. and May Co. of St. Louis,
which have declined comment on their possible interest in the
chain, the Tribune said.
</TEXT>
