<FIRST>u f BC-ProgramTrading 1stLd-Writethru f0110 12-12 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Program Trading, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0110,0398</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bear Stearns To Resume Computerized Trading Strategy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3-5 grafs with congressional reax; Picks up 3rd
graf pvs bg'ng, Bear, Stearns ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bear, Stearns &amp; Co. said Tuesday it was resuming
limited computerized program trading, but it promised to follow
several standards aimed at reducing market volatility.
   The company is the first among the major Wall Street firms to
resume index arbitrage trades for its own account. Several
brokerages abandoned such activity last month amid criticism it was
dangerously distorting the stock market and scaring away small
investors.
   The move prompted criticism in Washington, where legislation
that would allow the Securities and Exchange Commission to restrict
program trading was introduced before Congress.
   ``Bear Stearns' statement today shows why voluntary measures
restraining program trading don't work,'' said Rep. Edward Markey,
D-Mass., chairman of a House committee that investigated the
effects of program trading this past fall.
   ``It's like making red lights optional. It's too much to ask
traders to refrain on a voluntary basis from making money. I
believe their actions make the perfect case for the passage of
legislation which grants the SEC the authority to prohibit or
constrain manipulative or abusive trading practices which led to
artificial volatility,'' he added.
   Bear, Stearns said it would abandon all index arbitrage if the
Dow Jones Industrial Average is down 50 points. It also promised to
adhere to industry guidelines in observance of all trading halts,
or circuit breakers, during wild price swings in the market.
   In addition, Bear, Stearns said it would follow the so-called
uptick rule which was enacted to control excesses in short selling
of individual stocks. Short sellers borrow shares, then immediately
sell them for cash because they expect the price of a stock to
plummet. The short seller makes a profit by buying the replacement
shares at the lower price.
   Index arbitrage involves stock-index futures, or contracts to
buy and sell baskets of stocks based on particular indexes like the
Standard &amp; Poor's 500 index. These contracts have come to represent
a bigger market than that of common stocks, albeit with higher
stakes.
   Using computer programs, traders seek to capitalize on brief and
minute differences in prices of stocks and stock-index futures by
buying or selling stocks with opposite trades in the futures.
</TEXT>
