<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Sweden-Volvo     12-12 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Volvo,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Largest Company Deal Ever in Sweden Announced</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Swedish government and Volvo
automotive company announced a $3.7 billion agreement Tuesday
giving Volvo a 40 percent stake in the government-controlled
holding group Procordia, in the largest deal of its kind the
country has seen.
   In return, Procordia acquired AB Volvo's food division,
Provendor, and the auto giant's share in Pharmacia AB, a
pharmaceutical company.
   Procordia's takeover of the two Volvo subsidiaries creates a new
group which will have 48,000 employees and a yearly turnover of
about 35 billion kronor, or about $5.4 billion.
   Trading in the shares of the three companies was halted Tuesday
morning on the Stockholm bourse. The details were announced at an
evening news conference by Industry Minister Ivar Nordberg and
Volvo's managing director Pehr Gyllenhammar.
   The scale of the 24 billion-kronor deal is unprecedented, and
compares with the entire Swedish defense budget of 30 billion
kronor.
   Analysts said the deal will probably have a positive effect on
Swedish industry and will lead to structural changes with more
competitive companies.
   Gyllenhammar will be chairman of Procordia, while its present
chief executive officer Soeren Gyll will be proposed as CEO of the
new group.
   The purchase will turn Procordia into one of Europe's 20 largest
pharmaceutical companies.
   Procordia already controlled a pharmaceutical company, Kabi,
which together with Pharmacia expects a turnover of nearly $2
billion next year.
   Procordia will also become market leader in several food areas
within Scandinavia.
   Its food sector, which includes Pripps Brewery, had a turnover
of 5 billion kronor last year, while Provendor registered a 10
billion-krona turnover.
   Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson's Social Democratic government
approved the deal late Tuesday, but it also needs approval by
parliament.
</TEXT>
