<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 2129EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-Maybelline     12-12 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Maybelline,0202</SECOND>
<HEAD>Schering-Plough Puts Maybelline up for Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maybelline, one of the top sellers of
cosmetics in the United States, has been put up for sale, parent
company Schering-Plough Corp. said Tuesday.
   The company said Maybelline was put on the block as part of a
strategy to concentrate on prescription and over-the-counter
pharmaceuticals, and personal care and vision care products.
   Maybelline, established in 1915 and named after the sister of
founder T.L. Williams, was obtained by Plough in 1967 before Plough
merged with Schering, said company spokesman Linn A. Weiss.
   ``The business is strong, it's viable, it's growing,'' Weiss
said. ``The decision results from an orderly review of our
strategies and long-term objectives.''
   Maybelline recorded 1988 sales of about $280 million, up 10
percent from the previous year.
   It is second behind Cover Girl in individual units of cosmetics
sold.
   Schering-Plough sold its two European cosmetics companies,
Rimmel International Ltd. and Chicogo GmbH, in July to Unilever, a
European manufacturer of consumer products and package goods.
   Weiss declined to comment on whether Maybelline had any
prospective buyers.
   Merrill Lynch Capital Markets is assisting in the sale.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
