<FIRST>r f AM-SovietVodka 1stLd-Writethru f0314 12-12 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Vodka, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0314,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Votes on Repeal of Ban on Sale of Soviet Vodka</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with repeal passed unanimously;
picks up 3rd graf pvs: `Michael Carls, ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warmed by the thaw in East-West
relations, the City Council on Tuesday unanimously voted to repeal
a local ban on Russian vodka imposed in 1983 after a Korean
passenger jet was shot down by the Soviets.
   Mayor Paul Ackland said the city would write a letter to the
Soviet Embassy to inform them of the action.
   ``We want them to know that we as a community support the
changes being made,'' Ackland said, ``and hope our relationship
will continue to improve.''
   He said the city would send a gift of goods made in Hutchinson
as a token of friendship.
   Michael Carls, the council member who introduced the ban six
years ago, said it was also his idea to lift it.
   ``It's not a stunt. We take it seriously,'' said Carls, who
teaches American government to high school students in the town of
10,000 about 45 miles west of Minneapolis.
   ``It was first outrage over their denial of life to those
passengers on the jet and today it's a feeling of pleasure over the
extent of democratization over there,'' he said.
   Carls said other U.S. cities with municipal control over liquor
sales banned Soviet vodka from store shelves after Korean Air Lines
Flight 007 was shot down off Sakhalin Island in September 1983. All
269 people, including 61 Americans, were killed.
   The jet was shot down on a flight from Anchorage to Seoul after
it strayed into Soviet airspace.
   Jeannette Matheny, a clerk at Hutchinson Municipal Liquor Store,
said the ban created some discussion in 1983. But since then, she
said, it's been forgotten.
   ``I don't even think most of the public was aware of the ban,''
Matheny said. ``I understand that we will restock the vodka, but it
won't be an extensive line. One or two brands at the most.''
   Carls said there were no plans for a ceremonial sip of the
libation at the city council meeting.
   ``It will be adopted without opposition and without much
discussion,'' he said. ``We just don't want the events in eastern
Europe to go by without expressing our pleasure at what's going
on.''
</TEXT>
