<DOCNO> AP891212-0264 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-89 2149EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CorporateEspionage     12-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Corporate Espionage,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Canadian Charged with Corporate Espionage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian employee of NCR Corp. was held
without bail Tuesday after he was charged with attempting to sell
proprietary information about NCR products to Unisys Corp.
   Anthony S. Latchoo, 28, of Rexdale, Ontario, was arrested Monday
by FBI agents after a two-month investigation as he left Unisys
headquarters in Blue Bell, Pa., FBI special agent Wayne R. Gilbert
said in a statement.
   Latchoo, a product manager for NCR's Waterloo, Ontario,
engineering and manufacturing division, allegedly approached a
Unisys employee in October and offered to sell him information
about NCR document imaging technology and marketing strategies,
Gilbert said.
   Imaging technology allows businesses to store, process, display
and retrieve electronic information on a computer. Gilbert said the
information, if stolen, could have cost NCR more than $100 million.
   Latchoo had allegedly sought ``substantial monetary
compensation,'' Gilbert said.
   The Unisys employee contacted by Latchoo informed superiors, who
in turn reported the incident to the U.S. Attorney's Office in
Philadelphia, according to Unisys spokeswoman Charlotte LeGates.
   She said she could not comment further on the arrest because
company officials did not want to hamper the FBI investigation.
   Latchoo met with the Unisys employee Monday and was arrested at
the end of the meeting, FBI spokesman John Kundts said.
   NCR spokesman Robert Farkas said the Canadian facility produces
document-processing equipment.
   Kundts said both Unisys and NCR, based in Dayton, Ohio,
cooperated in the investigation.
   Farkas said NCR learned of the attempted espionage from the FBI
on Dec. 7. A preliminary assessment indicated just one person was
involved and no information actually changed hands, he said.
   Latchoo has been charged with interstate transportation of
stolen property. If convicted, he faces up to 10 years in prison
and a $10,000 fine.
   Latchoo has been suspended by NCR pending a review of the
charges, according to Farkas.
</TEXT>
